<FIRST>r a PM-BoxOffice     02-22 0523</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Box Office,0543</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Rain Man' Enjoys Oscar Boost, but `The 'Burbs' No. 1 at Box Office</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Rain Man'' took off at the weekend box
office on the strength of its eight Oscar nominations, but the
film's performance still wasn't good enough to top the
record-setting opening of ``The 'burbs.''
   Despite generally negative reviews, ``The 'burbs,'' a new comedy
starring Tom Hanks as a suburban homeowner bedeviled by peculiar
neighbors, collected $11.1 million in its first four days of release
to land in first place.
   Universal Pictures said it was the best opening weekend ever for
a film released in the first quarter.
   ``Rain Man,'' a study of a contriving car salesman who tries to
understand his autistic savant brother, finished second. Boosted by
a leading eight Academy Award nominations last Wednesday, including
best picture and best actor for Dustin Hoffman, ``Rain Man'' grossed
$6.7 million.
   With the holiday weekend running a day longer than the previous
weekend, ``Rain Man's'' take was up a robust 47 percent.
   In third place was ``Bill and Ted's Excellent Adventure,'' a new
comedy about two teen-age time travelers, with receipts of $6.2
million. It was followed in fourth by ``Three Fugitives,'' featuring
Nick Nolte and Martin Short as crooks on the run, which collected
$4.6 million.
   In fifth place was the slimy sequel ``The Fly II,'' starring Eric
Stoltz as the son of a mutated scientist, on ticket sales of $4.3
million.``Beaches,'' a melodrama starring Bette Midler and Barbara
Hershey, grossed $3.7 million to finish in sixth place.
   Just behind it was ``Cousins,'' the English-language remake of
France's ``Cousin, Cousine,'' with a gate of $3.5 million.
   Rounding out the top 10 were the corporate success comedy
``Working Girl,'' in eighth with $2.72 million; ``Dangerous
Liaisons,'' the tale of power-hungry seducers in pre-revolutionary
France, in ninth with $2.717 million; and the new drama ``True
Believer,'' featuring James Woods as a crusading lawyer, in 10th
with $2.6 million.
   Here are the top movies for the weekend as tallied by Exhibitor
Relations Co., with distributor, weekend gross, number of theater
screens, average per screen, total gross and number of weeks in
release.
   1. ``The 'burbs,'' Universal, $11.1 million, 1,951 screens,
$5,690 per screen, $11.1 million, one week.
   2. ``Rain Man,'' United Artists, $6.7 million, 1,590 screens,
$4,163 per screen, $110.6 million, 10 weeks.
   3. ``Bill and Ted's Excellent Adventure,'' Orion, $6.2 million,
1,196 screens, $5,156 per screen, $6.2 million, one week.
   4. ``Three Fugitives,'' Disney, $4.6 million, 1,374 screens,
$3,340 per screen, $26.1 million, four weeks.
   5. ``The Fly II,'' 20th Century Fox, $4.3 million, 1,528 screens,
$2,829 per screen, $12.7 million, two weeks.
   6. ``Beaches,'' Disney, $3.7 million, 1.072 screens, $3,444 per
screen, $35.8 million, nine weeks.
   7. ``Cousins,'' Paramount, $3.5 million, 720 screens, $4,867 per
screen, $7.6 million, two weeks.
   8. ``Working Girl'' 20th Century Fox, $2.72 million, 825 screens,
$3,298 per screen, $48 million, nine weeks.
   9. ``Dangerous Liaisons,'' Warner Bros., $2.717 million, 354
screens, $7,677 per screen, $12.1 million, nine weeks.
   10. ``True Believer,'' Columbia, $2.6 million, 897 screens,
$2,894 per screen, $3 million, one week.
  
</TEXT>
