<FIRST>r a PM-People-Bridges     02-22 0251</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-People-Bridges,0258</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Diff'rent Strokes' Star Pleads Innocent to Armed Robbery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COMPTON, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Diff'rent Strokes'' star Todd Bridges,
already jailed on an attempted murder charge, pleaded innocent to
armed robbery in another case involving an alleged confrontation
with his car repairman.
   Bridges entered the plea Tuesday in Los Angeles County Municipal
Court and a preliminary hearing was scheduled for March 23. The
actor remained in jail without bail on an attempted murder charge
filed in another case.
   The latest charge stems from a Jan. 23 incident in which he
allegedly pulled a gun and took his BMW automobile from a repairman
without paying the nearly $500 repair charge.
   ``The person we believe to be Bridges took his car to the place
to be repaired and, instead of paying, took the car away at
gunpoint,'' said Deputy District Attorney Patti Ryan.
   Bridges, who played Willis Jackson on TV's ``Diff'rent Strokes,''
has pleaded innocent to charges he shot Kenneth Clay five times at
an inner-city drug den on Feb. 3. Clay survived and identified
Bridges as the attacker.
   The charges against the actor are the latest in a string of
brushes with the law.
   Last year, he pleaded no contest to a charge of making bomb
threats against an auto customizer he hired to work on his Porsche.
The actor was given a suspended sentence of one year in jail.
   In 1983, Bridges paid a $240 fine for carrying a concealed
firearm, and last year he was convicted of reckless driving.
</TEXT>
