<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--Germany-Extremists     02-22 0134</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Germany-Extremists,0136</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report that Right-wing Extremists Killed 25 Over 10 Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLOGNE, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Right-wing extremists killed 25
people in West Germany during the past 10 years and injured scores
of others, a government agency says in a new report.
   The Constitutional Protection Office, a division of the Interior
Ministry, says in the report released Tuesday that there are about
25,000 such extremists in the country, of which between 450 and 500
are violent extremists.
   The report says right-wing extremists committed more than 1,200
violent crimes from 1983 to 1987, including 29 terrorist acts. The
crimes included bombings, personal attacks and destruction of Jewish
landmarks and property.
   The Constitutional Protection Office said the worst right-wing
terrorist attack occurred in 1980 during Munich's Octoberfest
celebrations, when a bomb blast killed 13 people.
</TEXT>
