<FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-89 0046EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-AFL-CIOMeeting     02-22 0420</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AFL-CIO Meeting,0430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Labor Leaders High On Dole Despite Differences</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAL HARBOUR, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   AFL-CIO leaders offered praise for Labor
Secretary Elizabeth Dole after their first meeting despite
disagreements on proposals to raise the minimum wage and expand
child care and parental leave opportunities.
   ``I'm sure that there will be some areas where we disagree and
will pursue our best efforts in the Congress but I have a high
regard for the secretary of labor, for Secretary Dole,'' federation
president Lane Kirkland said Tuesday after the second day of the
AFL-CIO's annual meeting.
   For her part, Mrs. Dole emerged from the meeting with the labor
group's Executive Council with a promise that she would open her
door to organized labor _ something union leaders say was missing
during the Reagan administration.
   Nonetheless, there were several evident disagreements between the
positions of the administration and labor, particularly over whether
legislation to increase the minimum wage from $3.35 to $4.65 an hour
should contain a provision allowing for a lower training wage for
youths.
   Mrs. Dole said Bush's support hinged on inclusion of the training
wage, something labor leaders fervently oppose.
   The two sides agreed to work together on an issue Mrs. Dole
raised _ studying ways to establish ``portable'' pension systems so
workers who change jobs frequently because of the changing economy
can amass a retirement fund.
   Neither side offered specifics of how such a program would work,
but Kirkland thanked Mrs. Dole for raising the issue and said labor
would offer its ideas to her.
   Mrs. Dole also promised a thorough review of a proposal, released
by the department before she took office, to lift a nearly
50-year-old ban on industrial homework in the women's apparel
industry. But she said she was reluctant to even consider
re-establishing several similar bans in the garment industry that
were lifted during the Reagan years, a request the Executive Council
had made on Monday.
   Whether the cordial relationship between labor and the Bush
administration lasts could be determined in the next 10 days, when
Bush likely will decide whether to name an emergency board to
intervene in stalled negotiations between Eastern Airlines and 9,000
members of the International Association of Machinists.
   The machinists are scheduled to strike March 4 but the AFL-CIO
has asked Bush to intervene, a move that would automatically push
back the strike deadline 60 days.
   Mrs. Dole said Bush was awaiting advice from the Labor and
Transportation departments before making a decision.
</TEXT>
