<FIRST>u a AM-Navajos-MacDonald     02-22 0421</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Navajos-MacDonald,0432</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judicial Order From Relative Keeps Navajo Nation Under MacDonald</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WINDOW ROCK, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Navajo tribal judge Tuesday barred
the ruling council of the country's largest Indian nation from
ousting its chairman _ his brother-in-law _ who has been accused in
congressional testimony of corruption.
   The Tribal Council had tried to place Chairman Peter MacDonald
and his associate, Vice Chairman Johnny Thompson, on administrative
leave. As a result of the judge's action, Thompson apparently became
temporary chairman of the council's winter meeting, which had tried
to choose different leaders to preside over the battle over
MacDonald's fate.
   Tribal District Judge Harry Brown, MacDonald's brother-in-law,
issued the temporary restraining order, said Geoffrey Standing Bear,
MacDonald's attorney. Brown scheduled a hearing for Friday to
determine whether to permanently halt the council's decision to
place MacDonald and Thompson on paid leave, Standing Bear said.
   Brown found that the council failed to follow the correct
procedure for removing a chairman from office last Friday night,
when it voted 49-13 against MacDonald and Thompson, Standing Bear
said.
   ``The chairman is entitled to his constitutional rights,'' he
added.
   Standing Bear would not answer questions about why he went to a
judge in Kayenta, about 140 miles by indirect roads from the tribal
capital, when he could have sought the order in any district court.
   He acknowledged that MacDonald and Brown are married to sisters,
and said Brown expected to be overruled by another judge because of
the conflict.
   Council members nevertheless were advised by Navajo Attorney
General Michael Upshaw to ``obey the order of the court.'' Upshaw
refused to comment further, but said he would answer written
questions from the council on the legality of further procedures.
   After Brown's order was read, chairman-designate Marshall Plummer
stood up, Thompson sat down, and Plummer squatted at the right of
Thompson's chair.
   The subtle transfer of power was indicated by Thompson's
remaining seated, said councilman Leonard Haskie of Tohachi, N.M.
   ``Marshall Plummer stepped aside out of respect for the court and
only did that because of the court order,'' Haskie said. ``We plan
to consult with our attorneys on our next course of action, because
the Navajo Nation cannot continue at a standstill.''
   MacDonald was in Window Rock but did not attend the meeting, his
staff said.
   A U.S. Senate committee heard testimony earlier this month that
MacDonald took kickbacks and gifts, particularly in a deal in which
a Phoenix oilman made $7.2 million profit from the sale of the Big
Boquillas Ranch to the tribe.
</TEXT>
