<HEAD>Eds: ADDS Christensen; CORRECTS to she sted he in lead of the Burke
obit. A separate moved for AMs as a0632 on Burke. Burke also moved on the
sports wire.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Mildred Burke</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mildred Burke, a 20-year women's world
wrestling champion who attributed her success to her muscular build
and her alligator clutch hold, died Saturday. She was 73.
   Ms. Burke, who was 5-foot-2, 138 pounds in her wrestling prime,
had such a well-muscled build that the Police Department once
displayed her poster in its offices to shame its officers into
staying in shape.
   Ms. Burke, wrestling champion from 1936 to 1956, claimed to have
invented the alligator clutch, a pinning maneuver in which the
opponent is twisted into something resembling a pretzel.
   She was listed in ``Ripley's Believe It or Not'' for doing 100
body bridges _ arching the body face up _ on the desk of Ripley's
editor. In her later years she operated a wrestling school in Encino.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Doris deKeyserlingk</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WILLIAMSTOWN, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Doris deKeyserlingk, a native of
Russia who served as an interpreter at the Nuremberg war crime
trials and became the first woman granted tenure at Williams
College, died Tuesday at age 86.
   Mrs. deKeyserlingk, retired associate professor of Russian and
German, moved to the United States in 1937 to join her German
fiance, a lawyer, Baron Klaus deKeyserlingk, who had spoken out
against Hitler. She became a naturalized U.S. citizen in 1946.
   The deKeyserlingks returned to Germany in 1946 to participate in
the Nuremberg trials of Nazi war criminals, she as an interpreter.
   She was hired by Williams College in 1958 to head its newly
revived Russian studies program. Eight years later, she became the
first tenured woman faculty member since the college's founding in
1793.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Harold Christensen</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN ANSELMO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Harold Christensen, director of the
San Francisco Ballet school for 33 years, died Monday. He was 84.
   Christensen studied dance with his uncle, Peter, in Salt Lake
City. He later studied with George Balanchine at the School of
American Ballet in New York.
   Christensen and his brothers, Willam and Lew, received the Dance
Magazine Award in 1973 and the Capezio Annual Dance Award in 1984.
</TEXT>
