<FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-89 0140EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a BC-QuakeConcert     02-22 0325</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Quake Concert,0335</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet, American Musicians Perform for Earthquake Relief</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: No PMs Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Placido Domingo joined other classical performers
in a concert at Carnegie Hall on Tuesday to benefit the
Soviet-Armenian Earthquake Relief Fund of the American Red Cross,
and organizers said $350,000 was raised.
   The superstar tenor kept busy through the evening, singing,
playing piano, introducing the other artists and conducting the
audience for the ensemble sections of the finale, the drinking song
from ``La Traviata.''
   ``It's probably the first concert ever organized in 10 days. It's
probably the last,'' said James D. Wolfensohn, chairman of the
Carnegie Hall board, as he announced that the event had raised
$350,000. ``There are no parties; there is no dinner. All the money
goes to Armenia.''
   Soprano Aprile Millo got the evening's standing ovation, after
singing Dvorak's ``Ode to the Moon'' from ``Rusalka.'' Mezzo-soprano
Elena Obraztsova, who flew from Moscow just for the concert, was
called back for an encore and won the audience's hearts with a soft
Russian song.
   Domingo played piano and sang while Mstislav Rostropovich played
cello in Massenet's ``Elegy.'' Domingo also sang an ``Otello'' love
duet with newcomer soprano Kallen Esperian.
   Paata Burchuladze, who has the true Russian bass sound, sang from
``The Barber of Seville'' and Mussorgsky's amusing ``The Flea.''
Samuel Ramey showed that an American bass can be great, too, with an
aria from Verdi's ``Attila'' and Kern's ``Old Man River.'' American
mezzo, Frederica von Stade, also sang.
   The evening included instrumentalists, highlighted by
Rostropovich's exquisitely played ``Sonata in G minor for Cello and
Piano'' by Rachmaninoff. Pianists were Alexander Toradze and
Vladimir Viardo. Violinist Vadim Repin, 17, flew from Moscow to play
Wienlawski's ``Fantaisie Brilliante,'' a piece which exhibited his
virtuosity.
   Loris Tjeknavorian conducted an ensemble from the American
Symphony in his own ``Armenian Elegy.'' Accompanying pianists were
Eugene Kohn, Mason G. Senft, Samuel Sanders and Irina Vinogradova.
</TEXT>
