<FIRST>r a PM-Names     02-22 0891</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Names,0925</SECOND>
<HEAD>Names in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOYS TOWN, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Don't tell Willard Scott there isn't an
Oscar category for television weathermen.
   After Scott gave his ``Today'' show forecast from Boys Town's
Hall of History Tuesday, the Rev. Val Peter jokingly presented him
with the Academy Award given to Spencer Tracy for his role as Father
Flanagan in the 1938 movie ``Boys Town.''
   ``Here's the Academy Award right here,'' said Peter, Boys Town's
executive director. ``I'd like to present this to you this morning
for this magnificent performance.''
   Boys Town Mayor Corey Randle gave Scott a giant cookie and a
plaque making him an honorary resident. Scott surprised Randle by
giving him a kiss.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fred Rogers says he's baffled by the slick look
and frantic pace of many shows outside his television
``neighborhood.''
   ``All I know is that I'm offering myself as I am and as I do.
What I'm creaing is not something false to me,'' the host of ``Mr.
Rogers' Neighborhood'' said in an interview in the March issue of
Parents magazine. ``And there must be those who feel that their
truth is in this kind of mayhem.''
   Rogers says honesty is what he aims to give the children who
watch his program.
   ``That's what I long for them to have _ as many honest adults in
their lives as possible,'' he said.
   ``What I believe, and hope comes through on the program, is that
each person is unique, that each person is valuable, and that each
of us longs to be loved.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Carly Simon says her stage fright makes the
prospect of appearing at the Academy Award ceremonies scary, so
she's figured out a better way to claim her Oscar if she wins the
award for best song.
   ``I intend to have a look-alike,'' Simon said Tuesday on ABC's
``Good Morning America'' program. ``If they think it's the real me,
that's even better. Only my hairdresser will know for sure.''
   Simon has been nominated for the song ``Let the River Run,'' from
the film ``Working Girl.''
   The singer-songwriter said she didn't know who would perform the
song at the award ceremonies March 29. ``I haven't been approached
about that,'' she said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DEVILLE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Col. Fred Gregory says he found it easier to
navigate the heavens aboard the space shuttle than to make a 20-mile
drive to a rural school in central Louisiana.
   ``Buckeye is just not on anybody's map,'' Gregory said,
apologizing for arriving at the town from Alexandria 53 minutes
late. ``I went around the Earth every 90 minutes. I was driving
longer than that today.''
   Gregory, 48, who piloted the space shuttle Challenger on a 1985
mission and is scheduled to command a classified shuttle flight in
August, spoke Monday at Buckeye Elementary School, one of several
schools in the state he is visiting.
   The 10-year astronaut said he was looking forward to his next
flight.
   ``It's a DOD (Department of Defense) mission so I can't tell you
anything about it, but we're going to have a great time,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Eds: A version is moving on sports wires.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former San Diego Chargers running back Chuck
Muncie was sentenced to 2{ years in federal prison for perjury and
dealing cocaine after a judge ignored pleas for leniency from
Muncie's ex-coach, Don Coryell.
   ``The only way you're going to get the message in this case is if
you go to jail,'' U.S. District Judge J. Lawrence Irving told Muncie
on Tuesday.
   Defense attorney Cindy Aaron submitted eight letters, including
one from Coryell, the former Chargers coach, supporting a request
that Muncie be released to undergo drug rehabilitation.
   ``I'm more than willing to get my life back in order,'' said
Muncie, 35.
   Irving gave Muncie 18 months in prison for his Dec. 12 guilty
plea to dealing 2 ounces of cocaine to an undercover federal agent.
The judge added another year for perjury for Muncie's claiming under
oath Jan. 5 that he hadn't used cocaine since 1985. He tested
positive for the drug afterward.
   Irving told Muncie he had lied to federal probation officers, his
attorney and to the court. That ``simply can't be tolerated,'' the
judge said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A ballerina flings her arms heavenward and a
somewhat less graceful Mayor Edward I. Koch pumps his fists into the
air in a new poster series promoting the pleasures of New York.
   Koch joined Culture Commissioner Mary Campbell Tuesday in
presenting the citywide campaign, ``New York and the Arts: A
Cultural Affair.''
   ``Much of New York's cultural life remains invisible,'' said
Campbell. ``Our young people are assaulted every day with what's
wrong with this city ... we have to spread the good news.''
   ``New York is Dance,'' ``New York is Heritage,'' ``New York is
Children,'' the various posters announce. The other subjects are
theatre, music, art, museums and gardens and zoos.
   Fifteen thousand posters will line the walls of subways, bus
stations, airports and other gateways to the ``cultural capital of
the world.''
   The 30-by-46-inch posters, financed by Philip Morris Companies
Inc., are part of a campaign that includes advertising in print,
radio and television, and recruiting multilingual students to guide
the city's annual 17 million visitors. The $500,000 campaign is
privately financed.
