<FIRST>u i AM-Salvador-Talks 4thLd-Writethru a0407 02-22 0885</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador-Talks, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0407,0909</SECOND>
<HEAD>Salvadoran Rebels Offer To Lay Down Arms If Military Cuts Made</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with party leaders to urge Duarte
to meet with rebels on the offer. Picks up 7th pvs, `Reports from ...'
^By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OAXTEPEC, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   El Salvador's leftist rebels offered
Tuesday to lay down their weapons if the military is sharply cut,
the police force reorganized and next month's presidential elections
postponed by at least four months.
   The rebels proposed the compromise during a meeting with
representatives with Salvadoran political parties, who said they
would see President Jose Napoleon Duarte on Wednesday and asked him
to meet with rebels on the offer.
   It was the first time the rebels had offered to lay down their
arms. Last month, they offered for the first time to participate in
national elections.
   Delegates of the 13 political parties issued a declaration
Tuesday night saying they were committed to consider the offer of
the rebel Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front ``and to offer
our contribution in whatever is necessary to the peace process as
long as the government ... accepts the possibility of realizing the
contents of the proposal.''
   The parties had met for two days to discuss how to end a
nine-year civil war that has claimed 70,000 lives.
   The front's offer attempted to address a major stumbling block in
the talks _ the constitutional requirement that Duarte leave office
by June 1 _ by proposing an interim president.
   There was no immediate response from the government.
   The rebel proposal appears aimed at neutralizing El Salvador's
rightist-dominated military, which has warned publicly it might
seize power in a coup if Duarte does not step down as scheduled.
   ``I would say in general that the government has to talk now that
they cannnot refuse or evade direct talks with the FMLN,'' said
Ruben Zamora of the the leftist Democratic Convergence, a coalition
of six small parties.
   The offer was made as guerrillas in El Salvador attacked the
country's principal army base and an engineering detachment, leaving
eight dead and 17 injured.
   Reports from San Salvador said the rightist Republican
Nationalist Alliance, or Arena, was standing firm against postponing
the March 19 vote, which it is favored to win, but deputy chairman
Jose Francisco Merino Lopez said the party would not tip its hand.
   The Arena and guerrilla representatives met for talks Tuesday
morning but both groups refused to disclose details.
   At an afternoon news conference, one Arena delegate, Jose
Francisco Guerrero, called the guerrilla attitude ``sincere'' but
would not say whether the party favored or rejected postponement of
the election.
   ``Peace is very distant but the distance is not so great,'' said
Guerrero. ``With the cooperation of the FMLN and ours we can achieve
peace in the short term.''
   Guillermo Ungo, presidential candidate of the Democratic
Convergence, told reporters here the new guerrilla proposal was ``a
very important change that would give us a better chance for peace.''
   But Ungo said he did not see any possibility of achieving
concrete results. The rebels themselves appeared pessimistic about
the prospects of their offer.
   ``For reactionaries such as Arena it would seem that the meeting
with the FMLN is more an opportunity for dilatory maneuvers than the
mature response that the people demand for a viable means of
pointing the country toward peace,'' they said in a Tuesday
broadcast on the clandestine Radio Venceremos.
   ``Rejection of the proposal will mean the war will not only
continue, but will escalate,'' the radio said.
   Essentially, the guerrilla front reduced its original request for
a postponement by two months. In January, the front asked for a
six-month postponement after a cease-fire goes into force.
   The FMLN broadened the scope of the talks here with its call for
a cease-fire, for cutting the armed forces from its current strength
of about 56,000 to its 1978 level of 12,000, and for a merging of
three police forces into a single force.
   The proposal also called for members of death squads be brought
to justice. Many slayings have been attributed to death squads
allegedly linked to Arena, a charge Arena denies.
   Both sides at the talks here have acknowledged that even if they
reach an accord, they would still confront the problem of pursuading
the military and the government to go along.
   A text of the proposal, distributed here and in San Salvador,
called for the establishment of three multiparty commissions to
negotiate an end to the fighting, rewrite the country's election
laws and setting up international verification of the entire peace
process.
   The front proposed a March 19 deadline for the commissions to end
their work. It suggested the national legislature choose an
independent provisional president to rule the country after June 1,
when the constitution says Duarte must leave office.
   ``As one way around the constitutional issue on elections, the
FMLN proposes the Legislative Assembly name an independent as
provisional president with the agreement of the political parties
and the explicit stipulation that his term runs until the
elections,'' the guerrilla proposal said.
   The other major party represented at this mountain resort about
40 miles southeast of Mexico City are the incumbent Christian
Democrats, running second in polls. The Democratic Convergence is
running a weak third.
</TEXT>
