<FIRST>r a PM-ChildAbuser     02-22 0240</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Child Abuser,0247</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Convicted of Child Abuse for `Experiments'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note contents</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 57-year-old man who admitted setting up bogus
federal programs to entice young children to participate in
so-called scientific experiments was convicted of 12 counts of
sexually abusing children.
   An Allegheny County jury deliberated 5{ hours Tuesday before
deciding Eugene Allen of suburban Wilkinsburg was guilty of all
charges, including sexual abuse of children, indecent assault and
corrupting the morals of a minor.
   Allen, a traveling salesman who dropped out of high school,
photographed two children, aged 8 and 9, while catheterizing them
and using a self-invented device called a kidney machine on them.
   He claimed his research and experiments with the device, which he
had advertised as federally sponsored, were legitimate efforts to
detect kidney failure in children.
   Dr. Norman T. Welford, former deputy director for the U.S. Food
and Drug Administration, testified the machine, which was heated up
when in use, would have ``cooked'' the children if it had operated
as Allen intended.
   Allen's experiments on the children were filmed in his basement
and at a cottage in rural Cochranton.
   Testifying in his own defense Tuesday, Allen said he videotaped
and photographed hundreds of encounters with children and stored the
tapes under floorboards in his house ``for my own sexual pleasure.''
   He said he thought about seeking medical help, but ``was too
embarrassed.''
   Allen faces 55 to 111 years in jail.
</TEXT>
