<FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-89 0228EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-EducationSpending     02-22 0454</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Education Spending,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Education Secretary Sheds no Light on Department Budget</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Budget</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Education Secretary Lauro Cavazos told a House
panel he knew neither his exact budget nor how he would pay for
President Bush's $441 million in new education programs, prompting
one lawmaker to complain of deception by the White House.
   Initially, education officials said the $441 million for Bush's
new programs would come on top of former President Reagan's proposed
$21.9 billion education budget for fiscal 1990. But Cavazos backed
off that Tuesday during an appearance before the House
Appropriations subcommittee on labor, health and human resources and
education.
   ``The only thing that we have today that is solid is the $21.9
billion,'' Cavazos told subcommittee chairman William Natcher, D-Ky.
Cavazos added there would be ``no set number'' until after
negotiations with Congress were completed.
   The administration testimony prompted Rep. David Obey, D-Wis., to
complain:
   ``All the critical decisions have been postponed to a later date
in order to pretend that a process is moving forward when in fact it
is not. There is a very important deception going on here.''
   Democrats are becoming increasingly irritated over Bush's failure
to specify spending cuts to comply with deficit reduction
requirements. Instead Bush sent Congress a series of initiatives,
including the 10 education programs costing $441 million, and said
cuts would be negotiated later with Congress.
   Bush, in presenting a $1.16 trillion budget, has said cuts must
come from a pool of discretionary programs worth $136 billion in the
current budget. By freezing that figure for 1990, budget makers will
have to trim $10 billion to $11 billion in what would have been
normal growth in the programs.
   Many of them are educational programs.
   ``I can understand why you might be chafing a little bit about
the numbers,'' deputy education undersecretary Charles Kolb told
members of the panel. ``But ambiguity is inherent in this process.''
   ``I think the president has made it absolutely clear as to where
his priorities lie in terms of education,'' Kolb said.
   ``Well, he may have made it clear to you, but let me tell you
something, I have no idea where this money is supposed to come
from,'' Obey interrupted.
   ``It is certainly legitimate to question whether ... those are in
fact real initiatives or public relations initiatives which might
become real at a later date only if other spending cuts can be found
in your department,'' Obey said.
   Reagan recommended that 24 programs be eliminated and the
resulting $750 million in savings be shifted to several large
programs serving the disadvantaged. Cavazos embraced that plan as
well as Bush's new programs, most of them stemming from campaign
promises.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
