<FIRST>r w PM-US-SatanicVerses     02-22 0453</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Satanic Verses,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baker Defends US Bookstores that Yank `Satanic Verses'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III is
defending U.S. booksellers that have pulled ``The Satanic Verses''
from their shelves, saying they may have ``well-founded fears'' in
the face of Iranian death threats.
   Baker said Tuesday that the United States has a responsibility to
speak out against Iran's threats, but he refused to criticize the
U.S. corporations and bookstores that now refuse to sell the book.
   The book is viewed by many Moslems as blasphemous. While author
Salman Rushdie has said he did not intend to insult fellow Moslems,
Iranian leader Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini has refused to accept the
apology and has ordered the writer killed.
   Baker's restrained comments contrasted with the heated
denunciations of terrorism issued repeatedly by former Secretary of
State George Shultz.
   Baker discussed the book controversy during testimony before the
House Foreign Affairs Committee. Several congressmen were far more
critical of the U.S. booksellers that have pulled the book in
response to the Iranian threats.
   Rep. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J., said that while the bookstore
companies may have ``legitimate concerns,'' he argued that they are
setting a dangerous precedent.
   ``American publishers and book distributors are at this moment on
the front lines of defending our fundamental freedoms to speak and
to publish. It appears to me that they have done a grave national
disservice,'' Torricelli said.
   Rep. Tom Lantos, D-Calif., asserted that ``spineless American
bookchains'' are ``trembling before these terrorist threats of the
Ayatollah.''
   Some of the nation's largest chains, such as B. Dalton and Barnes
&amp; Noble, took ``The Satanic Verses'' off the shelves, but they
refuse to say whether they will continue to sell the book.
WaldenBooks has removed the book from shelves, but will continue to
sell it upon request.
   ``I'm not sure it's our job to sit here in judgment on those
people,'' ``We have spoken out. We will continue to do so. We will
continue to work quietly with our allies with respect to issues of
terrorism, and state-sponsored terrorism like this,'' Baker told the
committee.
   ``I do think it's incumbent upon us as a government to continue
to pursue a policy that rules out concessions to terrorists. But it
seems to me that concessions to terrorists may be different than
well-founded fears on the part of private citizens about their own
welfare and safety.''
   President Bush said Tuesday that such bookstore owners should be
given ``the protection of the law.''
   Bush condemned Iran's death decree against the British novelist
as ``deeply offensive to the norm of civilized behavior'' and warned
that Tehran would be held accountable for any actions against
American interests.

</TEXT>
</DOC>
