<FIRST>r p PM-GOP-Duke     02-22 0577</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-GOP-Duke,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>National GOP Ready to Censure Duke</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   National Republican officials are prepared to
denounce Klansman-turned-Republican state lawmaker David Duke with a
resolution likely to be approved by the party's executive committee
on Friday.
   At the direction of party chairman Lee Atwater and the apparent
concurrence of President Bush, a resolution was drawn up Tuesday
declaring that while Duke may be a registered Republican ``he is not
a Republican in gesture, deed or belief.''
   In Louisiana, where Duke won election to the state legislature,
the Republican reception was more accommodating.
   ``I don't understand what Lee Atwater is talking about,'' said
GOP state Rep. Art Sour. ``Censure him for what? The only control we
have over him is what he's done since he's been a Republican.''
   ``We will see if Mr. Duke is what he says he is or what the media
says he is,'' added state Rep. Peppi Bruneau, GOP caucus chairman.
``If he's what he says he is, he has no problem. He got to the House
the same way everybody else did.''
   The Louisiana legislature is convening for a special session, and
there is a challenge to seating Duke. But members of both parties
predicted that the move would fail and that he would become one of
18 Republicans in the 105-member chamber.
   At the national party headquarters, an anti-Duke resolution
already was ready for adoption by the party's executive council on
Friday.
   The resolution declared that ``the Republican National Committee
and the Republican Party reject and condemn David Duke, his beliefs
and the hate and fear he promotes.''
   In addition, the resolution declares that ``Duke will not be
considered a member of the Republican Party and will not receive any
aid or assistance of any kind whatsoever from the Republican
National Committee. Duke may be a Republican in party registration
but he is not a Republican in gesture, deed or belief.''
   Citing Duke's former roles as grand dragon of the Ku Klux Klan
and founder of the National Association for the Advancement of White
People, the resolution said, ``Duke and these groups preach
doctrines of racial, religious and ethnic hatred, bigotry and
discrimination against American citizens which are abhorrent to the
American tradition and have no place in the Republican Party.''
   Duke, 38, defeated home builder John Treen, 63, in Saturday's
election for a seat in the Louisiana House despite endorsements for
Treen by Bush, former President Reagan and the most powerful
political figures in the suburban New Orleans area. Both candidates
were registered Republicans.
   Duke has scoffed at threats to deny him national Republican Party
money, saying he never received any during his successful
legislative campaign. He also has said he is ``as much a
Republican'' as anyone.
   At a news conference Tuesday, Bush conceded his endorsement of
Duke's opponent might have been viewed by Louisiana voters as
``improper or overkill.''
   But, the president said, ``I did what I did because of
principle.'' He said Duke's record ``is one of racism and bigotry.''
   Atwater, who last week severely criticized Duke, said Tuesday
that he now wants to avoid getting into a public debate with the
former Klan leader.
   ``It plays right into his hands. What he wants is to get into a
prolonged argument with me on television, any other kind of media.
   ``He's a very effective demagogue and I'm not going to give him
an opportunity to do that any more.''
</TEXT>
