<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     02-22 0613</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>LILCO, NRC Staff Argue For Governments' Dismissal from Shoreham Proceedings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCKVILLE, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Suffolk County, New York state and the Town
of Southampton withheld information from the Nuclear Regulatory
Commission and should be dismissed from licensing proceedings for
the Shoreham power plant, say lawyers for the Long Island Lighting
Co.
   ``The issue before this commission ultimately is who is in charge
here,'' said Donald P. Irwin, a lawyer for LILCO, which owns
Shoreham.
   Irwin argued Tuesday that the state and local governments
deliberately defied the licensing board in an attempt to keep the
Shoreham case in a legal morass that has lasted for 3{ years.
   But a lawyer for Suffolk, Herbert Brown, said the county did not
show ``bad faith'' when officials refused to speculate before a
licensing panel what they would do in the event of an accident at
the Shoreham plant.
   Because the county has no evacuation plan, they could not say
what they would do, he reasoned.
   The NRC is considering whether to dismiss the state and local
governments from the Shoreham licensing proceedings. NRC spokesman
Frank Ingram said he did not know when a decision might come.
   If the state and local governments are dismissed, theoretically
no objections would remain to licensing Shoreham.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>Panel Told Nation Should Use Natural Gas, Develop Safe Nuclear</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Power
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation should react to the greenhouse
effect on global warming by using natural gas instead of coal and by
developing ``safe and publicly acceptable'' nuclear power, a House
panel was told.
   Robert M. White, president of the National Academy of
Engineering, said Tuesday these are among measures needed to prevent
further build-up of greenhouse gases that could be responsible for
global warming.
   White and three other witnesses cautioned that scientists still
do not know whether burning of fossil fuels and other human
activities will cause significant temperature changes, leading to
heat waves and drought.
   One witness, University of Virginia professor Patrick J.
Michaels, told a House Energy and Commerce subcommittee it would be
more prudent to await more study before making drastic policy
decisions.
   ``Our policy should be commensurate with the state of our
scientific knowledge,'' the professor of environmental sciences told
the energy and power subcommittee.
   Michaels said climate experts have a ``clouded vision'' of future
global warming, and added, ``basing sweeping environmental policy''
on such uncertainties ``is especially risky, even if the policy is
otherwise rational.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>GAO Says Agency Officials Ordered Changes in Report on Spotted Owl</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A congressional report says Fish and Wildlife
Service officials ordered a changes in a report in an effort to keep
the spotted owl off the endangered list.
   The General Accounting Office, an arm of Congress, said officials
ignored scientific evidence and ordered revisions in a study
prepared by biologists in the agency's Northwest regional office.
Scientists had concluded that unless logging was slowed in ancient
forests of the Northwest, the owl could face extinction.
   The timber industry in the Northwest has opposed any effort to
name the owl a threatened or endangered species, fearing that such a
move would disrupt logging in public forests. Environmentalists have
advocated protecting the owl as part of their campaign to halt
logging of old growth forests.
   ``While changes are an inevitable part of any draft report review
process, the nature of the changes made in this case and the way
they were made raise questions about whether objectivity was
maintained,'' the GAO said.
   The Fish and Wildlife Service, an Interior Department agency
which determines what should be designated for protection as
threatened or endangered, is required to consider only ``biological
factors'' in making its decision.
</TEXT>
