<DOCNO> AP890222-0038 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-89 0158EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Solidarity'sQuarters Bjt   02-22 0634</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Solidarity's Quarters, Bjt,0654</SECOND>
<HEAD>Without An Office, The Opposition Gets A Hotel Room</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bulgarian businessmen checking into the
Europejski hotel shook their heads in disbelief when they saw the
red-and-white lettered sign saying: ``Solidarity Press Office, Hotel
Club, 1st floor.''
   A bellhop, sensing the concern of his guests over the prospect of
ordering a drink in a room occupied by Poland's leading opposition
group, guided the Bulgarian guests to a bar in the other direction.
   Upstairs in the club, normally ``reserved for hotel guests
only,'' the bartender also appeared a bit confused by the news
conferences the free trade union movement holds after its nearly
daily talks with authorities on restoring Solidarity's legal status
and ending Poland's acute economic crisis.
   ``It's really interesting to listen, but it's bad for business.
These journalists have to work and they don't drink,'' said
Kazimierz Krajewski.
   Solidarity has had no offices in Warsaw since it was crushed in a
December 1981 military crackdown and subsequently outlawed.
   So it had to ask the government to find a place for it to hold
news conferences during the so-called round-table talks that began
Feb. 6.
   Authorities first offered Solidarity offices at nearby Warsaw
University, but the rooms were too small and there were not enough
telephones.
   Finally, the government-backed Patriotic Movement for National
Rebirth, a national unity organization, rented rooms for the
opposition in the Europejski.
   ``It's a great improvisation,'' said Kazimierz Woycicki,
organizer of the press office.
   Dozens of union activists have pitched in to run the press
service, compiling news bulletins and monitoring official coverage
of the talks.
   Every afternoon, Solidarity press aides redecorate the
rose-colored room. A Solidarity banner is hung on the wall and piles
of still-banned underground newspapers are placed on a coffee table.
   The underground press, which has thrived despite Communist
authorities' attempts to quash it, and since the round-table talks
began its press corps has turned out in force for the flurry of
Solidarity and official news conferences.
   The addition of these ``alternative'' journalists and questions
from curious Solidarity activists who clog the room often cause the
news conferences to drag on for as long as two hours, sending some
Western journalists to the bar or back to their offices.
   ``From time to time it's difficult for us ... some Solidarity
activists don't always know what a press conference is and they try
to start a discussion rather than asking pointed questions,'' said
Woycicki, himself a journalist for a church-affiliated monthly.
   Solidarity has opened its conferences to the state-controlled
media and is keeping careful tabs on the way the round-table talks
are being covered.
   Every morning at 9 a.m., Woycicki, Solidarity national spokesman
Janusz Onyszkiewicz and several other Solidarity spokesmen analyze
official newspapers and watch televison news reports on videotape.
   They are especially interested in how other Communist countries
are covering the round table.
   ``The journalists from Tass (the official Soviet news agency)
showed a big interest in our job. We have quite free relations with
them,'' Woycicki said.
   For the underground press, reporting on the round-table talks has
offered them freedom unknown since Solidarity had its own press
during its 16-month legal existence.
   ``I can imagine a better situation with typewriters and
telephones, but I am not going to grumble,'' said Krzystof Leski, a
journalist of the underground weekly Tygodnik Mazowsze, who is
trying to coordinate coverage of news conferences by the opposition
press.
   Government news conferences at the official Interpress Club just
across Victory Square offer simultaneous translation for foreign
journalists and better working conditions.
   But attendance there has been lower and the proceedings seem dull
in comparison to the bustle at the Europejski _ where only the
barkeeper seems anxious for it all to end.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
