<FIRST>r w PM-DuelingDiapers     02-22 0482</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dueling Diapers,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Diaper Services Make Environmental Appeal for the Reusable Kind</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Diaper services are hoping that a newfound
concern with the environment might help the cloth variety stage a
comeback against disposables.
   Perhaps no other product has had such an impact on child rearing
as the plastic and cellulose disposable diaper. But critics say the
disposable diaper, which does not decay when buried, has been adding
to the country's garbage problems since their use became widespread
in the 1970s.
   An estimated 18 billion such diapers are used _ and disposed of _
each year, according to a new study that was commissioned by the
trade group for diaper service companies. The disposable diapers
accounted for an estimated 3.6 million tons of waste last year,
about 2 percent of all waste buried in landfills, said the report by
Carl Lehrburger, an expert in waste management.
   Lehrburger was planning to discuss the results today at a news
conference.
   Although Lehrburger insists that the National Association of
Diaper Services had no editorial control over the study, he
nevertheless recommends as an immediate step that parents be
encouraged to shift to cloth diapers. Beyond that, he suggests that
governments consider a tax on disposable diapers and at the same
time provide tax incentives for the diaper service industry to
encourage such a switch.
   In the coming months the cloth diaper advocates plan to press the
environmental concerns as they lobby environmental groups as well as
state and local officials, said John Shiffert, executive director of
the association, in a telephone interview Tuesday from its
Philadelphia headquarters.
   While at least 21 states have debated legislation in recent years
limiting or banning plastic packaging waste, only in two states _
Oregon and Washington _ have the debates focused specifically on
disposable diapers, acknowledges Lehrburger. In both states the
legislation affecting diapers failed.
   Disposable diaper manufacturers have in the past disputed the
claim that soiled diapers pose a health hazard and have suggested
the impact of disposable diapers on the landfill problem is being
exaggerated.
   Officials of both Procter &amp; Gamble and Kimberly-Clark, which
together account for 80 percent of the disposable diaper sales,
could not be reached Tuesday.
   Lehrburger, in his report, estimates that about 2 percent of the
wastes put into landfills comes from disposable diapers. And as
states and local governments impose recycling requirements on other
garbage such as bottles and paper, these diapers will account for an
even higher percentage of the total wastes buried.
   ``As a society we have been sold on the idea of `disposability'
without full recognition of the costs associated with this
convenience,'' writes Lehrburger,
   The report, he continues, hopefully will be ``the beginning
point'' for a public policy debate over the benefits and drawbacks
of what many parents of young children have come to consider an
indispensable product.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890222-0040 </DOCNO>
