<SECOND>PM-US-Paraguay,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Paraguayan Leader Vows to Fight Drug Trafficking, Congressman
Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first U.S. lawmaker to visit Paraguay since
the coup earlier this month says the South American nation's new
leader is vowing to rid the country of its reputation as a haven for
``thieves and scoundrels.''
   Rep. Bruce A. Morrison, D-Conn., said Tuesday that he met for an
hour last week with Gen. Andres Rodriguez, who ousted President
Alfredo Stroessner in a coup Feb. 3.
   ``In our conversation, the provisional president was very
specific,'' Morrison said. ``He even assured me that he is willing
to receive requests from those who hunt war criminals, because he
wants to end Paraguay's historic reputation as a haven for ex-Nazis,
drug dealers and Third World dictators.''
   The congressman said Rodriguez also promised to help fight drug
trafficking. Paraguay is known as a key money-laundering center for
cocaine profits.
   But Morrison, who later in the day briefed State Department
officials on his visit, said the Bush administration should ``base
its policies toward Paraguay on future actions'' not promises.
   Also on Tuesday, the political council of the Organization of
American States adopted a resolution that the Rodriguez government
``guarantee a process of democratization with true participation of
all the political parties in clean and impeccable elections.''
   A special envoy of the new Paraguayan government accepted the
unanimous resolution.
   The council acted after a Paraguayan opposition leader, Domingo
Laino, suggested that holding elections too early would ensure
return to power of Stroessner's Colorado Party. Laino noted that the
OAS human rights commission has declared that Paraguay's political
structure is seriously tilted toward the Colorado.
   Laino said the Christian Democratic Party and his own Liberal
Party are illegal and the current law forbids the establishment of
alliances or electoral fronts.
