<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     02-22 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0301</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nikkei Closes At Record High, Dollar Off 0.53 Yen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices rose to close Wednesday at another
record high on the Tokyo Stock Exchange, while the U.S. dollar edged
lower against the Japanese yen.
   The dollar ended trading at 126.62 yen, down 0.53 yen from
Tuesday's 127.15-yen finish. The currency opened at 126.75 yen and
traded between 126.50 yen and 126.80 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which shed
197.00 points Tuesday, recouped 331.85 points, or 1.04 percent,
closing at 32,311.93, a new record high.
   The index's rebound came on the heels of testimony Tuesday by
U.S. Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan Greenspan, in which he told
the Senate Banking Committee in Washington of the need for a tighter
U.S. economy to fight inflation.
   Nobuto Nakahari, a trader with Nomura Securities in Tokyo, said
the Tokyo market was doing well in spite of such discouraging
factors as a three-day weekend starting Friday, the day of the
funeral for the late Emperor Hirohito, and a widening
stock-profiteering scandal.
   Eight people, including former government officials and business
leaders, have been arrested on bribery or securities law violation
charges in connection with the stock transactions.
   Executives of the Recruit Co., an information-employment
conglomerate, allegedly sought to buy influence by offering more
than 1.5 million unlisted shares to at least 150 politicians, public
officials and business leaders. Most of them later sold the stocks
for sizable profits.
   In currency dealings, the dollar lost ground as Japanese
investors started selling it after Greenspan's congressional
testimony, in which he gave little indication of a hike in the U.S.
discount rate.
   Trading was light in the absence of major market-affecting news,
said one dealer with a Japanese commercial bank in Tokyo.
</TEXT>
