<FIRST>r a PM-AmocoCadiz     02-22 0588</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Amoco Cadiz,0606</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Recommends $115 Million For 1978 France Oil Spill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Both sides claimed victory but promised appeals
after a judge recommended a $115.2 million judgment against Amoco
Corp. for the massive oil-spill damage from the 1978 wreck of a
supertanker off France.
   Tuesday's decision by retired U.S. District Judge Frank McGarr
was the latest round in a legal battle pitting the government of
France and about 90 other plaintiffs against Chicago-based Amoco.
   ``While we're gratified for some of the plaintiffs, this is still
only a small portion of the actual damages,'' said attorney Barry
Kingham, who represented the towns, associations of oystermen and
fishermen, hoteliers and the two French counties most affected by
the spill from the Amoco Cadiz.
   ``The judge is looking at the cleanup costs, but he has
consistently failed to recognize the harm goes beyond that,''
Kingham added. ``That will be the basis of our appeal.''
   Amoco attorney Frank Cicero said the recommendation by McGarr
``vindicates Amoco's position from the outset _ the damage claims
have been exaggerated.''
   ``Now we'd like to get the judgment in place, then go ahead and
appeal,'' he said.
   But a final judgment may still be far in the future.
   McGarr, who retired from the federal bench after the original
ruling but continues to serve as ``special master'' in the case,
scheduled a March 14 hearing on yet another possible revision.
   When it is completed, McGarr will forward a finished draft of his
recommendation to U.S. District Judge Charles Norgle, who will enter
a final judgment.
   In January 1988, McGarr recommended $85.2 million in damages
against Amoco. After appeals from plaintiffs, he increased the
amount by $30 million Tuesday.
   The largest recommended increase went to the government of
France, which is now in line for an award of $44.4 million, compared
with $31.9 million in the original ruling 13 months ago.
   At the lower end of the revisions were some 100 French towns,
whose commerce and well-being were affected by the spill that
created an oil slick 18 miles wide and 80 miles long, killing
thousands of birds and millions of sea creatures and washing waves
of thick black tar along 100 miles of coast.
   The towns had received $7.3 million in the original judgment and
sought an additional $8 million, but received only an additional
$200,000.
   Interest will be added to each award.
   The cash figures in the original award, as well as Tuesday's
recommendation, were in French francs. Attorneys for both sides said
the combined awards now total about $115 million _ $61 million in
actual damages and $54 million to $60 million in interest.
   In previous rulings, McGarr assessed liability to both Amoco and
Astilleros Espanoles S.A., the Spanish firm that built the Amoco
Cadiz and defaulted by refusing to recognize the district court's
jurisdiction.
   Amoco is continuing with litigation to recover the entire cost of
the judgment from Astilleros, said company attorney Cicero.
   ``Anywhere we can find assets, we can sue to collect those assets
for the judgment,'' he said.
   Amoco's shares rose 37.5 cents Tuesday on the New York Stock
Exchange to close at $77.125.
   The Amoco Cadiz ran aground two miles off the Brittany coast
March 16, 1978. The huge tanker, which had lost the use of its
rudder, had been under tow through the English Channel by a
German-owned tug when the towlines snapped in hurricane-force winds
and heavy seas and the ship became impaled along the rocks off
northwest France.
</TEXT>
