<FIRST>r i PM-Philippines     02-22 0497</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Philippines,0512</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coup Figure Says Post-Marcos Elections Planned, Not Aquino Presidency</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT H. REID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The military officers whose mutiny
helped propel Corazon Aquino to power initially planned to set up a
provisional government and hold new elections to replace Ferdinand
Marcos as president, a key conspirator said today.
   But Navy Capt. Rex Robles said then-Defense Minister Juan Ponce
Enrile, leader of the mutineers, decided Mrs. Aquino should instead
be sworn in as president to prevent Marcos from a making legal claim
to the office.
   Robles made the remarks during an interview on radio station DZRH
on the third anniversary of the mutiny, which triggered the popular
uprising that drove Marcos from power on Feb. 25, 1986.
   U.S. officials first refused to support the mutineers and did so
only after it became clear that Marcos was finished, Robles said.
   He said the Reform the Armed Forces Movement had planned to
launch a coup against Marcos in December 1985 but postponed the move
after he called a ``snap election'' for Feb. 7, 1986.
   ``So we decided to postpone until sometime after elections,
around April or May in the summer,'' Robles said. But the
conspirators advanced their plans after public outrage over massive
cheating in the election, in which both Marcos and Mrs. Aquino
claimed victory.
   ``If we succeeded in ousting Marcos or asking him to step down,
our plan was we would set up a transition council, either five to
seven members,'' Robles said. ``Our agreement was whoever joined the
transition council would not run in the election which we would hold
because it would be unfair.''
   When it appeared the mutiny would succeed, Robles said civilian
and military opponents met to discuss how to establish the legal
authority of a post-Marcos government.
   According to Robles, Enrile told the gathering: ``It is necessary
to swear Mrs. Aquino into office right now.'' Several politicians
were shocked by the suggestion.
   But Robles said Enrile argued that by swearing in Mrs. Aquino
first, Marcos ``would have to play catch-up'' and would lack legal
authority.
   ``It was Sen. Enrile's idea,'' Robles said. ``They were not
prepared (to accept) that concept that you must beat Marcos to the
presidency.''
   The National Assembly certified Marcos as the election winner
several days before the mutiny, but he had not taken his oath.
   Marcos took his oath on Feb. 25, 1986 soon after Mrs. Aquino was
sworn in. He fled Manila hours later aboard a U.S. helicopter and
departed before dawn the next day for exile in Hawaii.
   Movement members frequently have complained that they were never
given credit for their role in ousting Marcos. The reform movement
included former Lt. Col. Gregorio ``Gringo'' Honasan, sought in the
violent August 1987 attempt to topple Mrs. Aquino.
   Enrile was fired as defense minister on Nov. 23, 1986, after an
alleged coup plot by his followers. He was elected as the only
opposition member of the Senate in May 1987.
</TEXT>
