<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     02-22 0303</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0312</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tokyo Stocks Surge To Record High, Dollar Off 0.53 Yen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange's leading index rebounded
sharply today, closing at another record high, while the U.S. dollar
fell against the Japanese yen.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, a 197.00-point loser Tuesday,
shot up 331.85 points, or 1.04 percent, today and closed at
32,311.93. The gain was the largest this year.
   Strong buying interest among both individual and institutional
investors, largely due to stability in the currency market and in
interest rates, contributed to the rise, said a dealer with Daiwa
Securities in Tokyo.
   In heavy trading, with first section volume estimated at 1.4
billion shares, steel, construction and auto shares were among
gainers.
   In currency dealings, the dollar closed at 126.62 yen, down 0.53
yen from Tuesday's close of 127.15 yen. The currency opened at
126.75 yen and ranged between 126.50 yen and 126.80 yen.
   The dollar's weakness in Tokyo followed comments Tuesday by U.S.
Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan Greenspan in congressional
testimony, dealers said.
   Greenspan told the Senate Banking Committee that the United
States would keep its current monetary policy unchanged as it sought
to head off inflation. He was to testify again today.
   Some market players had expected him to suggest higher interest
rates, said a dealer with a major commercial bank in Tokyo, speaking
on condition of anonymity.
   Such expectations helped push the dollar up by 1.40 yen on
Tuesday. Higher U.S. interest rates make dollar-denominated
investments more attractive to foreigners.
   Meanwhile, Bank of Japan Governor Satoshi Sumita told a news
conference today that he sees the dollar remaining steady against
the yen and that he expects no major changes in Japanese or U.S.
economic policies.
   ``Foreign exchange rates (for the dollar) probably won't move
far, either up or down,'' he said.
