<FIRST>r a PM-People-Frelich     02-22 0270</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-People-Frelich,0279</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hearing-Impaired Actress Protests `The Equalizer' Casting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tony Award-winning actress Phyllis Frelich is
leading a coalition of deaf and hearing-impaired groups in
condemning use of a non-handicapped woman on CBS-TV's ``The
Equalizer.''
   Miss Frelich, who is hearing-impaired, complained Tuesday that a
hearing actress, Cynthia Nixon, portrays a deaf woman in a March 8
episode titled ``Silent Fury.''
   ``They say they could not find a hearing-impaired actress capable
of carrying the role,'' Miss Frelich said. ``We know better.
   ``Would anybody even consider hiring a white actress to paint her
face black and pretend to be black? Of course not. Then why do they
do the same thing to us? Why must we be subjected to this insulting
and demeaning discrimination,'' she said.
   The actress, who won a Tony in ``Children of a Lesser God'' on
Broadway, has launched a month-long letter-writing campaign
targeting CBS President Kim LeMasters and ``The Equalizer'' producer
James McAdams to prevent the episode from being aired.
   McAdams, the series executive producer, said the producers hired
a hearing-impaired man to play Miss Nixon's hearing-impaired fiance
and they auditioned several deaf actresses in the New York area but
could not find someone ``who was right for the role.''
   Howie Seago has the leading guest role of the boyfriend and there
are several deaf actors in supporting roles, McAdams said.
   ``We did earnestly look for a hearing-impaired person,'' McAdams
said. ``If we didn't consider any deaf actresses, if we slammed the
door in their face, then they'd have a point.''
   He said Frelich's protest could discourage other producers from
making programs about handicapped people.
</TEXT>
