<FIRST>r i PM-China-Bush     02-22 0265</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Bush,0275</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Invites Leading Chinese Dissident to Dinner</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China's best-known dissident, Fang Lizhi, said
today that he has been invited to attend a banquet hosted by
President Bush for Chinese senior state leaders.
   Fang, known for his sharp criticisms of Marxism and his call for
more democracy in China, said in a telephone interview that he plans
to attend the Sunday night dinner at a Beijing hotel.
   He said that if he has a chance to talk to Bush he will bring up
the issue of human rights, including the imprisonment of political
activists in China.
   Bush arrives in Beijing Saturday for a two-day visit following
his attendance of the funeral of Emperor Hirohito in Tokyo.
   The U.S. president is to dine at the Great Hall of the People
with President Yang Shangkun on Saturday night. The following day,
the American side is to host a return banquet for Yang and other
Chinese leaders.
   Premier Li Peng is also expected to attend that dinner.
   U.S. Embassy officials declined to provide other names on the
guest list, said to number about 500.
   Fang, also known for his work as an astrophysicist, gained
international prominence in early 1987 when he was fired from his
job and expelled from the Communist Party after being accused of
fomenting nationwide student demonstrations for democracy.
   He has since been the Chinese government's most outspoken critic,
decrying human rights abuses and demanding a faster pace of
democratic reform.
   Last month, Fang wrote an open letter to senior leader Deng
Xiaoping calling for an amnesty for political prisoners.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
