<FIRST>u i PM-SovietPolitics     02-22 0470</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet Politics,0491</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Moscow Party Chief Boris Yeltsin Wins Place On National Ballot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boris Yeltsin, the ousted Moscow Communist Party
chief and outspoken critic of party conservatives, won a spot today
on the ballot to represent the capital in the new national
legislature, Radio Moscow said.
   Yeltsin, who lost the party job in November 1987 after
complaining about the slow pace of reform, received 532 votes at an
electoral committee meeting that ended before dawn at the ornate
House of Unions in downtown Moscow.
   Yevgeny Brakov, director of the giant ZIL automotive plant,
received 570 votes and will compete with Yeltsin for one spot in the
March 26 elections.
   Both were chosen by committee members from a field of 10
potential candidates to represent Moscow.
   The committee made its decision after the two candidates
presented campaign platforms in the chandelier-lit red-and-white
Hall of Columns.
   Yeltsin, 57, and Brakov ``both support restructuring and
democratization, but propose different solutions to specific
problems,'' the radio said.
   Under an law approved in December, two-third of the seats in the
new 2,250-member Congress of People's Deputies will be filled by
candidates nominated in the workplace and chosen by voters on a
territorial basis.
   The rest of the deputies are to be chosen by party, union,
professional and other officially recognized groups.
   The new congress will meet annually and choose the Soviet
president and members of a new, smaller and more active sitting
parliament.
   Yeltsin told the committee members before they approved his
candidacy that he staunchly supports President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev's policies, both at home and abroad.
   ``From the viewpoint of the strategy of external politics, I
fully support him,'' he said in a seven-minute speech interrupted
six times by applause. ``From the viewpoint of the strategy of
internal politics, fully.''
   But, he said, ``from the viewpoint of tactics, I have my own
opinion.''
   Brakov, 51, presented a mainstream program, also supporting
Gorbachev's reforms and focusing on the need for better supplies of
food and consumer goods, a line more likely to be acceptable to
Communist Party officials.
   He was nominated by 33 workers' groups compared to 19 for Yeltsin.
   Because election law permits candidates to be nominated in more
than one geographical area early in the campaign, Yeltsin also has
been nominated in Sverdlovsk, where he could stand a better chance
of election.
   Until he was removed as a non-voting member of the ruling
Communist Party Politburo a year ago, Yeltsin was one of the
strongest backers of Gorbachev's policies of perestroika and
glasnost, or openness.
   At the time, Gorbachev accused him of being overly ambitious and
blaming others for his mistakes.
   Hospitalized with heart trouble after he was sacked as the Moscow
party chief, Yeltsin said at the meeting that he was ``physically
healthy and ready to fight.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
