<FIRST>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     02-22 0313</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0329</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Steady In Quiet European Trading, Gold Rises</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was steady in quiet European trading
late this morning. Gold prices rose strongly.
   Foreign exchange traders said they expected the dollar to remain
stable in lackluster trading over the next few days as the market
tried to sort out the implications of U.S. Federal Reserve Chairman
Alan Greenspan's Congressional testimony.
   Greenspan was scheduled for a second day of testimony today, but
traders said they didn't expect it to give them a new lead.
   ``What he had to say, he has said,'' one Rome trader said.
   The dollar gained potential support from Greenspan's indication
that because of inflationary pressures he wouldn't lower interest
rates any time soon. But at the same time, he predicted only modest
growth for the U.S. economy, indicating little fear the economy is
overheating.
   In London, the dollar rose against the British pound, which fell
to $1.7455 from $1.7565 Tuesday.
   Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Tuesday:
   _1.8406 West German marks, down from 1.8420
   _1.5695 Swiss francs, up from 1.5685
   _6.2725 French francs, down from 6.2735
   _2.0767 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0910
   _1,351.50 Italian lire, down from 1,356.00
   _1.1965 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1897
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 0.53 yen to a closing 126.62 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted at 126.85 yen.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $385.40 a troy ounce, up
from $380.75 bid late Tuesday. At midmorning today, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $386.00.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $385.90, up from $383.00 bid late
Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $3.17 to close at a bid $387.51.
   Silver was quoted in London today at a bid price of $5.94 a troy
ounce, up from Tuesday's $5.93.
</TEXT>
