<FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     02-22 0530</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0546</SECOND>
<HEAD>Showers, Warm Temperatures Along East Coast; Arctic Air Hits Midwest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Showers and thunderstorms dampened the Atlantic Coast from
Florida to New Jersey early today and another wave of cold arctic
air began pouring into the Midwest.
   The thunderstorms and heaviest rain were concentrated over
Florida, where several cities recorded over half an inch of rain
Tuesday evening and early today.
   Mild weather accompanied the coastal rain, with early morning
temperatures in the 50s as far north as Boston.
   Nine Southeast cities tied or set new high temperature records
Tuesday. They included Norfolk, Va., where the temperature hit 76,
one degree above the old mark, just three days after the city was
buried by nearly a foot of snow.
   Cooler air prevailed west of the Appalachians. Arctic air flowed
into the northern Plains and upper Mississippi Valley from Canada,
generating some snow along Lake Superior in Upper Michigan. A snow
and blowing snow advisory was in effect for the area with up to 6
inches expected.
   A mixture of freezing drizzle, sleet and snow glazed parts of
northeast Ohio Tuesday evening.
   Drier weather should bring some relief to flood-stricken
Kentucky, although there was a chance for some light drizzle or snow
flurries today.
   Clear skies prevailed over the Great Plains and much of the
southwest, and rain was reported over western portions of Washington
and Oregon.
   Today's forecast called for rain along much of the Atlantic
Coast, with thunderstorms in Florida, and rain in the Pacific
Northwest and northern California. Scattered snow was expected in
the eastern Great Lakes region, the central and northern
Appalachians and northern New England. Some snow also was expected
in Upper Michigan.
   Highs were forecast to be in the single digits and teens from the
northern Plains through the upper Mississippi Valley to the upper
Great Lakes; the 20s and 30s in Montana, the middle and lower
Missouri Valley, the middle Mississippi Valley, the Tennessee and
Ohio valleys and the lower Great Lakes area; the 60s from central
California to the Rio Grande Valley of Texas, and across northern
Florida and southeast Georgia; and the 70s and 80s in Southern
California, the Desert Southwest and southern Florida.
   Highs elsewhere were expected to be in the 40s and 50s.
   Temperatures at 2 a.m. EST ranged from 10 degrees below zero at
Warroad, Minn., to 77 degrees at Miami and Key West, Fla.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 47 cloudy; Boston 52 partly cloudy; Buffalo 31
snow; Charleston, S.C. 59 rain; Cincinnati 30 snow; Cleveland 31
cloudy; Detroit 26 cloudy; Miami 76 partly cloudy; New York 47 rain;
Philadelphia 49 rain; Pittsburgh 35 drizzle; Portland, Maine 43
foggy; Washington 47 rain.
   _Central: Bismarck 11 snow; Chicago 20 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth 41
fair; Denver 29 partly cloudy; Des Moines 8 fair; Indianapolis 28
snow; Kansas City 18 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 6 fair; Nashville 36
foggy; New Orleans 49 cloudy; St. Louis 28 windy.
   _West: Albuquerque 37 fair; Anchorage 29 cloudy; Las Vegas 48
fair; Los Angeles 60 fair; Phoenix 59 fair; Salt Lake City 26 fair;
San Diego 59 fair; San Francisco 56 partly cloudy; Seattle 46 rain.
