<FIRST>u i PM-Mideast-Soviets     02-22 0656</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mideast-Soviets,0679</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet, Israeli Ministers Fail To Bridge Differences</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CAI5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DALIA BALIGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The foreign ministers of the Soviet Union and
Israel met today for 2{ hours but failed to bridge differences on
how to peacefully resolve the Middle East crisis.
   Eduard Shevardnadze and his Israeli counterpart, Moshe Arens, met
at the Soviet Embassy overlooking the Nile River and agreed to
discuss their differences further at a later date. They didn't say
where or when.
   Shevardnadze, on a 10-day Middle East tour, told reporters
Tuesday he would try to persuade Israel to enter negotiations with
the Palestine Liberation Organization, which the Jewish state
considers a terrorist group.
   The Soviet Union severed ties with Israel after the 1967
Arab-Israeli war and has been a major Arab supporter. Tentative
Soviet-Israeli contacts began only recently, and both ministers
appeared to regret the long break in communication.
   ``The worst thing is not to have a dialogue,'' Shevardnadze said.
Arens referred to the ``long dry spell, 20 years, of not talking
together.''
   ``Our conclusion is that we want to meet some more,'' Arens said.
``We have to extend contacts. We have to find ways to present our
views. I think we are creating a basis for understanding, possibly
for agreement.''
   Today's talks with Arens, however, brought no breakthrough for
Shevardnadze to convey to PLO chairman Yasser Arafat at a meeting
scheduled this evening.
   ``We cannot say that we have come to a solution on all aspects,
but that was not our expectation. To expect that would be naive,''
Shevardnadze said after the meeting.
   ``Fundamentally, we agreed to continue contacts at foreign
ministers' level and other levels,'' Shevardnadze added. ``There are
differences between us, different views, and we will continue
discussions.''
   Arens said Israel and the Soviet Union ``are in a process of
building a foundation of understanding.''
   He repeated Israel's position on the need for direct talks with
Arab partners on peace.
   ``Israel made peace, salaam, with Egypt,'' Arens said. ``If the
rest of the Arab world followed Egypt's example and made direct
contacts, we will have peace.'' Egypt and Israel signed a peace
treaty in 1979, the only one between an Arab country and the Jewish
state.
   The Soviet minister noted Israeli's importance in bringing peace
to the region.
   ``The state of Israel is a most important factor in the
settlement. Without good will from Israel, there can be no solution
for the problem. Another aspect is that without the Soviet Union,
also no peace,'' Shevardnadze said.
   He said that Soviet-Israeli experts would meet in a few days to
discuss the issues in depth.
   Neither minister referred to speculation the Cairo meeting could
set the stage for restoration of relations between the Soviet Union
and Israel.
   Yasser Abed-Rabbo, head of the PLO's information department and a
member of the organization's 15-man Executive Committee, said the
Soviets should not renew relations unless Israel accepts an
international conference.
   Like the Arabs, the Soviet Union wants an international peace
conference sponsored by the United Nations, which would be attended
by the PLO and other regional parties as well as the five permanent
members of the Security Council.
   Israel opposes this, fearing such a conference would be
prejudiced against it, but Israel has said it would accept a
conference under the aegis of the Soviet Union and the United States.
   Shevardnadze said that even had he agreed with Arens on an
international peace conference, that would not mean the conference
would be held immediately.
   He said the Soviet Union is discussing the Middle East with the
United States and that the subject will figure in his scheduled
March 6 meeting with U.S. Secretary of State James Baker III.
   ``I am a natural optimist. This is the only way,'' Shevardnadze
said. ``The conflict has to be resolved.''
   Arens flew home early this afternoon. Arafat arrived about half
an hour later to meet with the Soviet minister.
</TEXT>
