<FIRST>u a PM-Nielsens     02-22 0385</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nielsens,0393</SECOND>
<HEAD>Burt's Back for ABC; NBC Leads Networks in Ratings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Burt Reynolds returned to the small screen last
week, and television viewers were apparently mighty pleased.
   His two-hour movie ``B.L. Stryker,'' part of ABC's rotating
``Mystery Movie,'' ranked 13th in the weekly A.C. Nielsen ratings.
That's better than the other two movies in the series _ Peter Falk's
``Columbo,'' which had stiff competition from CBS' ``Lonesome
Dove,'' and ``Gideon Oliver,'' which premiered Monday night.
   Last week was uneventful, despite being part of the February
sweep _ one of four months a year when local stations' ratings are
measured and networks pile on the specials to help affiliates. There
wasn't a movie or miniseries in the top 10, and NBC's series won the
week.
   Without big events, viewing numbers were back down slightly below
normal. The three networks had a combined audience share _
percentage of sets in use _ of 67. The season average has been 68.
Three-network shares had soared into the 80s earlier this month for
``Lonesome Dove.''
   Next to ``B.L. Stryker,'' NBC had the highest-rated movie of the
week, ``Swimsuit,'' at 20th. The first part of ABC's ``Passion and
Paradise'' two-parter did not inspire passionate ratings. It ranked
51st.
   NBC made it 35 in a row after winning the week ending Feb. 19
with an average, prime-time Nielsen rating of 16.2. CBS had a 13.1
and ABC 12.2. Each rating point represents 904,000 households with
televisions.
   The top-rated shows of the week were: ``The Cosby Show,'' NBC,
with a rating of 26.2 and a 41 share; ``A Different World,'' NBC;
``60 Minutes,'' CBS; ``Golden Girls,'' NBC; ``Cheers,'' NBC;
``Murder, She Wrote,'' CBS; ``Roseanne,'' ABC; ``L.A. Law,'' NBC;
``Empty Nest,'' NBC; and ``Hunter,'' NBC, tied with ``Who's the
Boss?'' ABC.
   The lowest-rated were: ``A Man Called Hawk,'' ``Tour of Duty,''
``Dolphin Cove,'' ``West 57th,'' ``Almost Grown,'' ``Smothers
Brothers,'' ``Pete's Dragon,'' ``Murphy's Law,'' ``HeartBeat'' and
``A Fine Romance.''
   The ``CBS Evening News'' continued to win in the news race. Last
week's numbers couldn't have been much closer, though, with
four-tenths of a rating point separating the three broadcasts. CBS
had an 11.5 and 20 share; ``ABC World News Tonight'' had an 11.3 and
20; ``NBC Nightly News'' had an 11.1. and 20.

</TEXT>
