<FIRST>r a PM-Fernald-EPA     02-22 0221</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fernald-EPA,0228</SECOND>
<HEAD>EPA To Stay Away From Government's Fernald Plant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Environmental Protection Agency workers
will not return to the Fernald uranium processing plant because of
the risk of exposure to radioactivity, despite new assurances from
the operator, a spokeswoman said.
   The operator of the plant, which processes uranium for nuclear
weapons, says that the Feed Materials Production Center is safe and
that the urine sampling analyses it uses to test people for
radiation exposure are reliable.
   In addition, the tests have been vindicated by outside
laboratories, Westinghouse Materials Co. of Ohio announced Tuesday.
   The EPA made the decision last week after two of its inspectors,
including Catherine McCord, chief EPA inspector at the plant, were
contaminated with uranium in December while attending meetings at
the facility, which is 18 miles northwest of Cincinnati. The plant
is owned by the federal Energy Department.
   Anne Rowan, a spokeswoman in the EPA's Chicago regional office,
said the EPA had not seen Westinghouse's announcement about the
vindicated tests and was unfamiliar with it.
   ``We have not changed our position,'' Ms. Rowan said.
   She said the EPA is investigating its own testing methods, which
showed that its inspectors were exposed to uranium.
   The Ohio Environmental Protection Agency also is keeping
inspectors away from the plant until the exposure problems are
corrected.
</TEXT>
