<FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-89 1020EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Nicaragua     02-22 0434</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nicaragua,0448</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sandinistas Kick Off Celebration Of Revolution</HEAD>
<HEAD>By DORALISA PILARTE</HEAD>
<HEAD>Associated Press Writer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel Ortega kicked off the
10-year anniversary of the uprising that brought his leftist
Sandinistas to power by saying the nation must not let its guard
down against U.S.-backed rebels.
   ``Reagan left; the revolution stayed,'' Ortega told 35,000 people
at a rally in Managua on Tuesday evening.
   Ortega was to meet today with opposition leaders to discuss
electoral reforms. He said the talks will center on the accord he
and the presidents of El Salvador, Honduras, Costa Rica and
Guatemala signed Feb. 14 in El Salvador.
   He said the National Assembly on Feb. 28 will discuss freeing
more than 1,700 former soldiers who served under ousted President
Anastasio Somoza. He said 2,000 jailed rebels, known as Contras,
will be freed ``in the same measure that the Contra force is
dismantled.''
   ``As long as the Contras are there, the United States is there,
threatening,'' Ortega said. ``We cannot yet let our guard down.''
   Traditional cumbia music was played and uniformed civilians waved
flags and pictures of the man who gave their Sandinista movement its
name.
   The rally and a march began celebrations leading up to July 19,
the date marking 10 years since the Sandinistas entered the capital
after they toppled Somoza. The festivities also commemorated the
55th anniversary of the death of Augusto Cesar Sandino, a
nationalist general who was shot by U.S.-backed National Guard
troops on Feb. 21, 1934.
   One-third of the people at the rally Tuesday evening were dressed
in green military uniforms, including reservists, young men and
women in the mandatory military service, and regular army personnel.
   In a speech earlier Tuesday opening the National Assembly's fifth
session, Ortega said any electoral reform drawn up during talks with
the opposition ``will have to be debated, approved or disapproved at
this site.''
   During their meeting in El Salvador, the five Central American
presidents agreed that Nicaragua will institute democratic reforms,
such as giving equal air time to opposition parties, amnesty for
some political prisoners and including opposition representation in
the Supreme Electoral Council.
   Ortega also promised to move up elections to February 1990, 10
months earlier than scheduled.
   The presidents also agreed to draft a plan within 90 days to
dismantle the Nicaraguan rebel force now living in Honduran
territory.
   Through most of Reagan administration, the United States gave
arms to the Contras. In February 1988, Congress stopped military aid
and continued only humanitarian assistance to the Contras, 10,000 of
whom now live in camps in neighboring Honduras with about 10,000
relatives.
</TEXT>
