<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--FunnyMoney     02-22 0178</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Funny Money,0182</SECOND>
<HEAD>$310,000 in `Benjies From Heaven' Rain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>IRVINE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Traffic jams flourished this week as
motorists jumped from their cars to scoop up thousands of $100 bills
apparently tossed from a car. But there was a catch: The money was
funny.
   In fact, the pale lime-green bills didn't look much better than
photocopies, but that didn't stop motorists Monday and Tuesday, as
they screeched to the side of roads and jumped out to get rich quick.
   ``It was a zoo. People were really frothing at the mouth,'' said
police Sgt. Ron Flathers. ``Since Benjamin Franklin's picture is on
the $100 (bill), we say it was raining Benjies from heaven.''
   The first cash storm was reported at 9 p.m. Monday when $50,000
to $100,000 was found along four miles of a parkway. A short time
later, about $10,000 in bills were reported fluttering along the
Costa Mesa Freeway.
   Then on Tuesday morning, $200,000 more littered the San Diego
Freeway in San Clemente.
   Secret Service agents are trying to learn the source of the money.
</TEXT>
