<FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-89 1038EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Czechoslovakia 1stLd-Writethru   02-22 0586</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Czechoslovakia, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0528,0602</SECOND>
<HEAD>Czech Human Rights Spokesman Arrested</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to ADD details on meeting between activists. No
pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist authorities today
arrested a spokesman from the Charter 77 human rights group, a
dissident said, one day after a co-founder of the group was
sentenced to nine months in jail.
   Tomas Hradilek was detained in his hometown of Lipnik nad Becvou,
200 miles east of Prague, and charged with inciting rebellion and
damaging Czechoslovakia's image, said dissident Anna Sabatova.
   There was no official confirmation, but authorities in this
communist country do not routinely report arrests. If convicted,
Hradilek could be imprisoned up to five years, Ms. Sabatova said.
   The charges are based on two letters he wrote last month to
Communist Party chief Milos Jakes and to President Gustav Husak
protesting the violence police used to break up peaceful gatherings
in Prague.
   ``This is glasnost in Czechoslovakia,'' said fellow Charter 77
activist Vaclav Maly, referring to the greater openness Soviet
President Mikhail Gorbachev has advocated but which has failed to
take hold in Czechoslovakia.
   Maly said today's detention means all three spokesmen for the
movement are in police custody. Charter 77 _ the Soviet bloc's
oldest, unofficial human rights organization _ was formed in January
1977. It was named for the document issued by founding members
calling on Czech to respect civil liberties.
   Maly and Sabatova spoke to Western reporters outside the trial of
fellow Charter spokesman Alexander Vondra and six other dissidents
charged with hooliganism for trying to lay flowers in memory of
student Jan Palach on Jan. 16 at Prague's Wenceslas Square.
   Palach burned himself to death Jan. 16, 1969 to protest the 1968
Soviet-led invasion of his homeland that crushed a reform movement.
   Vaclav Havel, a prominent playwright and a Charter 77 founder,
was sentenced Tuesday to nine months in jail after he was convicted
of inciting people to attend the Jan. 16 memorial service, which
authorities contend was a demonstration.
   Later Tuesday, six members of an official human rights committee
held a first meeting with Western human rights campaigners and
members of the Charter 77 movement, state media and dissidents said
today.
   Representatives of Helsinki monitoring committees in four West
European countries and the United States attended the meeting, the
Communist Party daily Rude Pravo said in a brief report that did not
mention the Chartists' attendance.
   Maly, who also attended, said the discussion focused on changes
needed in Czechoslovak laws, in particular new rules that double to
a year the maximum jail penalty for violating public order laws.
   This week's detentions signal a crackdown by the communist rulers
on Charter 77 movement and leaders of other emerging independent
groups.
   The trial of the seven opened Tuesday and resumed today with
defendants repeatedly challenging police testimony.
   An eighth defendant, Charter 77 spokeswoman Dana Nemcova, is in a
hospital and will be tried separately.
   Judge Antonin Tesik, who four times has ordered the defense to
``shut up,'' denied a defense attorney's request to instruct
witnesses on perjury after one policeman testified that when the
dissidents were arrested ``the crowd applauded and called us (the
police) heroes.''
   Most Czechoslovaks were dismayed by the police action against
peaceful demonstrators.
   The defendants said they planned no demonstrations and intended
to leave the square after laying flowers.
   Information about the proceedings came from a Reuters
correspondent and a correspondent for Voice of America radio
station, who were the only foreign journalists allowed to attend.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
