<DOCNO> AP890222-0087 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-89 1044EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-WindowWashers     02-22 0304</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Window Washers,0313</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dade Metro Commission Passes Ordinance Against Window Washers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials hope the prospect of fines and jail will
wipe out the practice of washing car windshields and then begging
motorists for payment.
   Under a Dade County ordinance approved Tuesday by the Metro-Dade
Commission, people arrested for windshield washing along roadways
could face a $500 fine and up to 60 days in jail beginning next week.
   The ordinance is particularly aimed at Miami, where, as in other
cities, homeless people wash windshields of cars stopped at traffic
lights to earn spare change. Miami did not specifically outlaw the
practice, but police have arrested washers occasionally on charges
of impeding traffic.
   In August, the fatal shooting of a windshield washer by a Miami
police officer rekindled demands to rid the streets of the washers.
   A Dade Circuit Court judge will hear evidence today to determine
whether the officer acted properly. The officer claims he shot the
washer in self-defense when he lunged at him with a knife.
   ``Motorists in Dade are afraid of these men,'' said Metro-Dade
Commissioner Jorge Valdes, who sponsored the ordinance after he said
his wife was frightened when a washer approached their car.
   ``I think it's very important that we work for the public safety
of the citizens, no matter what the consequences,'' Valdes said.
   Commissioners Barbara Carey and Charles Dusseau voted against the
restriction. Both wanted the washers gone, but thought the penalties
too harsh.
   County Manager Joaquin Avino said it's unlikely that violators
would spend much time in jail.
   ``Cells are already too crowded with more serious criminals. ...
What you basically have is a revolving door,'' Avino said. ``They
would be booked and released on their own recognizance.''
   ``I think the ordinance will give enforcement more teeth,'' Miami
police spokesman Ray Lang said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
