<DOCNO> AP890222-0088 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-89 1045EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-PoliticalParties     02-22 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Political Parties,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court, in California Case, Says Party Leaders May Make Endorsements</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   States may not prohibit political party leaders
from endorsing primary election candidates, the Supreme Court ruled
today.
   The justices, by an 8-0 vote, struck down such a California law
as an impermissible infringement of constitutionally protected
freedom of speech.
   The court also struck down as unconstitutional California laws
limiting the term of office for party leaders and dictating the
make-up of state party central committees.
   A federal appeals court had thrown out key California election
laws, and today's decision upheld that ruling.
   ``The challenged California election laws burden the First
Amendment rights (of freedom of speech and freedom of association)
of political parties and their members without serving a compelling
state interest,'' Justice Thurgood Marshall wrote for the court.
   In overturning the ban on primary election endorsements, Marshall
said that attempts to preserve party unity and protect voters from
confusion and undue influence cannot justify such a prohibition.
   He said the state also failed to prove that its regulation of
political parties' leadership structure was necessary to ensure
orderly and fair elections.
   Justice John Paul Stevens did not join Marshall's opinion but, in
a separate concurring opinion, also voted to strike down the
California laws. Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist did not
participate in the case for unannounced reasons.
   California revamped its election laws around the turn of the
century to break the grip on political parties by wealthy special
interests, particularly the Southern Pacific Railroad Co.
   But the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, in its ruling last
year, said such laws as the ban on primary election endorsements now
have the effect of undermining the parties' main goals.
   Agreeing with the appeals court today, Marshall said, ``Depriving
a political party to endorse suffocates'' its freedom of speech and
association.
   He added: ``The endorsement ban prevents parties from promoting
candidates at the crucial juncture at which the appeal to common
principles may be translated into concerted action, and hence to
political power in the community.''
   The case is Eu vs. San Francisco County Democratic Central
Committee, 87-1269.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
