<FIRST>u i PM-Egypt-Israel     02-22 0387</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Egypt-Israel,0398</SECOND>
<HEAD>Egypt, Israel Near Agreement On Taba</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Mideast-Soviets</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAURICE GUINDI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Strained Egyptian-Israeli relations showed
strong signs of improvement today when the countries agreed on
compensation in a border dispute and Egypt's foreign minister
accepted an invitation to visit Israel.
   The thaw coincided with the approach of the 10th anniversary of
the neighbors' peace treaty, the first and only one between an Arab
nation and the Jewish state.
   Visiting Israeli Foreign Minister Moshe Arens spoke of increased
confidence and said the March 26, 1979 peace treaty ending 30 years
of war between the two nations is ``the foundation stone'' for an
overall Arab-Israeli settlement.
   The agreement, announced Tuesday night by Tourism Minister Fuad
Sultan, removed the major obstacle to Egypt's recovery of the Taba
enclave, awarded by international arbitration in September.
   Under the agreement, Egypt will pay $37 million _ little more
than half the initial claim _ to the Israeli owners of the
Aviya-Sonesta Beach Hotel in Taba.
   If the hotel earns more than $6.3 million a year, the owners will
get that amount up to a ceiling of $3 million a year.
   Sultan said Egypt also will pay $1.15 million for Rafi Nelson
Village, a cafeteria with tourist cabanas on Taba beach.
   The 250-acre enclave overlooks the Red Sea's Gulf of Aqaba at the
southern end of the Egyptian-Israeli frontier.
   President Hosni Mubarak said last month that compensation was the
main impediment to implementing the arbitration ruling.
   Still being discussed are access to Taba for Israelis and
delineation of the frontier from the final border marker to the
beach, a stretch of 150 yards. Egyptian and Israeli officials said
only minor differences remain.
   Information Minister Safwat el-Sherif told reporters that final
agreement is expected by the end of February at a meeting in Taba of
Egyptian, Israeli and U.S. representatives. El-Sherif said Egypt
will take over after Taba on March 15 after Israel withdraws.
   Israel refused to relinquish Taba when it completed its
withdrawal from Egypt's Sinai peninsula in April 1982. Bilateral
talks failed and the dispute was referred to arbitrators in Geneva
in 1986.
   After meeting with Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze
today, Arens said his Egyptian counterpart, Esmat Abdel-Meguid, had
accepted his invitation to visit Israel at a date to be fixed later.
</TEXT>
