<FIRST>u a PM-HospitalWorkers 1stLd-Writethru a0484 02-22 0648</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hospital Workers, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0484,0661</SECOND>
<HEAD>Governor to Lead Negotiatons Aimed at Ending Hospital Strike</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with negotiations underway, new
quote; Picks up 5th graf, ``The governor...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KAREN SCHWARTZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CRANSTON, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Edward D. DiPrete today urged union
leaders to end a walkout at the state General Hospital, where for a
third day National Guard troops substituted for striking nurses and
attendants.
   The first face-to-face talks between hospital and union officials
began less than five hours before a judge's 3 p.m. back-to-work
order was to take effect. Union leaders did not say whether they
would comply with the order.
   ``I ... believe that the elements for the settlement are right
now there,'' DiPrete told the negotiators. But, he added, ``it's
going to take some work.''
   National Guard troops in combat fatigues took over for the
striking attendants and licensed practical nurses when the walkout
began Sunday night at the 410-patient hospital, which provides
long-term care for the chronically ill. Union leaders have
complained about staffing changes at the facility.
   Nanci Martin, DiPrete's press secretary, said talks between the
union and officials of the state Department of Mental Health,
Retardation and Hospitals would be mediated by DiPrete aide Robert
K. Vincent and state Labor Director Bernard Singleton.
   Today's negotiations followed a private hourlong meeting between
DiPrete and union President Joseph G. Fargnoli on Tuesday night,
Martin said.
   ``The governor is hoping that both sides will discuss this,'' she
said. ``The governor is going to be available.''
   Fargnoli made no commitment that the workers would return to
their jobs, Martin said.
   About 120 guardsmen, including seven with nurses training, worked
at the hospital and the neighboring Institute of Mental Health where
union members also failed to show up for their jobs, said Capt. John
Loughlin, a Guard spokesman.
   ``When you join the Guard you realize there's a possibility
you'll be called out to something you may not be totally familiar
with, or may not be totally thrilled about,'' Loughlin said.
   Sue Carberry, a registered nurse who reported to work, said that
although the combat fatigue-clad guardsmen helped to bathe, feed and
dress patients, ``if they don't have someone to tell them what to do
it's difficult.''
   ``I can change my son's diaper, but it's a little different
changing someone else's,'' said Sgt. Al Topp. ``I couldn't do it if
I worked here full time.''
   DiPrete said during a hospital visit that he was willing to keep
the Guard out ``as long as they need people here.'' He said he was
satisfied with the patient care.
   Martin, the governor's spokeswoman, declined to say if DiPrete
prepared concessions to the union, but said he directed hospital
officials to continue staffing patterns that the state imposed last
week to curb overtime, prompting the walkout.
   About a third of 85 normally scheduled attendants and about half
of the nurses reported for work Tuesday, hospital administrator
James Benedict said.
   Benedict said 22 acute-care patients were at or would be moved to
other area hospitals.
   The hospital's medical director, Dr. Rajnikant Shah, said about
half the patients were in medical danger.
   ``I'll be contacting more facilities than I've contacted already
in hopes of appealing to them to take patients more rapidly for us.
We could begin to empty out entire units, if need be,'' Benedict
said.
   A four-day sickout by union members ended Jan. 31 when DiPrete
called out the Guard and threatened to fire employees who failed to
report for work.
   The members of Local 1350 of the American Federation of State,
County and Municipal Employees claim the state has failed to fill
vacant staff positions at the hospital called for in their contract.
The state, in an effort to cut overtime costs, has refused in many
cases to bring in additional workers to replace employees who call
in sick.
</TEXT>
