<FIRST>r a PM-SlipperyEscapee     02-22 0256</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Slippery Escapee,0262</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prisoner Carves Pistol From Soap, Escapes Jail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CROWN POINT, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An inmate used a ``John Dillinger
special'' _ a pistol carved from a bar of soap _ to escape from the
Lake County Jail, where Dillinger himself pulled a real gun to
escape 50 years ago.
   Robert Edward Gregory, 25, a convicted burglar, pulled the fake
pistol on a court bailiff Tuesday, then used it to steal a car,
police said. He later was arrested wihtout incident by police who
spotted the car and returned him to jail. No one was hurt.
   According to legend, Dillinger escaped from the jail in 1934
after brandishing a gun he carved from wood. The legend lives even
though it later was revealed that Dillinger had used a real
.45-caliber automatic.
   Dillinger remained free four months, until he was shot dead in
Chicago in July.
   Gregory's soap gun bought him less than an hour of freedom.
   ``The guy is an artist,'' said Lake County Sheriff Stephen R.
Stiglich. The gun was shaped like an Army .45-caliber pistol and was
blackened with shoe polish or dye, police said.
   Gregory, who served 3{ years of a five-year sentence for
burglary, was arrested in September for public intoxication and
possession of a firearm after taking a potshot with a rifle while
sitting in a car with friends. He had remained in the county jail
since then.
   Just before his escape, Gregory had appeared before Lake County
Judge James A. Krajewski for violating his parole in that incident.
</TEXT>
