<FIRST>r w PM-Bush-Mideast 2ndLd-Writethru a0521 02-22 0907</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Mideast, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0521,870</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tokyo Meetings Unlikely to Produce New Initiatives</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS quotation in 7th graf pvs, ``You walk''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush is still assessing his options
in the Middle East, and his meetings this week with Arab and Israeli
leaders are unlikely to produce new U.S. initiatives to end the
conflict in the region, analysts say.
   Bush departed today for Japan and the funeral of Emperor
Hirohito. While there, he will meet with King Hussein of Jordan and
Presidents Hosni Mubarak of Egypt and Chaim Herzog of Israel, as
well as other world leaders.
   Preparations also are under way to line up visits to the United
States in March and April by Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir,
Hussein and Mubarak, sources said.
   At a news conference Tuesday, Bush told reporters that he would
not be rushed into formulating a policy toward the Middle East
simply because Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze is
engaging in high-profile diplomacy in the region.
   Bush said he wants to take his first Mideast step to be a
``prudent'' one. ``I don't want to be stampeded by the fact that the
Soviet foreign minister takes a trip to the Middle East,'' he said.
   Bush has talked before about pursuing a go-slow policy in the
Middle East.
   ``You crawl before you walk,'' Bush said a week after his
inauguration, when asked whether the time had come for Secretary of
State James A. Baker III to meet with PLO Chairman Yasser Arafat.
   ``There is no policy,'' said Mideast expert Judith Kipper of the
Brookings Institution, at least in part because key positions still
remain unfilled at the State Department.
   Apart from supporting the Reagan administration's decision to end
a 13-year boycott of direct contacts with Arafat's PLO, Bush has
said little to indicate how _ and whether _ his Mideast policy might
contrast with the shuttle diplomacy pursued without success by the
previous administration.
   In fact, Baker last week told European diplomats he thought that
they, too, should move carefully in the area of Mideast peace
offensives.
   A Baker aide, describing the secretary's response to a survey of
the situation by a European Community team, quoted Baker responding
that ``this is an area that if you don't prepare an initiative in
the right way, if you push too hard on the wrong level and on the
wrong issues, the possibilities that are there might be pre-empted.''
   In small bits and pieces, some general Bush administration
Mideast policy principles have begun to emerge:
   _Vice President Dan Quayle told the Anti-Defamation League of
B'nai B'rith on Feb. 10 that the United States would not try to
impose a settlement on Israel, which has been stung by the American
opening to the PLO.
   _Bush administration officials believe Israel must show more
flexibility in ending the violence in the occupied territories of
the West Bank and Gaza strip. The State Department criticized Israel
in its recently-released human rights report, saying Shamir's
government had used unnecessary force in quelling Palestinian
violence in the territories.
   _Baker said at his confirmation hearings that he is opposed to an
independent Palestinian state.
   Further complicating the Bush administration's formulation of its
Mideast strategy is a new and more aggressive role by the Soviet
Union.
   Shevardnadze said in Damascus, Syria, last week that the Kremlin
will push for an international peace conference on the Mideast under
the auspices of the United Nations.
   Several Mideast scholars in this country complain that the Reagan
administration gave only lip service to the notion of an
international conference with Soviet participation, and say the U.S.
government did not genuinely support that concept in the last eight
years.
   What remains obscure is whether Bush will follow the Reagan
administration approach of trying to set up Arab-Israeli
negotiations _ and what role the PLO would play in such talks.
   The effort failed despite four trips to the region by former
Secretary of State George P. Shultz, and several separate missions
by former Assistant Secretary of State Richard Murphy.
   Israel vehemently opposes U.S. dealings with the PLO, and
administration officials say Foreign Minister Moshe Arens will meet
with Baker in the second week of March.
   But Israeli Embassy spokesman Yossi Gal said, ``We expect to be
working very closely with the administration.''
   Several private experts disagreed on whether Bush's cautious
approach was the correct one.
   ``It would be a grave mistake on the part of the administration
to move too fast,'' said Neil Pickett of the Hudson Institute.
   ``I am hoping for a cautious and methodical approach,'' he said,
``but I am very aware of the pressures on him (Bush) not to do
that.''
   Samih Farsoun, an American University professor, said, however,
``there seems to be an international consensus that the U.S. drags
its feet.''
   ``The time for a U.S. peace settlement is now, and the auspices
for it is the United Nations,'' he said. ``I think it is time to
move forward because the PLO has come around.''
   Ms. Kipper, who recently returned from a Mideast tour, said the
administration has shown little enthusiasm for new peace initiatives
because ``they would like to see the Israelis come up with new ideas
in the occupied territories.''
   ``There are very real differences between the United States and
Israel,'' she said. Ms. Kipper said that the opening to the PLO has
transformed ``a dormant policy difference into an active policy
difference.''
</TEXT>
