<FIRST>u a PM-RushdieRallies 1stLd-Writethru a0490 02-22 0714</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rushdie Rallies, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0490,0727</SECOND>
<HEAD>Writers Group Stages Pro-Rushdie Rallies</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with demonstrations outside Iranian
mission, book stores; Picks up 4th graf, `Writers' union ...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Verses-Law, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of authors marched outside the Iranian Mission to the
United Nations today as outraged writers stepped up their protests
over the reaction to Salman Rushdie's novel, ``The Satanic Verses.''
   ``I write controversial books. What publisher is now going to
take chances with a controversial book?'' asked activist Abbie
Hoffman, one of about 300 writers marching in a driving rainstorm
outside the mission in New York City.
   The members of the National Writers Union, on the sidewalk across
from the mission, carried signs which said ``Free Speech Is
Fundamental'' and ``Hands Off Our Constitution.''
   Union president Alec Dubro was rebuffed by building security at
the mission when he attempted to deliver a letter there expressing
outrage at the death threats toward Rushdie.
   The writers then marched on two Fifth Avenue book stores _ B.
Dalton's and Barnes &amp; Noble. Both stores are owned by B. Dalton, one
of the chains that has pulled the book from its shelves in several
cities.
   ``To see book stores caving in like that to demagoguery is
horrifying. These are the largest book-sellers in the country,''
said author Laura Shapiro. ``They exist in honor of freedom of the
press. For them to be so cowardly is despicable.''
   Writers' union locals also planned rallies today in Boston,
Washington, Chicago, Minneapolis and San Francisco.
   A group of prominent authors, including Norman Mailer, Susan
Sontag, Joan Didion, E.L. Doctorow, Robert Caro and Gay Talese,
scheduled a public reading of the book in Manhattan today.
   In Dover, Del. a high school English teacher says she has
encouraged her students to spend part of today protesting outside a
Waldenbooks store. That chain, the nation's largest, has also
withdrawn of the book ``Satanic Verses'' from display on its shelves.
   ``It's not against Waldenbooks, but the position of leadership
the U.S. has failed to take making it necessary for them to drop the
promotion of sales of the book,'' said Dover High School teacher
Phyllis Levitt.
   Iran's religious leader, Ayatollah Khomeini, has placed a bounty
on Rushdie's head, saying ``The Satanic Verses'' blasphemes Islam.
Khomeini also threatened anyone involved in the book's publication.
   ``We've never seen writers as deeply outraged as they've been
over this issue,'' said Alec Dubro, president of the National
Writers Union. He blamed the ``craven response'' of the chains as
well as the threats themselves.
   The chains cited their employees' safety as the reason for
removing the book. The threats also prompted Rushdie to cancel a
U.S. promotional tour and go into hiding with his wife,
American-born novelist Marianne Wiggins.
   Ms. Wiggins was reported today to have canceled a similar
seven-city U.S. tour to promote her new novel, ``John Dollar.''
   Because so many bookstores have stopped selling ``Satanic
Verses'' out of fear of violence, a trio of Yale University
graduates has set up a toll-free number, 1-800-544-7475, through
which anyone may order the book.
   ``We were discussing this and decided it's kind of scary that the
book is relatively unavailable to the American public,'' said one of
the men, Kevin Kiernan of New York. ``A lot of people just don't
know what is in the book and people want to see what is in the
book.''
   Kiernan said they'll sell the book for the retail price, $19.95.
He said they have made arrangements with the book's publisher,
Viking Penguin, but he did not yet know how long it would take to
fill an order.
   In a telegram, the eastern branch of the Writers Guild of America
told Len Riggio, chairman of B. Dalton and Barnes &amp; Noble, that the
group ``strongly protests your removal of the Salman Rushdie book
from the shelves of your stores.''
   ``Intimidation and fear generated by those who do not believe in
our system of free speech cannot justify your company imposing a new
form of censorship,'' it said.
   ``We believe your action sets a dangerous precedent under which
any type of literary material could be forced out of circulation if
threats are made against the distributors, broadcasters or
exhibitors of that material,'' the telegram said.
</TEXT>
