<FIRST>u i PM-ShipSinks 4thLd-Writethru a0558 02-22 0512</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ship Sinks, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0558,0527</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Victims Found From Sunken Cargo Ship</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to UPDATE with four bodies recovered. Pickup
6th graf pvs, ``The Panamanian-registered...''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A cargo ship carrying 17 people sank in the
Atlantic Ocean early today, and rescuers battling 90 mph winds and
rough seas recovered four bodies and searched for the 13 other crew
members, the coast guard said.
   U.S. long-range helicopters, British planes and ships, and a
Danish fishing vessel joined the search for survivors from the
Panamanian-registered Secil Angola, which sank 350 miles west of
Scotland.
   At midday, a Royal Air Force plane returning to Britain spotted
nine life jackets in the water, and Flight Lt. Jim McLeod said
survivors were ``possible.''
   The Danish vessel, the Hordagutt, recovered the bodies, the coast
guard said. Officials said the search was contining.
   McLeod said winds up to 90 mph, combined with snow flurries and
40-foot waves, made it difficult to see anything on the water.
   The Secil Angola, carrying salt from Spain to Iceland, sank at
7:30 a.m. after losing its forward hatch covering and taking on
water, the coast guard said.
   The first distress call came at about midnight, said coast guard
spokesman John Griffiths in Clyde, Scotland.
   At 6 a.m., the ship's captain sent a last desperate message:
``There is great danger. Helicopters please hurry.''
   An RAF Nimrod maritime reconaissance aircraft, the first on the
scene, reported the stricken vessel was awash _ just above the
surface of the water _ at 7:20 a.m., said Griffiths.
   Minutes later the pilot reported radio contact has been lost, the
ship had turned on its side and sank.
   Griffiths said the Nimrod dropped three life rafts and other
rescue equipment onto the water.
   When helicopters reached the area, one crewman was lowered by
cable to search each dinghy and life raft for survivors, said a
spokesman at the rescue coordination center at Pitreavie, Scotland.
   ``On these dinghies the canopies inflate automatically,'' he
said, speaking anonymously in keeping with British custom.
   ``If you are inside, in these kind of conditions ... you don't
poke your head out of the slot,'' he said. ``They would not hear the
aircraft, so the winchman has to go down to look at each one
individually.''
   The crewman had only one hour to complete his search before the
helicopter, operating at maximum range, was forced to return to
Britain to refuel, he said.
   The rescue center requested help from the U.S. Air Force, which
sent two long-range helicopters with midair refueling capabilities
from Keflavik, Iceland, 550 miles away.
   ``Our helicopters had to refuel in air twice,'' said Lt. Matthew
Hamilton. ``They encountered some really bad weather about 7:30, had
to fly around it, which added about 100 miles to their trip.''
   When British officials initially indicated they thought there
were no survivors, the American aircraft returned to base, he said.
   ``Based on the water temperature and the sea state and the
weather, we decided that it was best that we turn around and come
back,'' he said.
</TEXT>
