<FIRST>u w PM-Budget 1stLdWritethru a0446 02-22 0648</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Budget, 1st Ld Writethru, a0446,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Administration Seeks Budget Talks, While Hill Democrats Seek Details</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: Leads with 6 new grafs with morning testimony, picks up 3rd
graf previous, ``We must...''</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX10</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congressional Democrats resumed their criticism
of President Bush's $1.16 trillion budget today, accusing the
administration of sidestepping needed decisions on savings.
   Richard G. Darman, the administration's budget director, defended
the fiscal 1990 blueprint before the House Budget Committee today,
but the panel's chairman, Rep. Leon Panetta, D-Calif., said Bush's
call for deficit savings over a wide range of programs _ without
specifying where spending would be cut _ was inadequate.
   ``These are important to the country and to the American
people,'' Panetta said of the domestic programs that could face
spending reductions. ``The public is entitled to know where the
president stands on these crucial programs.''
   Republicans on the budget committee defended the proposal.
   Rep. Bill Frenzel of Minnesota, the panel's ranking Republican,
said he believed Bush had presented ``a pretty complete budget
picture within 19 days of the inauguration.''
   Darman told the Senate budget panel on Tuesday that the best way
for Bush and the Democratic-controlled Congress to work out a budget
was by negotiating.
   ``We must come to an executive-legislative agreement,'' Darman
told the senators. ``To that end, as a matter of practical reality,
we must negotiate.''
   But Darman ran into a torrent of criticism over the budget that
Bush presented to Congress on Feb. 9.
   Much of it focused on what is becoming known as the budget's
``black box'' _ a collection of more than 1,000 programs, mostly in
domestic areas, that the president wants to hold to the same $136
billion spending total in effect for this year.
   The proposal would save $10 billion to $11 billion from budget
growth that would occur otherwise, but Democrats say Bush's budget
leaves Congress with the painful job of selecting programs to cut.
   ``Where are the cuts going to come from?'' asked panel chairman
Jim Sasser, D-Tenn. ``We don't know. The Bush administration has yet
to tell us.''
   Darman, for the first time, indicated that the administration
considered the ``black box'' approach to be among the items that
could be negotiated.
   ``That's one option,'' he said of the grouping of programs.
``Another option is one that says if you've got ideas for priorities
that need to be funded, we'd like to see those.''
   Lawmakers also repeated charges that the assumptions Bush used
about the economy's expected performance were so optimistic that
they would unrealistically diminish the amount of savings needed to
satisfy the Gramm-Rudman deficit reduction law. That legislation
requires a deficit of no greater than $100 billion next year, or
automatic spending cuts are triggered.
   Sen. J. Bennett Johnson, D-La., said that since there are no
elections this year, and thus no immediate pressures on legislators
seeking re-election, ``We ought to do some serious budgeteering.''
He said that many lawmakers, however, ``are not willing to engage in
a charade.''
   Republicans jumped to Darman's support, including Sen. Pete V.
Domenici, R-N.M., the senior Republican on the committee, who said
he disagreed with the Democrats on the need for fine detail.
   ``I don't think we have to know the details but rather an overall
view,'' he said.
   And Sen. Warren Rudman, R-N.H., said past budgets proposed by
President Reagan were usually pronounced dead on arrival.
   ``Yours is still quivering so I guess you're ahead,'' he told
Darman.
   Administration and congressional officials have held several
meetings already to discuss Bush's budget, and more will be held,
Sasser told reporters after Tuesday's hearing.
   In the most recent session Tuesday morning at the White House,
Bush, Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell, D-Maine, House Speaker
Jim Wright, D-Texas, and others spent most of their time talking
about the budget process rather than specific program or spendng
decisions, participants said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
