<HEAD>Seven Palestinians Shot In Clashes, Four Homes Sealed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with PLO leader's appeal to Israel. No
pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONI RABIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli troops shot and wounded seven
Palestinians today, an Arab reporter said, and underground leaders
of the uprising called for a ``day of confrontations'' to mark the
anniversary of a radical PLO faction.
   A top PLO official said today the organization supports
establishment of a Palestinian state alongside Israel, and he said
the Palestinian charter calling for destruction of the Jewish state
is open to discussion.
   The army sealed the Gaza Strip house of a man suspected of
hurling concrete blocks from his roof at troops, an army official
said. Troops also sealed rooms in three other Gaza Strip homes.
   In the West Bank village of Beit Amin, residents discovered in a
well the body of a man accused of cooperating with Israeli
authorities. Muhammad Abed Suleiman, 25, disappeared two months ago
and residents believe he was killed by fellow Palestinians. An army
official said he was investigating the report.
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin has said more than 60 suspected
collaborators have been killed by fellow Palestinians since the
December 1987 start of the uprising. In all, 384 Palestinians and 16
Israelis have died in the revolt against Israel's occupation of the
West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   A leaflet distributed by the underground Unified National
Leadership of the Uprising called for a ``day of confrontations''
with troops today to mark the 1969 founding of the Marxist
Democratic Front for the Liberation of Palestine, a radical
Palestine Liberation Organization faction led by Nayef Hawatmeh.
   Israel radio reported troops were put on alert.
   Four people wounded in today's protests were hurt in a clash that
occurred when soldiers raided West Bank villages north of Jerusalem
and rounded up dozens of suspects, an Arab reporter said. Hospital
officials confirmed the reports of wounded, and said the youngest
shot was a 13-year-old boy.
   Three other Palestinians were shot and wounded when troops fired
on students hurling rocks at them in Gaza's Jebaliya and Shati
refugee camps, an Arab reporter said.
   An army spokesman said he was checking the reports.
   He said troops sealed three rooms in three homes in Gaza's
Abassan village. They belong to Palestinians accused of setting fire
to a municipal council building to protest a visit by military
personnel, he said.
   Two of the homes only had two rooms, meaning half the house was
blocked off. A family of five lived in one, and an eight-member
family lived in the other.
   During a peace symposium in Jerusalem, a videotape was shown of
Salah Khalaf, Yasser Arafat's No. 2 man.
   Khalaf, known by his nom de guerre Abu Iyad, assured his audience
the PLO recognizes Israel and deplores violence and said: ``We have
arrived at a truth that we hope the Israeli leaders will arrive at
before it is too late. This is the truth which says that two peoples
and two states must coexist in this land,'' Khalaf said in the
address.
   ``All other matters are open to discussion, our covenant and
yours can be discussed,'' Khalaf said.
   The convenant refers to the Palestinian National Charter.
