<HEAD>Garbage Collectors, Other City Workers Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 6,000 municipal workers Wednesday
began a weeklong strike that will halt garbage collection and leave
parks without attendants.
   ``If you don't find a solution ... Greece will stink!'' went the
cry from more than 5,000 demonstrators outside the Interior Ministry.
   The strike began with a march to press demands for a collective
wage agreement and salary increases.
   Dimitris Mihalopoulos, president of the union of municipal
workers, said they were striking because the socialist government
reneged on a promise to settle the dispute.
   ``We are the people who, rain or snow, from daylight to midnight,
clean the cities ... It's not fair that more than 6,000 of us should
not have a collective wage agreement,'' Mihalopoulos said.
   The strike also includes city clerks, record-keepers and road
workers.
   Mihalopoulos said the workers' average monthly salary of about
$400 ``was not enough to support a family.''
   A similar strike last year resulted in piles of uncollected
garbage rotting on streets. Radio stations asked residents to keep
their garbage at home during the strike.
</TEXT>
