<FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-89 1235EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-ForestFires     02-22 0406</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Forest Fires,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Forest Fire Payment Plan Negotiable, Administration Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A controversial plan to pay for fire fighting
on public land is only a starting point for negotiations with
Congress on ways to trim the federal budget, an Agriculture
Department analyst said today.
   The plan was proposed in the Reagan budget sent to Congress in
January and has been endorsed by President Bush as part of the
on-going talks with Capitol Hill on ways to reduce spending.
   Under the Reagan proposal, part of the receipts collected by the
Agriculture and Interior departments for timber sales, mining,
recreation and other fee-paid activities _ that normally go to the
states _ would be used to pay fire-fighting bills.
   The plan was ``not directly addressed'' by Bush in his message to
Congress or in documents provided by the Office of Management and
Budget, ``but it wasn't overruled, either,'' said Mike McDonald of
the USDA's budget office.
   White House budget director Richard Darman calls the Reagan
budget proposals ``a starting point for negotiations in Congress,''
McDonald said in a telephone interview.
   For many years, the Forest Service has kicked back 25 percent of
its annual receipts to the states. In the 1988 fiscal year that
ended last Sept. 30, for example, more than $318 million went to 41
states and Puerto Rico. Oregon led with $144.5 million.
   McDonald said that under the plan, estimated fire costs would be
deducted from estimated total national receipts. The remainder then
would be apportioned to the states where the forests are located.
   As it stands now, each state's share of forest revenues would be
reduced by 18.4 percent.
   ``I've been telling people that whatever you got last year,
presuming that receipts are relatively steady ... the
receipt-sharing payment probably would be about 18.4 percent less
under the Reagan proposal,'' McDonald said.
   That is also the starting point for the Bush proposal, he said.
   ``The only difference betweena the two is the Reagan proposal was
more firm as part of the president's budget,'' McDonald said. ``The
Bush proposal is merely a starting point for negotiation.''
   Using the formula of 18.4 percent, this year's state shares of
the forest earnings _ assumming receipts are about the same as in
1988 _ would be reduced to less than $260 million from $318 million.
Oregon's share would drop to about $118 million from $145 million
last year.
</TEXT>
