<FIRST>u p PM-Duke-SwearingIn 4thLd-Writethru a0597 02-22 0756</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Duke-Swearing In, 4th Ld - Writethru, a0597,0772</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Ku Klux Klan Grand Wizard Takes Seat in Louisiana House</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with comments from Duke, details
from floor debate; Picks up 8th graf, `Duke's 227-vote ...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto staffing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA ASHTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Ku Klux Klan leader David Duke was
sworn in as a member of the Louisiana House today after surviving
two last-minute attempts to block him from taking his seat.
   Duke, a Republican, had overcome opposition by President Bush,
former President Reagan other prominent party leaders to defeat
homebuilder John Treen in Saturday's election in Metairie, a nearly
all-white suburb of New Orleans.
   ``I love this country and I love this state and I am anxious to
get to work and solve the problems of this state,'' Duke told a
packed House chamber today.
   Duke took the oath of office at 10:35 a.m. after the House voted
69-33 to table a motion by a freshman representative to investigate
Duke's credentials.
   Louisiana's House and Senate convened today for a special session
to consider rewriting the state's tax code.
   About 30 minutes before the Legislature convened, State District
Judge Clarence McManus rejected a motion by Treen to block Duke from
taking his seat. Treen, also a Republican, had contended that Duke
did not meet residency requirements.
   Odon Bacque, an independent legislator from Lafayette, then asked
the House to investigate whether Duke was a legal resident of the
district as he was called to the podium to receive the oath of
office. But the House voted to table the motion, clearing the way
for Duke, 38, to be sworn in.
   ``Men of principle must stand when principles are placed in
jeopardy and now is such a time,'' Bacque told the House.
   But Democratic Rep. John Alario urged the House to table the
motion, clearing the way for Duke to take his seat.
   ``I stand here today not to defend Mr. Duke but to defend
democracy. I am confident there is a super majority in this
Legislature who will stand for equal justice for all, no matter who
is elected to its membership,'' Alario said.
   Duke accused Bacque of engaging in ``political chicanery.''
   Duke's 227-vote margin of victory was certified Tuesday by the
secretary of state's office in Baton Rouge after the votes were
counted.
   Treen says Duke lived in a home a few blocks outside his district
and kept an apartment in the district so he could run there. State
law requires a candidate to have lived in the district he wants to
represent for at least a year.
   Duke declined to say whether he had two addresses but said he met
the residency requirements ``in every respect. It's a frivolous
challenge.''
   At a news conference in Baton Rouge, he said he had changed since
his days in the Klan and promised to silence his critics with his
work in the Legislature.
   ``I'm just really proud to live in America,'' said Duke. ``I'm
also looking forward to an end to the hoopla.''
   Duke left the Klan in 1980 but remains the president of the
National Association for the Advancement of White People, which he
describes as a civil rights group for everyone.
   ``I'm certainly not the David Duke I was during my years in the
Klan, but I'm certain I've grown like all people do, mentally,
spiritually,'' he said. ``I believe in the civil rights of all
people. I think the criticism I've endured will be muted by my
activities in the House of Representatives.''
   National Republican Party officials disagree with Louisiana GOP
leaders over how to respond to Duke's election. Under national party
Chairman Lee Atwater's direction, a resolution was prepared
declaring that Duke was ``not a Republican in gesture, deed or
belief.''
   The resolution was expected to be adopted by the party's
11-member executive council, which will confer by telephone Friday.
   But members of the Republican caucus at the Louisiana House said
there were no plans to bar Duke from their ranks if he was sworn in.
   Duke joined the GOP a few days before declaring his candidacy.
Treen is a longtime Republican who was backed by President Bush and
former President Reagan.
   Bush said in Washington that the unprecedented high-level
endorsements may have helped Duke inadvertantly. He said voters may
have considered his letter of support ``improper or overkill,'' but
added that Duke's record is ``one of racism and bigotry and, I'm
sorry, I just felt I had to speak out.''
</TEXT>
