<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Microwave     02-22 0303</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Microwave,0312</SECOND>
<HEAD>Microwave Examined After Mystery Illness Hits Seven</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SHEFFIELD, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Health officials were examining a new
microwave oven Wednesday after seven people, including an ambulance
worker and a doctor, fell ill mysteriously in its vicinity.
   Two people remained in a hospital isolation unit following the
incident, which occurred after the microwave and a TV set were
delivered to an apartment in a suburb of this north England city,
said police.
   The seven _ four people from the apartment, the doctor, his
driver and the ambulance worker _ felt dizziness, burning sensations
around their face and eyes, and some had convulsions, police said. A
dog in the apartment suffered symptoms as well.
   Police examined both appliances at the apartment and
environmental health officials took the microwave to a laboratory
for further examination.
   Rotherham Police Inspector Tony Swabey said the cause of the
illness was not known but ``we are looking at these appliances
closely because it is known that microwaves in particular can give
off rays.''
   The incident occurred early Wednesday at the apartment of Betty
Bisby, 52. Her two daughters _ Linda Young, 26, and Christine
Kendrick, 30 _ were staying the night, along with a family friend,
Les Jarvis, 55.
   After becoming ill, they called a doctor, who also became sick,
along with his driver. The doctor called an ambulance, and although
at the doctor's behest the worker who came inside wore protective
clothing, she suffered burning symptoms as well.
   Mrs. Young and Jarvis were treated at a hospital and released,
but Mrs. Bisby and Mrs. Kendrick remained in an isolation unit at
Sheffield's Lodge Moor Hospital.
   The three others did not require medical treatment.
   Fire crews checked the apartment but did not find any gas leaks
or toxic fumes. The environmental health department in Rotherham
refused comment.
</TEXT>
