<FIRST>r a PM-SisterSlaying 1stLd-Writethru a0575 02-22 0451</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sister Slaying, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0575,0457</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman Accused of Helping Sister's Assailants Escape</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 4th graf to UPDATE with one suspect surrendering;
Picks up 5th graf, `Shari Bierman ...'; SUBS 6th graf, `The men ...' to
delete now-outdated material.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who authorities say had a
long-standing rivalry with a sister found stabbed to death this week
has been arraigned on charges of helping the killers escape.
   Wearing a jail uniform and frequently weeping, Shari L. Bierman,
20, appeared Tuesday in Wyandotte County Circuit Court to face
charges of felony theft and aiding a felon to escape in the death of
Syndi S. Bierman, 17, an honor student and athlete at Piper High
School.
   Miss Bierman's beaten and stabbed body was found Sunday in the
bedroom of her home in Piper, an unincorporated community of about
2,500 people about 20 miles northwest of Kansas City.
   Shari Bierman's boyfriend, Conrad Joseph Hernandez, 24, and
Archie E. Owens Jr., 20, were charged in absentia with the killing.
   Hernandez surrendered today to Oklahoma authorities after a
disagreement with his companions over whether to surrender, police
said. Owens remained at large.
   Hernandez indicated he would waive extradition to face the
charges, said Sgt. John Bowman, a Tulsa police spokesman.
   Shari Bierman was held under $50,000 bond after District Attorney
Nick Tomasic told the judge that the investigation was continuing
and that additional charges could be filed against her. He also said
she should be held for her own safety until Owens and Hernandez were
captured.
   The men were stopped Monday while hitchhiking in Oklahoma, but
authorities there didn't know they were wanted in Kansas and didn't
detain them.
   Rick Grosko of the Wyandotte County Sheriff's Department said
there had been a long history of animosity between the two sisters.
``They seemed to go together like oil and water,'' he said.
   ``There was jealousy because Syndi is pretty and popular, Shari
got pregnant and dropped out,'' said Lisa Hennessy, who had been
visiting the younger sister at the Bierman home Saturday night
before the slaying.
   Syndi Bierman was upstairs preparing for bed after a visit from
two friends, while her sister and the two men were downstairs in the
basement, Tomasic said.
   Tomasic said the two men began removing items from the house and
confronted Syndi Bierman, making sexual advances toward her. In the
attack that followed, her throat was cut and she was stabbed in the
chest and abdomen and beaten, officials said.
   Authorities said it was unclear where Shari Bierman was during
the attack. She phoned the sheriff's department to report a burglary
and her sister's body was found when officers arrived.
</TEXT>
