<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Jews Bjt   02-22 0677</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Jews, Bjt,0694</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jewish School Opens in Moscow, First in Half-Century</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet Jews who studied their religion
clandestinely for years came out into the open Wednesday to enroll
in the first school of Jewish studies in the country since Stalin's
time.
   The opening of the Judaic Studies Center ``is the event we've
been awaiting all our conscious lives,'' said Yuriel Neishtadt, who
sported a full black beard and wore a hand-woven religious skull cap.
   Neishtadt, 31, said he secretly studied Hebrew and Jewish prayers
with small groups of friends.
   Until recently, Soviets were jailed for teaching Hebrew. Among
the most prominent teachers was Josef Begun, who served more than
three years in prison on charges of anti-Soviet agitation and
propaganda, before being released exactly two years ago. He
emigrated to Israel in January 1988.
   In a symmetry of history permitted by President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev's reforms, Neishtadt and other Soviet Jews will be taking
classes from descendants of some of the country's Jewish leaders.
   Rabbi Gedalya Rabinowitz, director of Yeshiva Oholei Yitzhak in
Jerusalem, told about 200 people gathered for the opening that his
``great grandfather's great grandfather'' had established a Jewish
school in Moscow 150 years ago.
   ``And now I am here 150 years later at the inauguration of a new
house of study and prayer,'' said the gray-bearded Rabinowitz. He
then gave the center's first lecture, about customs of the
springtime holiday of Passover.
   Rabbi Joel Poupko, director of Judaica for the Jewish Community
Centers of Chicago, said his grandfather headed a Yeshiva in the
Russian city of Yelets but was imprisoned under dictator Josef
Stalin in 1926.
   ``It is some 63 years later, and we give thanks to almighty
God,'' Poupko told the audience at the House of Scientists.
   The Jewish center, known as a Yeshiva, will be housed elsewhere
in Moscow, in an apartment complex owned by the Soviet Academy of
Sciences. On the Soviet side, the center is organized by the Academy
of World Civilizations, a branch of a Geneva-based group of
scientists known as the World Laboratory. On the Western side, help
comes from the Aleph Society, a group of philanthropists in Israel
and the United States that supports the work of Rabbi Adin
Steinsaltz, one of the world's most prominent specialists on the
Jewish Talmud and a teacher at the new center.
   The center, with an initial enrollment of 80 students, will train
rabbis and scholars in the Bible, the Talmud, Jewish law and history.
   Another of the visiting scholars, David Berger, a history
professor at Brooklyn College, said he helped interview prospective
students and was almost brought to tears. One man in his 20s who had
studied with his father began his interview by citing from memory a
passage from the Torah in Hebrew, Berger said.
   ``There's a level of commitment that is really remarkable and you
don't see it in the West where we take things for granted,'' Berger
said.
   But one student who was chosen accused the Soviet government of
supporting the center purely for ``propagandistic purposes'' and
said some would-be classmates were discouraged from enrolling. The
student spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Gorbachev has opened many doors for Jews and other religious
groups, and has promised changes in a 1929 law prohibiting religious
classes for the young.
   For the Soviet Union's estimated 1.8 million Jews, the
liberalization has meant an increase in emigration, the opening last
week of the first Jewish cultural center in the Soviet Union in more
than 50 years, greater tolerance of religious celebrations and less
repression of Jewish activists.
   On Tuesday, leaders of the Washington-based B'nai B'rith group _
once villified in the Soviet press and popular literature _
presented a founding charter for a branch to 40 Moscow Jews, said
spokesman Daniel Mariaschin.
   Steinsaltz said the Soviet Union was once the ``Jewish
heartland'' of the world and the center could help restore that
status.
   However, he cited a Jewish saying that cautions: ``Every
beginning should be judged by what comes after.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
