<FIRST>r a PM-MercyKilling     02-22 0395</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mercy Killing,0406</SECOND>
<HEAD>78-Year-Old Man Sentenced To Two Years House Arrest In Shooting of
Wife</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYANN MROWCA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRIENDSHIP, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 78-year-old man who fatally shot his
bedridden wife and then swallowed a handful of pills was sentenced
today to two years of house arrest.
   Frank J. Reinl also was placed on 10 years of probation by Adams
County Circuit Judge Raymond Gieringer, whose voice cracked and who
paused several times during an hourlong sentencing hearing.
   ``Sir, what you did was absolutely wrong. The court cannot
condone it,'' the judge said. ``You may have considered it an
ultimate act of love _ I believe you did _ but it was wrong.''
   Before he was sentenced, Reinl cried, trying to explain briefly
why he killed his wife.
   ``I realized she could not be alone for a single second,'' he
told the judge.
   He described how his wife, who had suffered a series of strokes
and had been released from a hospital six days before the shooting,
kept getting out of bed to go to the bathroom every few seconds.
   Reinl pleaded guilty in November to one count of second-degree
murder in the Feb. 8, 1988, shooting of his wife, Rose, 73.
   Shortly before the shooting, Reinl had lost more than 30 pounds
and learned he had progressive leukemia, defense attorney Gary
Kryshak said.
   ``There is nothing that this court is going to do that is going
to punish Frank Reinl more than the fact that he has to live with
what he did,'' Kryshak said.
   Adams County District Attorney Mark Thibodeau agreed, saying it
was obvious that he loved his wife. Reinl had been meticulous in her
care since she suffered her first stroke in June 1987 and called the
doctor to the point of being bothersome, he said.
   But the prosecutor said what Reinl did was still wrong and a
message had to be sent to the public that it would not be condoned.
   ``It would serve no purpose to put you in prison. The prisons are
already full,'' the judge told Reinl. ``But his court must send a
message that it's not OK to take a life, not even a loved one.''
   He also ordered Reinl to pay $5,000 to start a crime prevention
fund, noting that the presentence report indicated he was ``a man of
some means.''
</TEXT>
