<FIRST>r w AM-US-Czechoslovakia     02-22 0281</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Czechoslovakia,270</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Regrets Sentencing of Czech Dissident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department expressed deep regret
Wednesday over the sentencing of a dissident Czech playwright,
calling it ``bitter testimony'' to the lack of human rights in
Czechoslovakia.
   Vaclav Havel, a human rights activist, was sentenced Tuesday to a
nine-month prison term after he was convicted of inciting people to
attend what Czech authorities regarded as an anti-government
demonstration last month.
   State Department spokesman Charles Redman said that the
administration had strongly urged the Czechoslovak government last
week to drop the charges against Havel and to enter into a dialogue
with dissident groups in Czechoslovakia.
   ``Mr. Havel's trial yesterday and his nine-month sentence are
bitter testimony to the lack of respect for fundamental human rights
in Czechoslovakia,'' Redman said.
   He noted in particular that much of the government's case on the
incitement charge against Havel apparently involved his interviews
with Western media, including Radio Free Europe.
   Ironically, Redman said, these interviews were intended by Havel
to head off a reported plan by a group to repeat a 1969 act of
self-immolation by Jan Palach, a student who was protesting the
Soviet invasion of Czechoslovakia the previous year.
   ``Havel had been thwarted in his efforts to use Czechoslovak
media to appeal to this group not to commit such an act and had
turned in frustration to Western media, which routinely provide
information of broad interest to Czechoslovak public opinion, which
official media do not carry,'' Redman said.
   ``We're also troubled by reports that even more individuals may
face charges arising from last month's peaceful demonstration in
Prague. We again urge the Czechoslovak government to abandon the
confrontational practices of the past.''
</TEXT>
