<FIRST>r i AM-SovietKrishnas     02-22 0469</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet Krishnas,0483</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Soviet Hare Krishnas on Pilgrimage to India</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SANTOSH BASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CALCUTTA, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scores of saffron-robed Soviet Hare
Krishna devotees chanted and danced in ecstasy after they arrived in
the land where their faith began.
   The 49 men _ all but one with shaven heads _ and 10 women arrived
from Moscow on Tuesday to begin a three-week pilgrimage.
   ``We are in the land of Caitanya!'' they shouted as they ran from
an Aeroflot plane into Calcutta airport's arrival lounge.
   Caitanya is the 14th century Indian Hindu philosopher whose
teachings are followed by devotees around the world.
   Under the leadership of Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev,
the Kremlin has sought to portray itself as more tolerant of
religions.
   Although Soviet law does not forbid the practicing of religion,
it requires that religious groups be registered with the state. Hare
Krishnas have said in the past that authorities have refused to
register them or failed to respond to their requests for
registration. They have claimed that Hare Krishnas have been jailed
or placed in psychiatric hospitals as recently as August 1987.
   ``Gorbachev's perestroika and glasnost has really worked. We are
here thanks to the new policy of our leader,'' said Olga Kiscleva, a
Moscow teacher and poet in her early 30s.
   She said she joined the Hare Krishna movement nearly 18 years ago.
   The pilgrims said they were the first followers of the Soviet
Union's International Society for Krishna Consciousness (Iskcon)
allowed to make a foreign visit.
   At a news conference, Ms. Kiscleva and other members of the group
said their movement had only recently attained tolerance in the
Soviet Union.
   ``Until April 1988 Iskcon was virtually banned in the Soviet
Union,'' Ms. Kiscleva said. ``During that period many of the Iskcon
followers were jailed. Then came May 1988 when Iskcon was given
Soviet official recognition. We are now free to practice our
religion publicly.''
   She said there were 450 ``initiated Iskcon devotees'' in the
Soviet Union and at least 10,000 other Hare Krishna followers.
``They are living in 60 different cities and preaching the Iskcon
philosophy,'' she said.
   Their ranks included writers, artists, teachers, engineers and
scientists, Ms. Kiscleva said.
   ``Ours is the first group to visit India, the birthplace of Lord
Caitanya. Many more will follow,'' she added.
   The chant of ``Hare Krishna'' _ ``Praise Krishna'' _ was
recommended by Caitanya as the simplest form of prayer to the Hindu
deity. Krishna, who personifies the ideal child, lover and
philosopher, is revered as one of the 10 incarnations of Lord
Vishnu, a member of Hinduism's supreme trinity of gods.
   The Soviets plan to spend a few days in Calcutta and then embark
on a tour of temples in India. They are scheduled to return to
Moscow on April 15.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
