<FIRST>r i AM-Price     02-22 0633</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Price,0650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Outgoing U.S. Ambassador Reflects on Years in Britain</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``She calls me Charlie and that's fine,'' said
Charles H. Price II, U.S. ambassador to the Court of St. James's.
``I always refer to her as prime minister.''
   Price was talking about the relationship he has forged with
Margaret Thatcher during a 5{-year spell as ambassador to the Reagan
administration's close ally.
   He said the first call he got at the embassy on the night of the
Pan Am air disaster was from Mrs. Thatcher, offering him a ride to
the crash site in Lockerbie, Scotland.
   He ended up going on his own, but Mrs. Thatcher's gesture was ``a
measure of how considerate and thoughtful she is,'' he said.
   Price, 57, returns this month to his native Kansas City, Mo., to
resume his banking career as an executive and chairman-designate of
Ameribanc Inc. His successor is President Bush's nominee, Henry
Catto, a onetime U.S. chief of protocol.
   Ronald Reagan's man in Margaret Thatcher's Britain has had a U.S.
foreign service plum: an imposing embassy in Grosvenor Square and an
elegant residence, Winfield House, in 12 acres of private grounds in
Regent's Park, and an Anglo-American relationship that has seldom
been closer.
   Yet, his years of service were a trying time for the United
States and its West European allies.
   The 1987 treaty to remove the superpowers' medium- and
shorter-range nuclear missiles from Europe raised old West European
anxieties about America loosening the mutual defense
responsibilities within the NATO alliance. European Economic
Community moves to dismantle internal trade barriers by 1992 raised
U.S. fears of a ``Fortress Europe'' looming to keep out U.S. goods.
   Price predicts that in the next few years the Bush
administration, driven by pressure in Congress to make the Europeans
pay more for their defense, will fulfill one of Mrs. Thatcher's
worst fears and reduce the 325,000 U.S. troops in Europe.
   ``Burden-sharing,'' said Price of the arguments about defense
spending within the alliance, ``is a real issue which is potentially
divisive.''
   ``When Americans think about the fact ... that the cost of
maintaining that (troop) presence is larger than the combined
contribution of all the other allies, that becomes a very simplistic
thing that politicians can latch on to quickly in the fact of the
(federal) budget deficit problem,'' adds Price.
   ``I would not necessarily be surprised if in the course of the
next 2-3 years there was an American troop reduction.''
   On trade relations, Price is more optimistic, despite a current
dispute over an EEC ban on hormone-treated U.S. beef that has the
seeds of a damaging trade war.
   Price returns home a committed Anglophile, unshaken by
demonstrations over nuclear arms and the biggest protest this decade
at the embassy when 6,000 people converged after the 1986 U.S.
bombing of Libya. Mrs. Thatcher provoked a domestic uproar by
allowing the bombers to fly from British bases.
   Price, who built up an inherited candy business in Kansas City
and branched into banking, was named ambassador to Belgium at the
start of Reagan's first term. He arrived in London in 1983 to
replace John Louis, who made little impact as ambassador.
   Price often has been a go-between, and he traveled regularly on
the British prime minister's plane as the Thatcher-Reagan rapport
grew.
   Aides said he displayed a keen grasp of issues _ praise not
always given by career diplomats who sometimes grumble that
political appointee ambassadors are ill-informed figureheads
enjoying the fruits of their election campaign contributions.
   The Prices are leaving Winfield House a gift of a sculpture of
Barbara Hutton, the Woolworth heiress who built the beautiful
neo-Georgian house 50 years ago and gave it to the United States as
a residence for the ambassador in 1946.
</TEXT>
