<FIRST>r a AM-Everglades-Mercury     02-22 0408</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Everglades-Mercury,0421</SECOND>
<HEAD>Unsafe Mercury Levels Found in Everglades Fish, Officials Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State officials have found
potentially dangerous levels of mercury in largemouth bass from the
Everglades but are waiting for additional test results before
issuing health warnings.
   The discovery comes at the height of the season in the Everglades
and on nearby Lake Okeechobee, one of the top bass-fishing spots in
the nation.
   Concentrations of the heavy metal were more than double federal
safety guidelines, the Department of Health and Rehabilitative
Services said this week.
   The samples were taken in November; a second set of samples was
requested earlier this month.
   ``Personally, I don't think I'd eat any of those fish until the
results come in and HRS says it's safe,'' said Frank Morello, a
state fisheries supervisor.
   Mercury can cause birth defects and affect the nervous system,
causing poor coordination, numbness, deafness and impairment of the
sense of taste and smell, although experts say it takes long-term
exposure to high levels to cause problems.
   Additional test results will not be available for two to three
weeks, said Dr. Thomas Atkeson, HRS program manager for
environmental epidemiology.
   ``A period of two or three weeks is not going to make a
difference in anybody's life. I'd like to see a more robust data set
... before making a decision,'' he said.
   Officials said they don't know the source of the mercury but plan
to look at past use of now-banned pesticides by sugar growers,
illegal dumping of electronic components and air pollution.
   HRS, the state Department of Environmental Regulation and the
Florida Game and Fresh Water Fish Commission have formed a mercury
contamination task force.
   The game commission also found high levels of mercury in four
alligators that had been killed last week for examination. The
reptiles were taken from the same Everglades canals where the
tainted fish were caught.
   The first sample of nine Everglades bass showed mercury levels
ranging from 1.2 to 3.4 parts per million. A second set of 15 fish
from the same areas ranged from 1.5 to 2.75 parts per million. The
alligators tested had concentrations from 1 part per million to 2.37.
   The federally established level for concern is 1 part per million.
   If future tests show the levels to be between 0.5 and 1.5 parts
per million, a warning will be issued against eating the fish more
than once a week, said HRS spokesman Steve Konicki.
</TEXT>
