<FIRST>u i AM-India-Carbide     02-22 0525</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India-Carbide,0542</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Legislators Denounce Bhopal Court Award</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NILOVA ROY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition legislators on Wednesday
rejected the $470 million compensation that Union Carbide Corp.
agreed to pay victims of the 1984 Bhopal gas disaster, and they
promised to force the government to fight for more money.
   Survivors of the world's worst industrial disaster marched in
their own protest Wednesday as yet another petition was filed, this
one from a social service group seeking $600 million in damages for
death and injury caused by the lethal cloud of gas that seeped out
of a storage tank at Bhopal pesticide plant.
   The $470 million was part of a settlement reached Feb. 14 between
the U.S.-based multinational and the Indian government, which
originally demanded $3 billion.
   ``Is human life so cheap in this country we must accept such a
low amount?'' said Communist Party legislator Saifuddin Chowdhury.
   ``Our consciences are not dead, and neither are those of the
victims who are suffering but have come here to show they will not
be humiliated,'' he said in a special parliamentary debate.
   About 2,500 gas victims came to New Delhi from Bhopal to protest
the settlement Wednesday at the Boat Club, a grassy expanse half a
mile from Parliament building. They were supported by 500 Delhi
University students.
   Police prevented them from marching to Parliament.
   In Bhopal, 1,000 victims marched outside the residence of Chief
Minister Motilal Vorha of Madhya Pradesh state.
   More than 3,400 people were killed in the disaster, and 20,000
more are listed as seriously affected by the leak of methyl
isocyanate. Deaths attributed to it continue at the rate of at least
one a day.
   More than 500,000 damage claims have been filed. The latest was
filed Wednesday by the Association for Socio-Legal Literacy, a
social service group which sought a direction from the Supreme Court
ordering Union Carbide to pay $600 million because the Feb. 14 order
rendered the gas victims ``remediless.''
   Unde the agreement, the single payment absolves Union Carbide
from any other claims in the disaster. India's Supreme Court long
ago dismissed criminal charges brought against the Danbury,
Conn.-based multinational.
   Wednesday's parliamentary debate was inconclusive.
   Madhu Dandavate of the opposition Janata Party said Parliament
was the only forum that could reverse the Supreme Court order.
   ``We in this House must try to compensate them (victims) for the
tremendous suffering,'' Dandavate said. ``The settlement is a total
surrender to Union Carbide.''
   If it came to a vote, legislators of the governing Congress Party
vastly outnumber the opposition and have supported the government's
argument that a settlement had to be reached quickly to help victims
who already have suffered for four years.
   Congress Party legislators denied charges during debate that the
government colluded with Union Carbide, but some agreed the figure
of $470 million was low.
   K.N. Pradhan, a legislator from Bhopal who was personally
affected by the leak, said, ``I agree the compensation is very low,
but at least it is money in hand. What good would $3 billion have
done after 20 years when the cases were finally settled and all the
victims dead?''
</TEXT>
