<FIRST>r i AM-Argentina-US     02-22 0170</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Argentina-US,0176</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ambassador to be Replaced, Newspaper Reports</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Ambassador Theodore Gildred,
a California businessman and philanthropist, will be replaced
following the May 14 national elections, a newspaper reported
Wednesday.
   A spokeswoman at the U.S. Embassy said she had no comment on the
report in La Nacion, which cited sources in the Foreign Ministry.
   She added, however, that Gildred ``is not a career diplomat. He's
a businessman. He's been happy here, but he has other things to do.''
   Gildred, 53, is founder and chairman of the board of the San
Diego-based Torres Pines Bank, and the Lomas Sante Fe Co., which
develops and manages real estate.
   He presented his credentials to President Raul Alfonsin in
November 1986.
   President Bush will nominate as a replacement Terence Todman, a
former assistant secretary of state for inter-American affairs and
ambassador to Chad, Costa Rica and Spain, La Nacion reported.
   Foreign Minister Dante Caputo was told of the impending change
this week while in Washington, La Nacion reported.
</TEXT>
