<FIRST>r a AM-Mexico-Hazards     02-22 0410</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Hazards,0420</SECOND>
<HEAD>AFL-CIO Report: Workers Face Hazards at Mexican Plants Near U.S.
Border</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAL HARBOUR, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers at Mexican factories just across
the U.S. border are routinely exposed to toxins because of vague and
little-enforced safety and environmental laws, labor leaders were
told Wednesday.
   A report to the AFL-CIO Executive Council blamed both the U.S.
and Mexican governments for the problems, saying Mexico has been
tardy in regulating workplace safety while the United States has
ignored the abuses because the area is attractive to American
corporations looking for cheap labor and scant government regulation.
   ``Both countries must undertake a massive effort to address this
alarming situation,'' said the report, which prompted a council
resolution condemning the situation and demanding action from both
governments.
   The study looked at the nearly 800 ``maquiladoras'' employing
approximately 300,000 Mexicans in the Rio Grande. The term, Spanish
for ``golden twins,'' refers to plants operated by foreign
corporations, most of them American.
   The report said that many workers are exposed to toxic chemicals
such as PCBs and that many locals drink contaminated water from
storage drums that once held hazardous materials.
   Communities that get their drinking water from the area have
unusually high cancer rates, and much of the waste that by law
should be returned to the United States for dumping instead is
disposed of in Mexico, the report said.
   Environmental problems associated with illegal and improper
dumping of toxins have spilled over into bordering communites in
Texas and California, the report said, citing California's polluted
New River as a prime example.
   ``But American companies don't seem deterred,'' it said. ``They
see increasing opportunity to capitalize on cheap labor and to
escape stringent health, safety and environmental regulations in
this country by shifting operations to Mexico.''
   The problems are complicated because the operations based in the
region are those that typically produce dangerous waste, such as the
chemical and electronics industry, said the report by Leslie Kochan,
an Oregon Department of Environmental Quality official who formerly
worked on environmental issues for the Texas Center for Policy Study.
   In addition, the factories are also rife with abuses of workers,
including wages of as little as $2.90 a day and working conditions
``that resemble the sweatshops of the late 19th and early 20th
century,'' the report said.
   Workers often are denied information about the hazardous
substances they handle and work without protective clothing and
equipment, the report said.
</TEXT>
