<FIRST>r a AM-MetSeason     02-22 0518</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Met Season,0536</SECOND>
<HEAD>Metropolitan Opera Announces Plans for Next Season</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American soprano Aprile Millo will open the
Metropolitan Opera's 1989-1990 season in the title role of Verdi's
``Aida,'' and the company will present five new productions,
including Mozart's ``Don Giovanni,'' Wagner's `The Flying Dutchman''
and Gounod's ``Faust.''
   Joining Miss Millo in the cast Sept. 25 will be tenor Placido
Domingo as Radames and Russian bass Paata Burchuladze in his Met
debut as Ramfis, the company announced Wednesday.
   The two other new productions will both be Verdi operas,
``Rigoletto'' and ``La Traviata.'' There also will be three
performances of Wagner's four-opera ``Ring Cycle,'' in a production
that will be staged in its entirety for the first time this spring.
Casting for the ``Ring cycle'' has not been announced.
   The first of the new productions, ``La Traviata'' on Oct. 16,
will have direction, sets and costumes by Franco Zeffirelli. Czech
soprano Edita Gruberova will sing Violetta and Neil Shicoff will
sing Alfredo. Carlos Kleiber will conduct.
   Luciano Pavarotti will sing the Duke in the ``Rigoletto''
premiere Nov. 3. American soprano June Anderson will make her Met
debut as Gilda. Leo Nucci will sing Rigoletto and Marcello Panni
will conduct.
   Eva Marton will sing Senta and James Morris will be the Dutchman
in the new ``Flying Dutchman'' on Dec. 11. James Levine, the Met's
artistic director, will conduct this opera, and also ``Aida'' and
``Don Giovanni.''
   Harold Prince will make his Met debut directing the new
``Faust,'' opening next Feb. 1. Carol Vaness will sing Marguerite,
Shicoff will be Faust and Morris will sing the role of
Mephistopheles. Charles Dutoit will conduct. Rolf Langenfass, who
designed the ``Ring Cycle'' costumes, will design sets and costumes.
   Zeffirelli will also direct and design the final new production,
``Don Giovanni,'' bowing on March 22, 1990 with American bass Samuel
Ramey in the title role. Miss Vaness will sing Donna Anna, Karita
Mattila will make her Met debut as Donna Elvira and Dawn Upshaw will
sing Zerlina. Italian bass Ferruccio Furlanetto will sing Leporello.
In later performances, Furlanetto will sing Don Giovanni and Ramey
will be heard as Leporello.
   Artists returning after an absence of a season or more include
Katia Ricciarelli, as Desdemona in ``Otello,'' with Domingo as
Otello and Justino Diaz as Iago and Kleiber conducting. Teresa
Stratas will sing all three heroines in Puccini's ``Il Trittico.''
Hermann Prey will sing Eisenstein in Johann Strauss' ``Die
Fledermaus.'' Shirley Verrett will sing opposite Domingo in
Saint-Saens' ``Samson et Dalila.''
   Three sopranos making debuts are Susan Dunn, as Leonora in
Verdi's ``Il Trovatore,'' Alessandra Marc in ``Aida'' and Ashley
Putnam, Marguerite in ``Faust.''
   Pavarotti and Ghena Dimitrova will sing in Ponchielli's ``La
Gioconda.'' Mirella Freni will sing the title role of Puccini's
``Manon Lescaut.'' Both Marilyn Horne and Kathleen Battle will sing
Rosina in Rossini's ``The Barber of Seville.'' Margaret Price and
Tatiana Troyanos will sing in Mozart's ``Cosi fan tutte.'' Gwyneth
Jones will take the title role in Puccini's ``Turandot'' and Miss
Millo will sing Liu. Hildegard Behrens will sing in Berg's
``Wozzeck.''
</TEXT>
