<HEAD>Mediator Meets with Airline, Union Representatives</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal mediator began meeting Wednesday with
representatives of Eastern Airlines and the Machinists union in an
effort to reach a settlement before a 30-day cooling-off period
expires, the director of the National Mediation Board said.
   Charles Barnes, executive director of the board, said the board
requested the meetings ``to make, in effect, a last attempt to
resolve differences before termination of the 30-day cooling-off
period.''
   The airline rejected the board's offer of binding arbitration to
end the 16-month dispute. That rejection triggered the 30-day
period, after which the union will be free to strike and the airline
free to impose its disputed terms on workers.
   The cooling-off period ends at midnight March 3.
   Mediator Harry D. Bickford was meeting with the two sides, Barnes
said. The meetings are expected to continue.
   Eastern, which estimates it is losing $1 million a day, is
seeking $150 million in wage concessions from the airline's 8,500
Machinists union members.
