<FIRST>r w AM-Budget     02-22 0457</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Budget,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Budget Director Provides No Specifics On Administration Policies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   White House budget director Richard Darman,
attacked by Democrats for playing games when the deficit must be
cut, refused Wednesday to reveal President Bush's policies on a wide
swath of domestic programs.
   Darman repeatedly declined to say what spending levels Bush
wanted next year for programs such as care for poor pregnant women,
veterans' education, mass transit, or even the Job Training
Partnership Act _ the bill Bush cited in choosing Dan Quayle for his
vice presidential running mate.
   ``President Bush's position is that he wants to negotiate the
answer to that, and you don't like that apparently,'' he told Rep.
Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., during one particularly testy exchange
during his testimony before the House Budget Committee.
   Boxer, demanding specifics, said that while some of the
initiatives in the $1.16 trillion budget Bush presented on Feb. 9
sounded good, ``we haven't really seen the bad parts.''
   Bush placed $136 billion in programs, mostly domestic agencies,
together in a ``flexible freeze'' with no increase to cover rising
costs, and without endorsing increases or cuts on any particular
program so long as the total remained the same.
   Boxer complained that Bush's fiscal 1990 budget appeared to
``reward the military establishment with full inflation while you
kill'' domestic programs.
   Darman responded that Boxer was applying a ``double standard'' _
judging military programs as increased when they go up with
inflation but calling domestic programs cut when they don't keep
that pace.
   The president's budget has it the other way around. Military
programs were deemed ``frozen'' when they were boosted to cover
inflationary costs. Domestic programs were frozen when they had no
increase at all.
   Darman denied that the hundreds of programs in the
administration's ``flexible freeze'' category were ones that Bush
doesn't care about. ``We just don't care as intensely,'' he said.
   Budget committee chairman Leon Panetta criticized Darman for
outlining options but not Bush choices in the hundreds of pages of
documents he was presenting to Congress.
   ``There have been too many games played with the deficit issue in
the past,'' Panetta said. ``My concern is when you strip the
rhetoric aside ... some of the same games are being played.''
   He cited optimistic economic forecasts, and the assumption that
Congress was going to approve new government fees and sell-offs of
government assets that it has rejected in the past.
   Darman repeated his request that Congress join in negotiations
with the administration. ``Why wait. Why don't we start right
away,'' he said.
   But Panetta said, ``What you have presented may not help
negotiations. It may hurt negotiations.''
   Congress has a deadline of April 15 to produce a final budget.
</TEXT>
