<FIRST>r i AM-Vietnam-US     02-22 0528</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Vietnam-US,0542</SECOND>
<HEAD>American War Veteran Favors U.S. Assistance to Vietnam</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American Vietnam War veteran who
recently accompanied a group of U.S. high school students to Vietnam
says the United States owes the Vietnamese development assistance.
   ``Our knowledge of history heavily tainted with hindsight enables
veterans like myself as well as civilians to realize that we made
some very big mistakes as a country,' said Tim Porta, 44, owner of a
resort hotel in Maine.
   ``We owe it now to the Vietnamese people to establish this
infrastructure that will enable them to go it alone. It has to be
done ... and really come from the heart and without strings
attached,'' Porta said in an interview Tuesday. He suggested the
United States could help pay for badly needed roads.
   Porta traveled to Vietnam with his 18-year-old son, Michael, one
of 17 students on a two-week educational tour that began Feb. 2. In
Vietnam, the students toured schools and discussed U.S.-Vietnamese
relations.
   ``The Vietnamese have the intellect, the desire, tremendous drive
and 10 years of exposure to a race of people that were light years
ahead of them and then all of a sudden it went out like a light in
1975 and then they were left with nothing,'' the elder Porta said.
   Trip organizer Stephen Knight, a history teacher from Fairfield,
Maine, said American textbooks on Vietnam were inadequate and that
traveling was the best way to learn.
   ``As a teacher, I would hope that they get a better understanding
of the problems of the world, how poor people are, how hard they
have to work for a living,'' said Knight, adding that the students
kept journals during their stay in Vietnam.
   The students have been studying about Vietnam for a year in a
specially accredited history class taught by Knight. The students,
averaging about 17 in age, came from Lawrence High School,
Messalonskee High School, Skowhegan High School, Waterville High
School and Waynflete High School, all in the Portland, Maine, area.
   Despite common complaints about rough toilet paper, dirty
bathrooms and unclean drinking water, the students described their
trip as ``valuable experience.''
   ``I just wanted to see how the people live,'' said Michael Porta.
``Even though they don't have a whole lot in their lives, a whole
lot that's positive or to look forward to, it seems like the people
are content, happy with what little they do have, whereas in America
everyone wants more.''
   Sixteen-year-old Heidi Holmes said: ``Americans have a mirrored
view from what veterans have told them. Things are more vivid if you
see them and learn them for yourself.''
   College student Kevin Cloutier, 21, who joined the tour, said
Americans should bury the past.
   ``I think the Americans feel they have to dwell on the war, dwell
on the people who were in the war and our policies even though the
war is over,'' he said.
   ``We still have to try to analyze what we did over there while
the Vietnamese want to forget that and let bygones by bygones and
continue the future as friends, not enemies,'' Cloutier added.
   The Americans left Bangkok on Wednesday for home.
</TEXT>
