<HEAD>Bush Nominates An Undersecretary Of Treasury And Three Judges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush announced Wednesday that
he will nominate Robert R. Glauber as undersecretary of the
treasury, succeeding George D. Gould.
   Glauber, 49, is a consultant to the Treasury Department and
previously was chairman of the advanced management program at the
Harvard Business School.
   The White House announced the appointment during Bush's refueling
stop in Alaska enroute to his five-day, three-nation trip to Asia.
   The president also announced the nominations of three candidates
for federal judgeship:
   _ Ferdinand F. Fernandez of California to be a member of the U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals in the 9th circuit succeeding Warren J.
Ferguson. Fernandez has been a U.S. district judge for the central
district of California since 1985 and previously had been a
California state judge. He is 51.
   _ Pamela Ann Rymer to the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals for the
9th circuit succeeding Anthony M. Kennedy, who was elevated to the
Supreme Court by former President Reagan. Rymer has been a U.S.
district judge for the central district of California since 1983.
She is 48.
   _ Melinda Harmon of Texas to be U.S. district judge for the
southern district of Texas succeeding John D. Singleton Jr. Harmon,
who had been Singleton's law clerk from 1973 to 1975, has been a
Harris County district court judge in Texas since 1988 and
previously worked for 13 years as a lawyer for Exxon Co., USA. She
is 42.
