<FIRST>r i AM-Namibia     02-22 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Namibia,0438</SECOND>
<HEAD>Union Leader Says Namibians Wary of South African Intentions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Namibian union leader said
Wednesday his compatriots remain deeply suspicious of South African
intentions in the mineral rich territory, despite an independence
plan set to begin April 1.
   ``Namibians can smell their independence in the air,'' said Ben
Ulenga, general secretary of the powerful Mineworkers Union of
Namibia.
   But he added, ``given the past treachery of the (South African)
apartheid regime, Namibians are very cautious and vigilant.''
   South Africa, which has ruled Namibia for 74 years, is to begin
implementing a United Nations independence plan April 1 leading to
elections early in November.
   Officials of the South-West African People's Organization, the
guerrilla movement that has waged a 22-year war for independence,
says the South African government is actively working against an
election victory for them and will attempt to destabilize the
territory.
   ``Namibia's future is tied up with events in South Africa,'' said
Ulenga, a SWAPO member. ``If the apartheid regime is in power
indefinitely there will be very little chance for peace and
stability in Namibia.''
   Ulenga, who spent nine years in a South African prison for his
guerrilla activities, spoke at a meeting sponsored by Tribute
Magazine, a black-oriented monthly published in South Africa.
   SWAPO is favored to win the elections but has not detailed its
political and economic policies.
   SWAPO leader Sam Nujoma has said the organization favors a
socialist economy, but says he foresees a mixed economy initially
and does not intend to embark immediately on widespread
nationalization.
   The organization has not made clear whether a SWAPO government
would tolerate opposition parties, such as members of the current
transitional government.
   ``We can never forget about those who have been working in close
cooperation with the South Africans,'' said Ulenga. ``Reconciliation
does not mean condoning the crimes of apartheid, the crimes of
collaboration with apartheid,'' he said of the system of legalized
race discrimination.
   Mwilima Kupuzo, a black Namibian serving in the
soon-to-be-disbanded interim Parliament, said a SWAPO government
will seek to create ``a one-party state dedicated to socialism.''
   Kupuzo, in the audience while Ulenga spoke, accused SWAPO of
intimidating people into supporting the group.
   He represents the Democratic Turnhalle Alliance, a multiracial
coalition that favors a multiparty democracy and free enterprise.
The alliance holds the largest number of seats in the transitional
government, which was established by South Africa in 1985 as an
interim step to independence. SWAPO was banned so it could not
contest elections.
</TEXT>
