<FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-89 1912EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Mandela     02-22 0486</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mandela,0503</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Groups Say Police Attempting To Divide Blacks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anti-apartheid groups said
Wednesday police officials are exploiting the criminal investigation
of Winnie Mandela's bodyguards to create divisions in the black
community.
   Activists said police even offered to pay for the funeral of
14-year-old Stompie Seipei, who allegedly was beaten at Mrs.
Mandela's home in December.
   Seipei's decomposed body was found in January, and two of Mrs.
Mandela's bodyguards were charged with the killing Monday.
   ``Police are trying to divide the (black) community and blame
Stompie's death on frictions in black groups,'' said Lister Skosana
of the Tumahole Civic Association, an anti-government community
group from Seipei's hometown in central South Africa.
   The teen-ager's death is at the center of a growing scandal
surrounding the wife of jailed African National Congress leader
Nelson Mandela and a group of unofficial bodyguards calling
themselves the Mandela United soccer club. They lived at her home in
Soweto, the sprawling black township outside Johannesburg.
   One team member, Jabu Sithole, and self-described team coach
Jerry Richardson, have been charged with the killing of Seipei and
abductions and beatings of three other men.
   Anti-apartheid leaders last week accused Mandela United of waging
a ``reign of terror,'' renounced Mrs. Mandela, and urged their
followers not to associate with her. They accused her of
``complicity'' in the abductions and beatings.
   Joyce Seipei, the dead boy's mother, said at a news conference
that police offered to pay for his funeral but she declined to
accept.
   Police spokesman Col. Steve van Rooyen denied police offered to
pay.
   Police usually place tight restrictions on funerals of political
activists, limiting the number of mourners to 200 and the ceremony
to three hours.
   Skosana said police promised Mrs. Seipei there will be no
restrictions on her son's funeral Saturday. Van Rooyen said he was
unaware of any restrictions.
   Police usually are reluctant to comment on investigations and
court cases, but they repeatedly have volunteered information in the
events surrounding Mrs. Mandela.
   When they raided her house Sunday, they were accompanied by a
crew from the state television network. The video film showed Mrs.
Mandela in a nightgown and Richardson pulling on a pair of pants
after being awakened and arrested.
   Mrs. Seipei refused to comment about Mrs. Mandela, saying through
an interpreter, ``I have not met her and I don't want to meet her.''
   The African National Congress said it believes Mandela United was
``infiltrated by the enemy,'' a reference to the South African
government.
   The exiled guerrilla movement, based in Zambia, said it
previously had urged Mrs. Mandela to disband the group, but she had
refused.
   ``She was left open and vulnerable to committing mistakes which
the enemy exploited,'' the statement said.
   Police sometimes boast publicly about their ability to infiltrate
opposition groups. Van Rooyen declined to comment when asked if
informers were active in Mandela United.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
