<FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-89 2025EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-StarsandStripes     02-22 0777</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Stars and Stripes,780</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stars And Stripes Editors Seek Protection From Military Censorship</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Editors of the Pacific Stars and Stripes urged
Congress on Wednesday to give control of the newspaper to an
independent civilian editor, complaining it now is subjected to
censorship and ``browbeating'' by military officers.
   Defense department officials and officers contended there is no
censorship but acknowledged there is a widespread perception that it
exists. They said management changes are not needed.
   The comments came at a hearing of the House Armed Services
subcommittee on readiness at which representatives of the General
Accounting Office said an investigation had found that military
commanders and their representatives ``have attempted to influence
the reporting of news'' by both the Pacific and European editions of
Stars and Stripes.
   Rep. Earl Hutto, D-Fla., the subcommittee chairman, said he hoped
the hearing had ``cleared the air'' but said no immediate follow-up
action was planned.
   Martin N. Ferber, an official of GAO's international affairs
division, said that although the Pentagon intended to establish
guidelines to protect Stars and Stripes against censorship and
command influence, ``it has not accomplished this objective.''
   Ferber said the problem is rooted in the fact that Stars and
Stripes is a government publication, striving simultaneously to
provide news to U.S. military personnel stationed overseas while
also acting as an information organ for the armed forces.
   This dual purpose, he said, leads to conflict between civilian
journalists attempting to exercise constitutional rights of freedom
of the press and commanders charged with executing a military
mission.
   ``Different expectations by these groups are the primary reason
allegations of censorship exist,'' Ferber said.
   He said a survey conducted by the Society of Professional
Journalists established evidence that was ``conclusive at Stars and
Stripes in the Pacific but inconclusive for the European paper.''
   ``We found that the content of the news covered in Stars and
Stripes, compared to the wire services from which the news was
drawn, was consistent with the allegations we investigated,'' Ferber
said.
   The current Pacific editor of Stars and Stripes, and two former
editors all said censorship was routine at the newspaper and called
for civilian control of the editorial product.
   ``I had running skirmishes with various generals and admirals who
wanted to kill _ or plant _ stories in the news columns despite the
ill effect that such censorship and news management had on the
newspaper's already battered integrity and despite clear military
regulations that proscribed such abuse,'' said Timothy Hutchinson,
executive editor of Pacific Stars and Stripes from 1981 to 1984.
   ``This browbeating had been going on for decades in the Pacific
... and the results of it were painfully obvious,'' Hutchinson said.
``Staff morale was terrible, and circulation was plummeting.''
   Dewey W. Brackett, the current Pacific editor for the newspaper,
contended the situation has not changed,
   ``In my judgment Pacific Starts and Stripes today is a wilful
failure,'' he said. ``The paper's independence and integrity has
been purposely cast aside''
   ``The reason the paper is censored is sadly simple _ It disturbs
the generals and admirals,'' Brackett said. ``They do not like to
read negative stories about the U.S. government, the Defense
Department, the military installations and personnel under their
command or the governments of the Asian countries in which they are
located.''
   But Air Force Col. Edwin J. Montgomery, the current commander and
editor in chief of pacific Stars and Stripes, strongly disagreed.
   ``I have never had anyone _ no flag officer, no ambassador, no
bureaucrat, no one _ force the running or killing of a story, nor
has anyone dictated how a story should be edited or played,'' he
said.
   He said the paper's reputation is threatened by ``the largely
anonymous, but publicly trumpeted, allegations that the newspaper is
censored.''
   Montgomery said he believes that certain civilian employees
``have an agenda and the agenda is to remove all military influence
over the paper.''
   He also complained that the GAO report to Congress was
``seriously flawed'' and said differences between the European and
Pacific editions of Stars and Stripes or choices of what news
service copy was run were ``editorial judgment,'' affected by such
things as other stories competing for space.
   Two senior Pentagon officials also said the issue is editorial
judgement, not censorship.
   ``I fervently believe the system we have in place is sound,''
said William E. Hart, deputy assistant secretary of defense for
public affairs.
   ``Our paramount objective is to ensure a free flow of news and
information,'' said Jordan E. Rizer, director of the American Forces
Information Service. ``There has never been a calculated withholding
of news ever reported to me.''
</TEXT>
