<FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-89 1638EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Lithuania     02-22 0489</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Lithuania,0504</SECOND>
<HEAD>Party Attacks People's Front as Extremist</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party of Lithuania has accused a
grassroots political group of becoming too extreme in its opposition
to government policies, Pravda said Wednesday.
   The Communist Party newspaper, in a report on a Lithuanian party
meeting a day earlier, accused some members of the Sajudis movement
of moving from support for party reform to clear opposition.
   Sajudis, part of the People's Front political movement, was
formed in the Baltic republic last year to push for greater
cultural, political and economic autonomy from Moscow.
   ``At the plenum it was noted that the extreme position started to
dominate the activity of Sajudis, at least of several of its leaders
and members,'' Pravda said.
   ``Today the movement has started to distance itself from its
initial proposals. Consciously or unconsciously, a part of Sajudis
openly is nearing the slogans of the clearly anti-socialist
(Lithuanian Liberty) League, and the so-called Party of Lithuanian
Democrats,'' the report said, referring to groups that advocate
outright independence for Lithuania.
   Party leaders said ``the threat of a split on national grounds is
quite serious'' in the republic, Pravda said.
   The plenum signified an effort by the party to regain the control
that has been shaken by the sudden emergence of Sajudis and the
spread of nationalist sentiments.
   Under pressure from Sajudis, the small republic has declared
Lithuanian the official language and chosen the flag of the
independent republic that existed between the world wars as the
republic's official banner.
   However, authorities were able in November to thwart an effort to
declare the republic sovereign in all areas except foreign policy
and defense matters as did Estonia, another Baltic republic.
   The Kremlin has tried without success to cool the ethnic
sentiments in the Baltic republics and elsewhere in the country.
   Sajudis has been active in putting forward candidates for
multiple-candidate elections March 26 for a new nationwide congress
of people's deputies, sometimes at the expense of party-backed
candidates. Pravda said the Lithuanian party also criticized many of
its own members for sympathizing with the organization.
   The plenum sharply criticized some official publications and
Lithuanian radio and television for leaning toward Sajudis, and the
party's ideological department came under attack for its lack of
activity.
   Kremlin-led calls for consolidation of ethnic groups into a
single program supporting Moscow's policies ``remain only on paper
so far,'' Pravda said.
   The plenum was held on the same day that the republic's
government declared Lithuanian the official language, making
official an act passed by its legislature in October.
   A week ago, Lithuanian activists marked the anniversary of the
declaration of independence from revolutionary Russia in 1918 with
rallies. A year earlier, a tight police presence had prevented any
such demonstrations.
   Ethnic Lithuanians make up about 80 percent of the republic's 3.6
million people, the largest such indigenous population in any of the
three Baltic republics.
</TEXT>
