<FIRST>r w AM-VeteransBudget     02-22 0187</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Veterans Budget,190</SECOND>
<HEAD>Seek Increase in VA Budget</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Veterans Affairs Committee on
Wednesday called for a $1.3 billion increase in the Bush
administration's recommended budget for the new Department of
Veterans Affairs.
   The committee's recommendation to the House Budget Committee, 4.3
percent more than what Bush submitted, was approved 27-0.
   The bulk of the increase, $1.1 billion, would be devoted to
medical care, for which the president had sought $10.7 billion.
   Officials of the Veterans Administration, which gets upgraded to
department status next month, have said they will be $600 million
short for medical care in the current fiscal year, but the
administration has not sought a supplemental appropriation.
   The committee recommended a $520 million supplemental
appropriation, of which $432 million would be devoted to medical
care, for the current fiscal year ending Sept. 30.
   Rep. G.V. ``Sonny'' Montgomery, D-Miss., told the committee
before the vote, ``The Budget Committee must decided whether to add
$2.1 billion to NASA's budget ... should we proceed to build a space
laboratory when so many veterans health care facilities are in dire
need of repair?
