<FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-89 2030EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Honeybees     02-22 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Honeybees,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hardworking Honeybees Give A Boost To Farmers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The hard-working honeybee is worth at least
$9.7 billion to farmers, not to mention all that sweet stuff that is
so good on biscuits, a new study by Cornell University showed
Wednesday.
   Honeybees are used by the millions to pollinate major crops of
fruits, berries, vegetables, tree nuts, oilseeds and legumes. Their
keepers rent them out commercially, trucking the bees to crop areas.
   The study was prepared by Cornell for the National Honey Board,
which was authorized by Congress and established by the Agriculture
Department in 1986 to promote honey and honey research, all financed
through a levy on producers.
   About a million colonies of bees are involved in commercial crop
pollination, about a third of all U.S. managed colonies, the report
said. That is about double the number estimated in the early 1980s.
   ``To a significant degree, because of the hard work of the
honeybee we have abundant food supplies at reasonable prices,'' said
Dan Hall, manager of the National Honey Board, which is based in
Longmont, Colo.
   Commercial pollination ranges from blueberries and cranberries in
New England to apples in the Northwest and New York to almonds in
California and some citrus in Florida.
   Other major examples cited included alfalfa seed in the West,
melons in Texas, cucumbers in the Carolinas and Michigan, sunflowers
in Minnesota, and seeds for onions, carrots, celery and other
vegetables in many states.
   Frederick Hoff of USDA's Economic Research Service said that
``many consumers are unaware that honeybees are used to pollinate
foods they are dependent upon. He said the study shows that
pollination is ``even more important than we thought.''
   The Cornell study was based on 1985 information and showed that
the $9.7 billion in direct benefits represented the dollar value of
increased crop yields and quality as the result of honeybee crop
pollination.
   ``Crop quality improvements include larger and more uniform size,
desirable shape, uniform maturation date, and all result in higher
market value,'' the report said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
