<FIRST>r i AM-Hungary-Holiday     02-22 0380</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary-Holiday,0391</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nov. 7 Won't be a Red Letter Day in Hungary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nov. 7, the anniversary of the Bolshevik
Revolution in Russia, will no longer be a red-letter day in Hungary.
   Instead, Hungarians will celebrate March 15, the anniversary of
the 1848 anti-Austrian uprising, as a public holiday for the first
time this year, spokesman Gyoergy Marosan said Wednesday.
   The Council of ministers took the decision at a meeting
Wednesday, he said.
   The decision to stop marking the anniversary of the 1917
Bolshevik Revolution _ a holiday marked in each of the Soviet bloc
countries _ is indicative of the degree of independence Hungary has
acquired with its ambitious reform program.
   The March 15 anniversary has been marked by small unofficial
rallies since 1972. Since 1983, however, increasing numbers of
people have taken part, and last year, 10,000 people marched through
the streets calling for democracy, a free press and free elections.
   These are some of the same demands made by the leaders of the
1848 uprising to shake off the Hapsburg rule. Although it failed, it
had a long-term effect on the future relations of the
Austro-Hungarian monarchy, and in 1867, the Hungarians were given a
series of unprecedented privileges.
   Alternative groups have demanded for years that March 15 be
declared a national holiday as it bears strong national significance
for Hungarians.
   Official rallies also were conducted in the past with a
reenactment of the reading of a 12-point program for democracy
issued at the time. Hungarians wore the national colors on that day.
   In December, parliament agreed to make March 15 an official
public holiday. It will be celebrated as such this year for the
first time since the communists came to power in 1948.
   Last weekend, more than 15 independent groups rejected a call by
the Communist Party to stage joint celebrations, referring to
previous police force at past independent rallies, the state news
agency MTI reported.
   On Tuesday, Communist Party Central Committee Secretary Gyoergy
Fejti said he regretted the decision, but said he hoped a joint
celebration still could be arranged.
   ``For years we (the party leadership) were accused ... of
speaking with the arrogance of power,'' Fejti said. I would regret
it if the opposition would speak with another arrogance.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
