<DOCNO> AP890222-0165 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-89 2031EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-Space     02-22 0224</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Space,0230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japan Launches Scientific Satellite</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan successfully launched a research satellite
Wednesday from its space center at Tanegashima, authorities said.
   The launch went smoothly and the satellite, named EXOS-D, entered
its orbit as planned, said the official from the Institute of Space
and Astronautical Science.
   EXOS-D, the 12th scientific satellite launched by the
government-sponsored agency, will study the Earth's auroras and
their relationship to plasma particles emitted by the sun, she said.
   Auroras are luminous displays, usually seen around the north and
south poles, believed to be caused by collisions of charged
particles from the sun and oxygen and nitrogen atoms in the Earth's
atmosphere. The 660-pound satellite contains eight devices to study
and photograph auroras and plasma waves, the official said.
   The satellite's elliptical orbit is expected to range from 250
miles to 6,250 miles.
   Japan limits its rocket launches to only 90 days a year _ 45 days
in July and August and 45 days in January and February _ because of
protests from tuna fishermen in the area of the space center, off
Japan's southern main island of Kyushu. The fishermen say rocket
launches are dangerous.
   Japan entered the aerospace field late because of restrictions
imposed by U.S. occupation forces after World War II, but has
advanced quickly in recent years with a high success rate.
</TEXT>
