<SECOND>AM-Newspage Stocks,0238</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stocks Plunge As Inflation Concerns Swell</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices fell sharply Wednesday as signs of
accelerating inflation punctured the optimism that has fueled the
stock market's recent rally.
   Stocks suffered from a government report of a jump in consumer
prices and from a statement by Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan
Greenspan, who said he was disturbed by inflation's strength.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks skidded 42.50 to
2,283.93, its biggest drop since Nov. 11, when the widely-followed
index tumbled 47.66.
   Broader measures of stock activity also fell, and declining
issues outnumbered advancing ones by nearly 4 to 1 on the New York
Stock Exchange.
   The Labor Department said consumer prices rose at an annual rate
of 7.2 percent in January, propelled by higher costs for gasoline,
poultry, fish, eggs and tobacco.
   The report and Greenspan's remarks heightened concerns that the
Fed would push interest rates higher to try to hold down inflation.
   High short-term interest rates could drain money away from stocks
and into higher-yielding securities such as Treasury bills. In
addition, high rates might push the economy into a recession that
would be bad for stocks.
   The stock market had rallied since late last year, returning for
the first time to the levels it held before the October 1987 crash.
Analysts said a sense of optimism had returned to Wall Street.
