<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Ukraine     02-22 0476</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Ukraine,0487</SECOND>
<HEAD>Protesters Gather in Kiev, Gorbachev Visits Coal Region</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KIEV, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Protesters on Wednesday displayed an
eight-foot rendition of a ballot with the names of candidates
crossed out and criticized the government's failure to allow
multiple-candidate elections.
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev meanwhile pushed reforms in Soviet
coal country.
   The demonstration by about 500 people in the Ukrainian capital,
the fourth in four nights, was held under a special decree allowing
spontaneous meetings concerning the March 26 elections that will
choose members of a newly formed Parliament.
   Demonstrations normally require government permission, and that
rarely has been forthcoming in the Ukraine. The republic's Communist
Party leader, Vladimir V. Shcherbitsky, is the only holdover on the
ruling party Politburo from the era of Leonid I. Brezhnev and
tolerates little dissident.
   Shcherbitsky's name and those of other Ukranian officials were
crossed out on the protesters' banner resembling a ballot. Another
poster read: ``Fear! Why is there only one candidate on the ballot?''
   Oles Shevchenko, head of the Ukrainian group monitoring
compliance with the Helsinki human rights accords, said virtually
all Ukrainian leaders are running unopposed and voters seeking an
alternative will only be able to cross out their names. The party
had promised that the March 26 elections will offer more than one
candidate for seats in the Congress of People's Deputies.
   Competing demonstrators at Wednesday's meeting, whom activists
claimed were government agents, held up a banner charging,
``Nationalism puts the brakes on perestroika,'' Gorbachev's policy
of political and economic reform. The sign was printed in Ukrainian
letters but slipped into Russian in the middle.
   Shevchenko said activists were encouraged by Gorbachev's
statements to Kiev residents broadcast on television Monday night,
suggesting workers throw out bosses who do not support reforms.
   Gorbachev, in the coal-mining center of Donetsk in the eastern
Ukraine on Wednesday, told a group of workers ``those who are trying
to put a stick through the spokes of perestroika, or to puncture the
tire, and let the air out, and reduce the movement of perestroika,
are the most dangerous people.''
   Donetsk is just south of Dnepropetrovsk, the city that was the
power base of Brezhnev, who died in 1982 and now is blamed for
fostering a period of economic and social stagnation and permitting
wide-spread corruption.
   Gorbachev's visit to Donetsk on the third day of his stay in the
Ukraine took up 90 minutes of the nightly news program ``Vremya,''
which normally is only a 45-minute program. The news program showed
Gorbachev talking with residents of the city, visiting factories and
holding a session with a group of miners.
   Workers complained about the inattentiveness of some local
officials and told the Soviet president that the area needs more
modern mining equipment to dig deeper into its coal veins. Gorbachev
preached economic reform, technical renewal and self-reliance.
</TEXT>
