<FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-89 2041EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-WildlifePolitics     02-22 0569</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wildlife Politics,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Allegations Of Fish And Wildlife Service Mismanagement Surface At
Hearing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LES BLUMENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service officials have
paid more attention to politics than to protecting the nation's
natural resources, a House subcommittee chairman said Wednesday in
pledging that Congress will fully investigate allegations of
mismanagement at the agency.
   Rep. Gerry Studds, D-Mass., made the comments at a hearing a day
after the General Accounting Office said top FWS officials pressured
biologists in the agency's Northwest regional office into
``sanitizing'' a study which originally warned the spotted owl was
threatened by extinction.
   ``We are well aware that serious allegations have been made in
recent months about the management of the Fish and Wildlife
Service,'' said Studds.
   Frank Dunkle, director of the FWS, told Studds the charges are
``unfounded, inconsequential and you are on a witch hunt,'' he said.
   Among the allegations that Studds said the GAO and the staff of
the Merchant Marine and Fisheries subcommittee on fisheries,
wildlife conservation and environment have or would investigate were:
   _ Political pressures may have influenced the agency's decision
not to list the spotted owl as an endangered species.
   _ The regional director in the agency's Portland, Ore., office
was reassigned for essentially political reasons and Congress was
misled about the reasons for the reassignment.
   _ FWS officials in the Fairbanks, Ala., office were ordered by
Washington-based officials to destroy files on a plan which called
for building a causeway to carry oil drilling equipment to an
offshore site.
   _ Proper procedures were not followed when the agency considered
the environmental impacts of the Two Forks Dam project in Colorado.
   _ Agency personnel have been ordered to carry out directives on
verbal rather than written instructions, and employees in at least
one office were required to sign a pledge that they would not even
keep a memo on file without approval.
   Dunkle refused to answer a string of questions from Studds about
whether political concerns should be allowed to take precedence over
scientific evidence or legal requirements, whether agency personnel
should be transferred because they don't agree with the ``policy
preferences'' of their superiors and whether an open investigation
of the allegations would be ``beneficial.''
   ``I will respond in writing,'' said Dunkle. ``I'm not sure what
you are getting at.''
   ``I'm surprised at your defensiveness,'' said Studds.
   ``My job is to carry out the laws set forth by Congress and I
have done just that,'' said Dunkle.
   After the hearing, Dunkle denied that he had applied any
political pressure on agency officials who eventually decided not to
classify the spotted owl as an endangered species.
   Dunkle told reporters he had not seen the report from GAO,
Congress' investigative arm, and declined comment.
   GAO said FWS officials intentionally ignored scientific evidence
and ordered changes in the study prepared by biologists in the
agency's Pacific Northwest regional office.
   The Fish and Wildlife Service, a Department of Interior Agency,
is required to consider only ``biological factors'' in deciding what
species are designated for protection as threatened or endangered.
   The agency concluded in December 1987 that the owl, which lives
only in ancient timber in Oregon, Washington and northern
California, was not endangered.
   The timber industry in the Northwest has vehemently opposed any
effort to name the owl a threatened or endangered species, fearing
that such a move would disrupt logging in public forests.
</TEXT>
