<DOCNO> AP890222-0170 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-89 2042EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Pell-PeacePlan     02-22 0300</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pell-Peace Plan,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Foreign Relations Chairman Asks Bush to Back Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations
Committee called on the Bush administration on Wednesday to throw
its weight behind the peace plan offered last week by Central
America's five presidents.
   ``I view these developments as encouraging and for that reason am
dismayed by the unenthusiastic reaction of the administration this
far,'' said Sen. Claiborne Pell, D-R.I. ``We should be providing a
fair breeze behind this initiative to make it work.''
   In the agreement, the Sandinista government of Nicaragua said it
would hold free elections by February 1990 and release some 3,000
political prisoners if bases used by Contra resistance fighters
inside Honduras are dismantled.
   Other signers included the presidents of Honduras, Costa Rica,
Guatemala and El Salvador.
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III told the House Foreign
Affairs Committee on Tuesday that while the agreement could provide
a good basis for bringing peace and democracy to Nicaragua, it lacks
deadlines and procedures to assure Sandinista compliance.
   He said the Sandinistas have made similar promises in the past
and have broken them each time.
   ``There are risks involved,'' Pell told the Senate. ``There are
no guarantees that the Sandinistas will comply with the accord. They
are Marxists who have not given up their communist principles. But
the economic realities they face provide significant pressure.''
   ``The United States should make known its support for this plan
to give it the best possible chance of working,'' Pell said. ``If it
fails, we should not give cause for that failure to be laid at our
door.''
   Pell said the United States should restructure aid to the Contras
in ways supporting the accord, including providing funds to resettle
the Contras and their families in Nicaragua or other countries.

</TEXT>
