<FIRST>u w AM-Sullivan     02-22 0500</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sullivan,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sullivan Prepared to Tell Congress He Misspoke on Abortion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dr. Louis Sullivan will tell Congress at his
confirmation hearing that he ``misspoke'' his position on abortion
both in a newspaper interview and to a senator, a source close to
the Health and Human Services secretary-designate said Wednesday.
   In his opening statement to the Senate Finance Committee on
Thursday, he will say he misrepresented his views when he said he
supported women's right to abortion and the Supreme Court decision
that legalized abortion, said the source, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   ``He'll say he misspoke,'' the source said. ``He's going to say
his personal view, his public view is that he's against abortion,''
with the same exceptions that President Bush endorses: in cases if
rape, incest and danger to the life of the mother.
   Finance Committee sources said they expect the confirmation
hearing to go smoothly and that panel members will vote their
approval following the hearing.
   Sources close to Sullivan, who will step down as president of the
Morehouse School of Medicine in Atlanta to join Bush's Cabinet, say
the nominee initially was unprepared for the heat that could be
generated by the emotion-packed issue of abortion.
   Sullivan riled abortion opponents with remarks he made in an
interview with an Atlanta newspaper shortly after his nomination and
again when Sen. Bob Packwood, R-Ore., reported the nominee had told
him he favored retaining the Supreme Court's Roe vs. Wade decision.
   His remarks prompted right-to-life groups to demand assurances
from the Bush administration that Sullivan's policies at the HHS
would follow those of the president on abortion.
   Sullivan's hearing had been scheduled for earlier this month but
was put off at the request of the White House because an FBI
background investigation was still under way and the nominee had not
finished his financial disclosure report.
   Two weeks ago, Sullivan put financial conflict of interest
concerns to rest when he decided to forfeit nearly $300,000 in
severance pay he could have received if he had cut his ties to the
medical school he founded.
   He was prepared to do that, according to a senior administration
official, but was concerned when news reports raised questions about
the arrangement and decided instead to forgo the money and instead
take an unpaid leave of absence.
   Sullivan is expected to be questioned about that decision, as
well as part of the FBI investigation that focused on his connection
to a former Georgia county official convicted of extortion.
   Unrelated to his extortion conviction, Reginald Eaves was paid
more than $34,000 over four years as a part-time lecturer at
Morehouse while he used his seat on the Fulton County commission to
promote issues that benefited the medical school. He gave only two
lectures.
   Sullivan will tell Congress he ``made a mistake'' by hiring
Eaves, which is what he said publicly when the arrangement came to
light last summer, according to a source close to the nominee.
</TEXT>
