<FIRST>r w AM-LivestockOutlook     02-22 0165</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Livestock Outlook,150</SECOND>
<HEAD>Producers At Last Expanding Cattle Herds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department said Wednesday that
the long-time slide in the U.S. cattle inventory has ended and that
producers are beginning to expand their herds.
   According to a USDA report issued Feb. 8, the nation's cattle
inventory as of Jan. 1 was virtually the same as it had been a year
earlier. Many private analysts had been saying the herd numbers
would show another significant decline.
   ``This expansion dramatically changes the beef outlook for 1989
and beyond,'' the department's Economic Research Service said.
``Beef cows number 2 percent above a year earlier, and beef
replacement heifers were up 5 percent.''
   Moreover, the report noted that the Jan. 1 figures showed last
year's calf crop was 672,000 head larger than had been projected
last summer.
   Including dairy animals, the U.S. herd of cattle and calves
totaled a 28-yer low of 99,484,000 head on Jan. 1, down only 40,000
head from a year ago.
</TEXT>
