<FIRST>r w AM-Senate-Armenia     02-22 0197</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Senate-Armenia,180</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Proposes Armenian Rebuilding Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate called on the Bush administration
Wednesday to consider organizing an international long-term
reconstruction effort for those areas of Soviet Armenia devastated
by last December's earthquake.
   It adopted a resolution calling on Secretary of State James A.
Baker III to submit by April 1 a report spelling out what the United
States, perhaps in conjunction with private efforts, could do to
help Armenia rebuild.
   Sen. Paul Simon, D-Ill., a sponsor of the resolution, said it is
obvious Armenia's needs go beyond the $106 million in international
public and private relief that has been provided since the
earthquake struck last Dec. 7.
   Simon said, ``We cannot lose sight of the stark reality of
Armenia: 500,000 homeless; 25,000 dead; 130,000 injured.''
   Sen. Claiborne Pell, D-R.I., chairman of the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee, said reconstruction in Armenia will cost an
estimated $13 billion.
   ``This legislation asks the administration to explore the idea of
establishing a joint public-private task force to participate in an
international relief effort,'' Pell said.
   ``The international community may be able to find ways to help
rebuild the collapsed towns throughout Soviet Armenia,'' he said.
</TEXT>
