<FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-89 1741EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Salvador     02-22 0757</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador,0785</SECOND>
<HEAD>Election Postponement, and Chance for Peace, Elusive as Ever</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Postponing the March 19
presidential election, proposed by the rebels as a cornerstone of
lasting peace, appeared no more likely Wednesday than before the
rebels and delegates of political parties met in Mexico.
   The proposal, made by the leftist guerrillas on Jan. 24, has been
the subject of intense debate ever since. They presented a revised
proposal Monday and Tuesday, and the political parties said they
would ask the government to consider it.
   But as the debate drags on, election time draws closer and the
level of violence in this small Central American country increases.
   At a news conference in Mexico City, the rebel Farabundo Marti
National Liberation Front said again its offer is good only for a
limited time. Guerrilla commander Roberto Roca said if the
government refused to talk, it will ``bear the blame for
continuation of the war.''
   The war began in 1980 and has killed 70,000 people, mostly
civilians.
   Some politicians described the talks as more a means of keeping
up appearances and avoiding blame for their failure than a serious
consideration of the rebel overture.
   Asked if any better chance existed now for postponing the
elections, Hector Silva, a leader of the leftist Democratic
Convergence, replied simply, ``No.''
   The Farabundo Marti told the politicians it would accept a vote
as early as July and would observe a cease-fire during a four-month
campaign.
   That would still put the election past the June 1 date on which
the constitution calls for President Jose Napoleon Duarte to step
down.
   The insurgents also said the armed forces, now at 56,000 men,
would have to be cut to 12,000 _ their size a decade ago.
   A high-ranking government official said the insurgents softened
their position by accepting an earlier date for elections than
proposed earlier, but hardened it with the stipulation on troop
reducion.
   ``One (bad) element of the new position is enough to sink it,''
he said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The U.S.-supplied and tutored armed forces opposed the proposal
from the start.
   ``While millions of Salvadorans clamor for peace and reject
violence, death and destruction, the FMLN, represented in Mexico by
four terrorist chiefs, is launching the most sinister strategic
plans of Marxism-Leninism in order to obtain power by force of
arms,'' the Defense Ministry said in a communique issued Wednesday.
   The armed forces and the rightist Republican National Alliance,
or Arena, consider the guerrilla proposal a ploy. Arena is favored
to win next month's election and has little motivation to accept a
delay.
   The executive branch and the U.S. Embassy also expressed doubts
about rebel sincerity.
   The guerrillas said the war will escalate if their proposal is
rejected and accused political parties of hiding behind the
constitution to avoid serious discussion.
   Party leaders agreed in Mexico to continue discussing the plan
once back in San Salvador and said they would press Duarte's
government to discuss the new rebel offer directly with its authors.
   Duarte four weeks ago said resolution of the matter was up to the
political parties.
   Asked Wednesday if the parties had thrown the ball back to the
government, the government official said, ``It's not so much that we
gave them the ball. We loaned it to them to play with for a while.''
   Guerrilla leader Shafick Handal said the last time the Farabundo
Marti sat down with Duarte, he came to the negotiations empty-handed.
   ``They didn't propose a thing,'' Handal said.
   Legislator Sigifredo Ochoa, a top Arena leader, told local Radio
YSU on Wednesday: ``There in Mexico everyone except us was trying to
see what advantage they could pull out of this. We are the only ones
who have been clear in our position from the beginning.''
   Asked about possible reduction of government troop strength,
Ochoa, a retired colonel, said, ``I'm against it. It changes the
essence of the original proposal.''
   Democratic Convergence leader Silva told The Associated Press
that Arena was rejecting the proposal without spelling out its
position.
   ``It is their way of saying `No' while paying the lowest price
politically,'' he said.
   The rebels meanwhile attacked two major army bases on Tuesday,
killing four soldiers and three civilians.
   Guerrilla sabotage left 60 percent of this Massachusetts-sized
country without electricity Wednesday. Roca said the guerrillas
don't intend to stop fighting while they await a decision on their
proposal.
   ``The operations of the (Salvadoran) army continue. For our part,
so will ours,'' said Roca.
</TEXT>
