<FIRST>u i AM-ShipDisaster     02-22 0479</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ship Disaster,0496</SECOND>
<HEAD>Freighter Crew Lost In Atlantic Storm</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Panamanian-registered freighter hauling a load of
salt to Iceland capsized and sank in violent seas on Wednesday, and
all 17 crew members died, the coast guard said.
   Ships, rescue planes and helicopters struggled in vain to aid the
Japanese-owned, 2,625-ton Sescil Angola, which sank 350 miles west
of Scotland.
   Squadron Leader Bob Conolly of the Royal Air Force said crew
members may have died because they waited too long to abandon ship.
   Later Wednesday, Clyde Coast Guard on Scotland's west coast said
a Danish fishing boat in the same area also sent a distress call.
Another Danish fishing vessel responded and was escorting it to
Stornoway in the Outer Hebrides.
   The Nunarsuit from Godthab, Greenland, with nine crew, ``had its
bridge windows smashed in by huge waves,'' said a Coast Guard
spokesman, who by custom was unidentified.
   ``But another Danish fishing boat from the same harbor, the
Narssalik, got there and is steaming with it to Stornoway. There are
no casualties,'' he said.
   Planes and ships searched all day for survivors from the Sescil
Angola, which was carrying salt from Spain to Iceland.
   When the search was called off at nightfall, five bodies had been
recovered and six more sighted, rescue services said.
   The freighter had reported water in two holds, and the last
message from the ship's unidentified captain said, ``There is great
danger. Helicopters please hurry.''
   Conolly, captain of a Nimrod reconnaissance aircraft that was
first on the scene, advised the crew to launch their lifeboat
immediately.
   ``The crew did not want to abandon ship. They wanted to come off
by helicopter. They held on too long and the boat turned over,'' he
said.
   But he added that weather conditions were so severe that even if
the crew had abandoned ship earlier, their chances of survival might
have been slim.
   The rescue effort involved Royal Air Force teams from Scotland,
northern England and Wales and U.S. helicopters from Iceland.
   Scottish coast guard officer John Griffiths at Greenock said the
freighter sent out its first distress call shortly after midnight,
and the first aircraft to enter the search took off 12 minutes later
from Kinloss in northern Scotland.
   It arrived over the Sescil Angola at 2 a.m. and dropped life
rafts, two of which were shredded by the wind and blown away.
   The coast guard said the freighter sank at 7:25 a.m.
   The first Royal Air Force Sea King helicopter arrived two hours
later. Winchman Bob Griffths said he was lowered to just above the
tops of the waves to inspect the life rafts.
   ``No one could have survived,'' he said.
   ``The conditions were horrendous. The life rafts were tied
together in pairs and were shooting up and down on 50-foot waves.
There were broken pieces of ship all over the place,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
