<FIRST>r w AM-Crops-Weather     02-22 0167</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Crops-Weather,150</SECOND>
<HEAD>Conditions Improving for Winter Wheat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain and snow have helped improve the soil
conditions for winter wheat but parts of the Great Plains grain area
still needs moisture, the government's Joint Agricultural Weather
Facility said Wednesday.
   Rain during the week of Feb. 13-19 helped winter wheat in
Oklahoma and parts of Texas, the facility said in its weekly report.
In Kansas, the crop needed snow cover and moisture.
   ``Snow cover was mostly adequate in the northern plains,'' the
report said. ``Additional snow improved cold weather protection in
Michgan; winter wheat was mostly good to fair in Illinois.''
   Freeze damage to grain planted last fall in Washington was still
unknown but was expected to be substantial in some areas, the report
said. Wind damage was light in Colorado and Montana, although
moisture was needed in Colorado to prevent wind erosion to winter
wheat.
   The facility is operated by the Agriculture and Commerce
departments to provide weekly updates on weather and crop conditions.
</TEXT>
