<FIRST>r w AM-LibyansArrested     02-22 0441</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Libyans Arrested,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>FBI Arrests Five in Scheme to Fund Libyan Anti-American Demonstrations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal agents arrested five people on
Wednesday as part of an investigation into a scheme to divert Libyan
student funds to help pay for anti-American demonstrations in the
United States and conferences of American dissidents in the African
nation.
   Special Agent-In-Charge W. Douglas Gow of the FBI's Washington
field office said the charges against the defendants included
conspiracy, wire fraud, credit card fraud and aiding and abetting.
   Their arrests followed by seven months the arrests of seven
others.
   The five new suspects were involved in the overall scheme, but
FBI spokeswoman Bobbi Wallace said she could not comment further
because another suspect remained at large.
   U.S. Attorney Henry Hudson, who is handling the case, was
unavailable for comment Wednesday.
   The five were indicted Feb. 14 by a federal grand jury in
Alexandria, Va., the FBI said.
   They were scheduled for arraignment in U.S. District Court in
Alexandria on Friday, Ms. Wallace said.
   They were identified as Abdussalam Deghaies, 32, of Aurora, Ill.;
Issa Hammad, 37, of Manassas, Va.; Jafar Jafari, 37, of Bethesda,
Md.; Omar Al-Madani, 31, who lives in the northern Virginia area;
and Maisoun Benmohmed, 26, who most recently resided in Ottawa,
Canada.
   Mrs. Benmohmed is the wife of Mousa Hawamda, who was arrested in
July along with six members of the Peoples Committee for Libyan
Students for diverting the funds.
   The six committee members pleaded guilty before a federal judge
in October. Five of them were deported after paying $20,000 in
fines. A sixth, Saleh Al-Rajhi is serving a five-year prison term.
   Hawamda fled the United States in September and is a fugitive,
Gow said.
   According to prosecutors, the scheme involved money laundering
and violations of the 1986 Libyan sanctions regulations that
prohibit travel to and transactions with Libya. The original
suspects worked through a Libyan students' organization to recruit
and fund members of selected American groups and to gather
intelligence information. The money allegedly was funneled through a
Washington travel agency operated by Hawamda.
   Al-Rajhi obtained personal data on U.S. government employees to
Libya for ``possible retaliation'' for the 1986 bombing raid on
Libya, authorities said. Hudson has said Hawamda, a Libyan
intelligence operative, had participated in a plot to assassinate a
high-level U.S. official, who administration sources later
identified as former White House aide Oliver L. North. North had
helped organize the raid.
   Deghaies was taken into custody in Chicago, while Hammad was
arrested in Manassas, Va., Jafari in Baltimore, Al-Madani in
Arlington, Va., and Mrs. Benmohmed in Alexandria, Va., the FBI said.
</TEXT>
