<FIRST>r w AM-EPA-Superfund     02-22 0848</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-EPA-Superfund,870</SECOND>
<HEAD>Score EPA Contract</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Environmental Protection Agency rewarded a
Superfund site-inspection contractor for sub-par work, paid contract
employees to attend conferences, and kept some inspection experts
confined to office work for nearly a year, according to an EPA
inspector general's report obtained Wednesday.
   Some contract employees were so frustrated with their inability
to make on-site inspections that they held mock exercises in a yard
near their office in an effort to maintain proficiency in sampling
hazardous materials, the report said.
   The inspector general also cited an EPA official who was so upset
at paying for contract workers to attend conferences, that he wrote
that the practice ``might not hold up too well under any type of
scrutiny _ congressional, inspector general, or otherwise.''
   The contract cited by the inspector general is between EPA and
NUS Corp. of Gaithersburg, Md. The company was hired to provide
field inspection teams to gather information on hazardous waste
cleanup sites in the agency's regions I through IV, headquartered
respectively in Boston, New York City, Philadelphia and Atlanta.
   The inspector general's report, obtained by The Associated Press,
will be reviewed at a hearing Thursday by the House Post Office and
Civil Service Committee's civil service subcommittee, headed by Rep.
Gerry Sikorski, D-Minn.
   EPA inspector general John C. Martin estimated the five-year
contract will cost $125 million by its finish.
   Another inspector general's report to be reviewed by the
subcommittee criticized the Philadelphia-based Region III management
of EPA's emergency Superfund response program. The program uses
contract employees to respond to environmental emergencies.
   The report found that members of a team of groundwater
hydrologists, toxicologists, chemists, and environmental scientists
often were used as file clerks.
   A geologist who charged 676 hours of his time to administrative
support told the inspector general he used the time to file reports,
answer telephones, update lists and maintain charts.
   The inspector general's reports included comments from the EPA,
which defended its actions.
   Regarding the NUS contract, the agency said the audit covered
only the first 13 months of a five-year contract, and failed to list
``major accomplishments'' of the site inspection program that
occurred near the end of the first year.
   ``The language depicting agency management as deficient is overly
strong and inappropriate,'' the EPA said.
   The EPA also disagreed with the emergency response team report,
emphasizing that maintaining good records is within the contract's
scope of work.
   But the agency said that to avoid the appearance of wasteful
work, the clerical tasks will now be handled by personnel from the
American Association of Retired Persons.
   At NUS, the company's vice president for administration, Donald
Couchman, said, ``We regard that (the report) as an internal review
of EPA management and we don't consider it appropriate comment at
this time.''
   The nation's Superfund program is designed to clean up hazardous
waste sites. More than 30,000 potential sites have been identified,
with 1,175 designated for a national priority cleanup list. Remedial
action has been completed at 48 sites, with some work underway at
more than half the priority sites, according to EPA.
   NUS was hired to provide field inspection teams at the potential
sites, ``the federal government's primary investigative capability
within the Superfund program,'' according to the inspector general's
report. The firm handles regions I through IV while another
contractor provides the same services for regions V through X.
   The contractor provides preliminary assessments, site
inspections, special studies and enforcement support, among other
services.
   The inspector general said Boston-based Region I, in December
1986, caused severe morale problems at NUS by ordering personnel not
to perform traditional site inspection visits, but to gather data
from state agency files _ or from consultants working for the
parties potentially responsible for the hazardous waste.
   Only a month after coming on board, NUS ``employee morale was
affected since almost all ... activity was office work,'' the report
said. ``A series of mock field exercises were conducted outside the
... office to maintain SI (site inspection) expertise.''
   This led to transfers and resignations by 41 percent of the
professional contractor staff in Region I, while ``performance
declined at the time of the resignations and transfers,'' the
inspector general's report said. The order against on-site
inspections lasted for 10 months.
   The report said EPA was ``too lenient'' in evaluating NUS
performance, and in giving the company ``award fees'' based on
performance.
   One unit of contract employees ``received laudatory ratings and
award fees of over $90,000 despite the fact that the FIT (field
inspection team) charged over half its time to support tasks, did
not perform field work, and without the region's knowledge NUS
transferred a large segment of the ... team to work on a state
contract,'' the report said.
   One EPA official had these description of NUS work: ``poorly
written...technically inaccurate...less than satisfactory...from
poor to pathetic.''
   At ``the number one Superfund site in the country,'' the Lipari
Landfill in Pitman, N.J., the EPA paid a nominal award fee even
though an EPA official was sharply critical of the company's work,
the report said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
