<FIRST>u i AM-Czechoslovakia 1stLd-Writethru a0705 02-22 0571</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czechoslovakia, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0705,0587</SECOND>
<HEAD>Human Rights Leader Arrested In Continuing Crackdown on Dissent</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with more quotes, details. EDITS
to TRIM. No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a continuing crackdown on
dissent, authorities on Wednesday convicted and sentenced seven
dissidents to up to a year for their part in a banned demonstration.
   The rulings came one day after playwright Vaclav Havel was
sentenced to nine months in jail for his role in the rallies that
commemorated a student who fatally burned himself to protest the
1968 Soviet-led invasion.
   Authorities on Wednesday also arrested and charged the spokesman
of the Charter 77 independent human rights group with inciting
rebellion and damaging Czechoslovakia's image, a dissident said.
   The presiding judge at the two-day trial sentenced dissidents Ota
Veverka, founder of the recently formed John Lennon Peace Club, to
one year in jail and Jana Petrova to nine months.
   Charter 77 activist David Nemec was given a six-month suspended
sentence and Jana Sternova, also a Charter activist, was given four
months suspended. The others received two-month suspended sentences.
   Nemec, Charter spokesman Alexander Vondra, Petr Placak of the
youth group Czech children and Stanislav Penc of the John Lennon
Peace Club, were fined between $200 and $400.
   Petrova, who had been jailed since Jan. 16, cried when she heard
the sentences.
   Veverka charged that Judge Antonin Tesik influenced witnesses
``by putting words in their mouths.''
   At least 12 witnesses had been heard at the trial, all but one
uniformed or plainclothes police.
   ``We are designated the so-called opposition by the (state)
media. A truly democratic state does not need to be afraid of the
opposition,'' Veverka said.
   Wednesday's convictions came amid a chorus of condemnations
Wednesday from Western and some East bloc countries over Havel's
conviction. The works of Havel, a founder of Charter 77 and
Czechoslovakia's best-known dissident, are banned in his country.
   In Washington, State Department spokesman Charles Redman called
the trial and sentence ``bitter testimony to the lack of respect for
fundamental human rights in Czechoslovakia.''
   In France, President Francois Mitterrand demanded the conviction
be canceled. The French Communist Party called it ``inadmissible''
and demanded Havel's immediate release.
   Britain sought an ``urgent explanation,'' Finnish writers
denounced the verdict and a Polish newspaper said a Warsaw theater
plans to stage two Havel plays.
   Thomas Hradilek, a Charter 77 spokesman, was detained in his
hometown of Lipnik nad Becvou, 180 miles east of Prague, and charged
with inciting rebellion and damaging Czechoslovakia's image abroad,
said Anna Sabatova, a fellow activist.
   She told Western journalists that Hradilek, 43, was interrogated
by a judge in the city of Ostrava for two hours and then released
pending a trial. The offenses could jail him up to five years, she
said.
   The charges were based on two letters Hradilek wrote last month
to Communist Party leader Milos Jakes and President Gustav Husak
protesting the police violence used to break up peaceful gatherings
in Prague in January. Radio stations broadcast the letters into
Czechoslovakia.
   Havel and the seven others were convicted on charges of inciting
people to attend the January rally and of obstructing police
officers by ignoring calls to leave downtown Wenceslas Square.
   The dissidents went there Jan. 16 to lay flowers in memory of Jan
Palach, who burned himself alive 20 years earlier to protest the
death of reform after the Soviet-led 1968 invasion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
