<FIRST>u i AM-Poland     02-22 0455</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland,0470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Walesa Appeals For Unity Among Textile Workers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LODZ, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa appealed for
unity Wednesday when he addressed 7,000 supporters at the union's
first legal rally in this central textile center in seven years.
   Behind the scenes, Walesa launched an attempt to patch up a
conflict that split Lodz Solidarity leaders into rival factions.
   Standing in front of a huge Solidarity sign in a hall under the
grandstands of a football stadium, Walesa spoke for 10 minutes, then
spent more than an hour answering questions about the historic talks
that the opposition began with the government Feb. 6.
   ``If the round table fails we will have great fighting, great
strikes and still bigger inflation,'' he said.
   Although Solidarity has not yet been legalized again, the rally
had permission from local authorities.
   Police posted near the entrances did not interfere as supporters
with Solidarity banners lined up to enter the stadium gates, which
were supervised by volunteers wearing red-and-white union armbands.
   Solidarity, the first independent union movement in the Soviet
bloc, was founded in 1980 and outlawed after the 1981 imposition of
martial law.
   For the past two weeks, Walesa has traveled Poland to explain to
the union's rank-and-file his decision to enter into the discussions
and appealing for time to let the talks produce results.
   ``People are being restrained only because of the round table,''
said Zenon Kuchler, a textile workers and veteran Solidarity
activist. ``If not they would be striking. Everyone has a stomach.
We have to eat.''
   Spectators, who came from the textile mills and clothing
factories scattered throughout the city and suburbs, seemed amazed
at the sight of the cavernous hall being used again for an official
Solidarity meeting.
   ``This is a second coming,'' said Kuchler. ``There was a birth
and now a rebirth.''
   Walesa told the crowd: ``Poland belongs to all of us. The problem
is too serious to try and win something as the party, as the
security forces, as Slowik's (the local Solidarity leader) group or
Walesa's group.''
   He was referring to Lodz Solidarity leader Andrzej Slowik's past
criticism of Walesa's leadership, including a 1987 decision to use
union funds given by the U.S. Congress to fund a health commission
that has purchased ambulances for public use.
   ``Let's do something so that our factories are not political.
They should be places where we come to work hard and where we are
paid well,'' Walesa said. ``We are not more stupid or worse than the
rest of Europe. We are simply badly governed.''
   Gesturing and mixing humor with serious arguments, Walesa charmed
the crowd and was frequently interrupted by applause. One questioner
suggested he run for president.
</TEXT>
