<FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-89 2117EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-NorthTrial-Leaks     02-22 0568</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-North Trial-Leaks,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-North Trial</HEAD>
<HEAD>Hamilton Defends Panel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former chairman of the House intelligence
committee resisted attempts by Oliver L. North's chief lawyer
Wednesday to prove that ``Congress leaked like a sieve'' and
couldn't be trusted with secrets.
   Rep. Lee Hamilton, D-Ind., the first prosecution witness against
the fired National Security Council aide, firmly defended the House
Permanent Select Committee on Intelligence's record of protecting
some of the nation's most closely guarded secrets.
   ``From 1984, 1985 and 1986 leaks occurred on Capital Hill as a
result of members and staff members who provided information,'' said
North's chief defense attorney Brendan V. Sullivan Jr.
   ``(The late CIA) Director (William) Casey told me he didn't know
a single leak from the House intelligence committee,'' Hamilton
replied. ``I will not deny leaks, but neither can I prove any such
leaks.''
   Sullivan is trying to prove that North, who is charged with lying
to Congress about his role in the Iran-Contra affair, had a
well-founded fear of telling lawmakers the truth about covert
operations.
   In his opening statement Tuesday, Sullivan told jurors that ``it
was the perception of the National Security Council and the
president of the United States that the Congress of the United
States leaked like a sieve.''
   And Sullivan tried to make the same point during lengthy
cross-examination of Hamilton, who chaired the intelligence panel
when it questioned North and then-national security adviser Robert
McFarlane about news reports in 1985 and 1986 about covert U.S.
support of the Nicaraguan Contras despite a congressional ban.
   Hamilton acknowledged that selective leaking of classified
information is a game played by the powerful people in Washington to
influence policy.
   ``Information in this town is power,'' Hamilton said. ``If you
control the flow of information, you can profoundly affect the
public policy process. If information that is classified is released
it can somehow impact on public policy.''
   But Hamilton denied a suggestion by Sullivan that he threatened
in a 1985 letter to then-Secretary of State George Shultz to leak
information about a secret CIA intelligence asset, apparently to
force the intelligence agency to sever its relationship.
   ``I did not threaten to leak anything,'' Hamilton said. ``I was
prepared to follow certain procedures of the House intelligence
committee to try to release information.''
   ``If I had succeeded in that, it would have been an authorized
disclosure and not a leak,'' Hamilton said. ``I did not threaten the
Secretary of State with a leak.''
   The exchange between Sullivan and Hamilton also highlighted the
difficulties posed by airing classified information in a public
trial.
   Sullivan showed Hamilton his letter to Shultz, which the defense
attorney described as discussing a man's ``relationship with the
CIA.''
   ``I don't know if I can comment on the contents of this letter,''
Hamilton said.
   ``You don't have to comment on the man's identity,'' Sullivan
said.
   Hamilton said he took no action after meeting with Shultz. ``The
secretary agreed with my point of view.''
   Sullivan also questioned Hamilton about an instance when the CIA
briefed the House intelligence committee in late 1984 and a report
about the classified information was published in a newspaper ``the
very next day.''
   ``I do not assume for a moment that the leak came from Capitol
Hill,'' Hamilton said. ``There are very experienced people in the
administration who leak information after it comes to the Congress.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
