<FIRST>r w AM-SEC-ToysRUs     02-22 0135</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SEC-Toys R Us,130</SECOND>
<HEAD>Toys R Us Executive Surrenders Profits, Pays Fine in Insider Trading
Suit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission said
Wednesday that an executive of Toys R Us Inc. agreed to settle civil
insider trading charges by repaying $35,000 in illegal profits and a
$10,000 fine.
   The commission had alleged that James M. Markham, former director
of industrial purchasing for the company, used advance knowledge
that the company's 1986 Christmas sales had jumped 27 percent over
1985.
   Markham purchased Toys R Us stock options before the sales
figures were announced publicly and then sold after the
announcement, the agency alleged in a complaint filed last Sept. 26.
   In addition to the money penalties, Markham, without admitting or
denying his guilt, agreed not to violate securities laws in the
future.
</TEXT>
