<FIRST>u i AM-HijackTrial     02-22 0226</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hijack Trial,0234</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defense Seeks Manslaughter Conviction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAUSANNE, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorneys for a Lebanese hijacker
who fatally shot a French passenger on an Air Afrique jetliner in
1987 asked for a manslaughter conviction Wednesday, saying he acted
on a reflex.
   The prosecution has asked for a murder conviction against Hussein
Hariri.
   In their final argument, Hariri's two lawyers said the death of
French passenger Xavier Beaulieu ``was an unfortunate accident.''
   Lawyers Gerald Benoit and Eric Hess told the court Hariri's claim
that he shot because he felt Beaulieu was making a threatening move
was not disproved during the three-day trial before five judges.
   Benoit and Hess did not contest the hijacking charge. Like
murder, it carries a maximum penalty of life imprisonment.
   Hariri, who has described himself as a ``soldier of God,'' said a
life term would be ``no problem'' for him. ``I am ready to die for
my religion.''
   The verdict and sentence was to be announced on Friday after a
closed session in Federal Criminal Court.
   Hariri went on trial Monday, 19 months after he hijacked the
DC-10 on a flight from Brazzaville, Congo, to Paris to press demands
for the release of Lebanese and Palestinians held by French, West
German and Israeli authorities.
   He was arrested after he shot Beaulieu when his deadline expired
for refueling the plane at Geneva airport.
</TEXT>
