<FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-89 2133EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-IndianInvestigation     02-22 0602</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Indian Investigation,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Witnesses Cite Federal Legal and Staffing Problems</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal governmental system and staffing
problems were cited by witnesses who testified Wednesday at a Senate
hearing on sexual abuse of children on Indian reservations.
   It's not that child sex abuse is inherently worse among Indians
than elsewhere in society, said Jane Burnley, director of the
Justice Department's office for victims of crime.
   It's that the federal government, which has jurisdiction over
Indian reservations, does not have the mechanisms to respond to the
problems the way states do, she said after she testified before a
special unit of the Senate Select Committee on Indian Affairs.
   Larry Blythe told the committee that his 2-year-old daughter and
6-year-old son were attacked in 1984 on a Cherokee reservation in
western North Carolina.
   He said defendants were convicted but their life sentences were
overturned on appeal because prosecutors had used a state law to
obtain convictions and state laws do not apply to crimes on Indian
reservations.
   In another trial, he said, prosecutors searched federal statutes
for provisions referring to rape and, while such a crime against
females was covered, similar acts on males were not. In his son's
case, a defendant pleaded guilty last spring to assault causing
bodily harm and got a 10-year sentence, Blythe said.
   He said federal statutes have since been amended for cases such
as those involving his children but that similar loopholes likely
exist for other types of crimes.
   Burnley said that since that federal law was amended in 1986,
many more cases of sex abuse on reservations have come to light but
arranging help for victims has been difficult.
   ``Victims' compensation has grown tremendously as a way of
funding treatment for victims of child abuse, but not in Indian
country,'' she told the committee.
   She said about $2 million for fiscal 1989 was earmarked by the
federal government for such cases among Indians, and Indians are
eligible to apply to state governments for money from their victims'
funds. But she said Indian reservations are usually in remote areas
where communication and transportation are poor, making therapy much
more difficult than elsewhere in society.
   Additionally, the panel was told, the Bureau of Indian Affairs
and the Indian Health Service do not have staff people on the
reservations trained to provide therapy for child sex abuse.
   ``It takes time to teach people what happens to children in these
situations,'' said Penny Coleman, who is with the solicitor's office
of the Interior Department.
   Instead of local police, she said, the FBI investigates the cases
on reservations but FBI agents are not trained specifically for
handling child abuse cases and the agency has comparatively small
staffs for the volume of work in Indian crime.
   Linda Guy, social services specialist in the Bureau of Indian
Affairs, said there have been so many changes in leadership in her
department that it is nearly impossible to handle child sex abuse
cases.
   Robert Delaware, acting head of the bureau's social services
division, told the panel he was the sixth acting chief since August
1986 and that he had little knowledge of the child molestation cases.
   ``I was put there to keep the administrative portion going,''
said Delaware.
   Sen. Thomas Daschle, D-S.D., a member of the investigating unit,
said that ``I don't care if you are acting director for one day or
three months, the impression you leave is that it is not your job _
leave it to someone else.''
   ``I can understand the frustration of the people on the
reservation. We're failing at this,'' Daschle said.
</TEXT>
