<FIRST>u a AM-HospitalWorkers     02-22 0576</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hospital Workers,0595</SECOND>
<HEAD>DiPrete Says Settlement Near In Hospital Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIMBERLY M. SHEARIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CRANSTON, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Striking nurses and attendants were divided
Wednesday on whether to obey a back-to-work court order, but the
governor said a settlement was near after the two sides negotiated
for the first time in five days.
   Gov. Edward D. DiPrete, who called in the National Guard to care
for the 410 patients at General Hospital when the walkout began
Sunday night, said workers who didn't take up their posts Thursday
morning would be fired.
   A hospital spokesman said for the 3 p.m. shift, 32 of 66
scheduled attendants reported, as did 11 of 14 registered nurses and
8 of 15 licensed practical nurses. A judge had set a 3 p.m.
back-to-work deadline.
   ``People are coming back to work in the spirit of abiding by the
court order,'' said hospital director James P. Benedict.
   After a union meeting Wednesday afternoon, some members walked
out chanting, ``No work. No work.''
   DiPrete, who called both sides together for negotiations at his
office, had said earlier a settlement was possible only if the
workers ended their three-day walkout.
   National Guard troops remained at the hospital Wednesday. Thirty
acute-care patients have been transferred to other facilities,
Benedict said.
   The hospital provides long-term care for the chronically ill. A
major factor leading to the strike was a complaint about low
staffing at the hospital.
   Three hours of talks, the first since negotiations broke off
Friday, ended with some concessions but no agreement, said Gerard P.
Cobleigh an attorney with Local 1350 of the American Federation of
State, County and Municipal Employees. ``There are some numbers they
have agreed on,'' he said.
   DiPrete, who traveled to Washington after the meeting, said if
necessary he would bring both sides back to the table. No new
negotiations were scheduled.
   ``I think the ingredients are right here on the table for a
long-lasting settlement to what has been a long-term problem,''
DiPrete said.
   He refused to give details, but said the state's offer of a
53-cent-an-hour pay raise, rejected ovewhelmingly by union members,
was still available. The increase would have raised attendants
starting salaries from $16,600 to $17,600 and nurses starting wages
from $18,800 to $20,000.
   A hearing before Superior Court Judge Antonio Almeida, who
imposed the back-to-work deadline, was scheduled for Thursday on the
state's request for sanctions. The union estimated possible fines of
$200 per day per person for violating the order.
   After the union meeting, one member who would not give his name
said members had voted to stay off the job. He said union President
Joseph Fargnoli told members a settlement was near ``and in a few
days we'll be going back to work.''
   Henry Griggs, a union spokesman, said no vote had been taken.
   Fargnoli said he ``encouraged them to go back to work'' as
outlined in the court-order. ``I guess they decided on an individual
basis'' whether or not to report to work.
   Roberta Reels, a union member, said she would return to her job.
   ``I do want to honor the picket line. I really do. But the court
has issued an order for us to go back to work and I'm going back to
work.'' she said.
   DiPrete said union members had no choice but to return to work.
``The issue on the table right now is, is the union going to obey
the court order?'' he said.
</TEXT>
