<HEAD>Wednesday's Developments on `Satanic Verses'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERT one graf after 5th graf pvs, `_ Similar protests...'
UPDATING with two book chains to restock novel. Picks up 6th pvs, `_ The
Association...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Satanic Verses, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Key developments involving Salman Rushdie's ``The Satanic
Verses'' on Wednesday, the official U.S. publication date of the
novel:
</TEXT>
<NOTE>U.S. PROTESTS</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   _About 300 members of the National Writers Union marched in New
York outside the Iranian Mission to the United Nations. More than
300 people heard writers such as Norman Mailer, Larry McMurtry, Gay
Talese and E.L. Doctorow read from Rushdie's work.
   _ Similar protests were staged in Washington and Boston, with
other rallies or panel discussions of the book planned in Chicago,
San Francisco and Minneapolis.
   _ The B. Dalton bookstore chain said B. Dalton and its Barnes &amp;
Noble subsidiary _ with a total of about 1,250 bookstores across the
country _ were reversing Friday's decision to take ``The Satanic
Verses'' off their shelves and will restock the novel.
   _ The Association of American Publishers, the American
Booksellers Association and the American Library Association took
out a full-page ad in Wednesday's New York Times to declare they
would ensure that copies of ``The Satanic Verses'' remain available
in stores and libraries.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>PROTESTS ABROAD</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   _West Germany called on the U.N. Security Council to take up the
Iranian threats. West German TV said the Cabinet also discussed
``further measures'' against Iran, possibly economic sanctions. West
Germany is Iran's biggest trading partner.
   _ Authors in Finland and the Netherlands condemned Khomeini's
order.
   _ In Cles, Italy, anti-terrorist police guarded a plant where the
book was being printed, and Italians placed hundreds of orders for
it as a publisher prepared to release a second run.
   _ A firebomb was thrown at the dormitory of London's main mosque,
and a newspaper reported that police were investigating whether it
was prompted by an anti-Moslem backlash to the Rushdie affair. No
one was injured.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>THE MOSLEM WORLD</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   _ Iran's Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini said the mounting Western
condemnation of his order to kill Rushdie proves the futility of
normalizing relations with the rest of the world and shows the
West's ``true nature and longstanding hostility.'' He also said the
publication was a Western plot against Islam.
   _ Libya said it has taken measures to confront publication of the
novel. _ A Saudi Arabia conference of Moslem theologians said
Rushdie should stand trial in an Islamic country for his novel.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>RUSHDIE</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Rushdie remains in hiding in Britain. His wife, American novelist
Marianne Wiggins, canceled a U.S. book-promotion tour for her novel,
``John Dollar,'' to stay with him.
</TEXT>
