<FIRST>r i AM-Yugoslavia     02-22 0369</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yugoslavia,0380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Strikes In Kosovo Continue, Communist Leadership Calls Situation
Critical</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of ethnic Albanians,
including more than 1,000 miners occupying their pits since Monday,
stayed off the job Wednesday in the troubled province of Kosovo,
official media reports said.
   The provincial communist leadership held an urgent session
Wednesday afternoon in the region's capital of Pristina, assessing
the security situation in Kosovo as ``extremely critical.''
   Fearing a possibility of open ethnic clashes between the Albanian
majority and Slav minority in the province, a Communist Party
organization of Yugoslavia's federal institutions issued an appeal
``for the use of primarily political means'' in seeking an urgent
stop to the politically motivated labor unrest.
   Responding to miners' demands, Yugoslav Communist Party chief
Stipe Suvar was likely to tour the tense region to try and defuse
the growing threat of a general strike in the province, Belgrade
television said.
   However, a spokeswoman at the federal party headquarters in
Belgrade declined to specify whether or when Suvar would go to
Kosovo, saying ``everything will be known soon.''
   Belgrade radio estimated that more than 10,000 ethnic Albanians
stopped work Wednesday ``in virtually all municipalities'' of the
economically backward southern Yugoslav province.
   The state Tanjug news agency said later that about 2,000 ethnic
Albanian university students from Pristina organized a protest
meeting in solidarity with the striking workers.
   In 1981, the Pristina university students triggered bloody riots
by demanding more autonomy for the province.
   The miners at the Trepca lead and zinc mine, some 125 miles south
of Belgrade, went on strike on Monday to protest alleged
discrimination by authorities in Yugoslavia's largest republic of
Serbia, of which Kosovo is an administrative part.
   Serbian leaders, aided by an unprecedented campaign in the
republic's press, have asserted that the constitution should be
changed to protect the Slav residents allegedly persecuted by ethnic
Albanians, who make up 85 percent of the province's population.
   Also Wednesday, Tanjug reported that the deputy defense minister
of Yugoslavia's republic of Montenegro was fatally shot Tuesday
night by a police officer in Titograd, the republic's capital.
   The news agency said the police officer was detained, but that
motives for the shooting were under investigation. No details were
available.
</TEXT>
