<FIRST>r i AM-SouthAfrica     02-22 0226</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Africa,0231</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police To Stop Arrests Of Blacks Breaking Segregation Law</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police officers no longer will
arrest non-whites using municipal facilities in violation of local
segregation laws, the state radio reported Wednesday.
   The radio said officers from now on will enforce provisions of
the Separate Amenities Act only if they receive a complaint.
   In such cases, the alleged offender will be asked to provide
information and will be advised that court procedings may ensue, but
will not be held in custody.
   The radio said the new procedures were outlined in a circular
being distributed to officers by police headquarters.
   The Separate Amenities Act, adopted in 1953, empowers local and
provincial officials to segregate public facilities such as parks,
libraries, beaches and sports facilities. Many municipalities have
opened some of these facilities to all races in recent years. Many
other cities and towns maintain segregation.
   The governing National Party has been widely accused of hypocrisy
recently because of its harsh criticism of a resegregation campaign
undertaken in towns where the extreme-right Conservative Party won
in local elections last fall.
   Critics noted that the Conservative Party, by restoring
whites-only status at parks and other facilities, was acting in full
accordance with the Separate Amenities Act. Critics also noted that
public facilities remain segregated in many towns controlled by the
National Party.
</TEXT>
