<FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-89 2204EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SchoolSpanking     02-22 0433</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-School Spanking,0446</SECOND>
<HEAD>Virginia Becomes First State in South to Ban School Paddlings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Gerald L. Baliles says he will sign a
measure making Virginia the first state in the South to ban school
spankings, but adds that he sometimes used corporal punishment with
his two children.
   ``It was not ruled out, but it was used very rarely,'' Baliles,
who has a son in high school and a daughter in college, said Tuesday
after the Senate voted 22-18 to pass a prohibition on corporal
punishment in public schools.
   The measure was approved by the House of Delegates earlier this
month on an 86-11 vote.
   Only 13 other states, none in the South, have banned school
paddlings.
   Almost every local school board in Virginia has a policy
discouraging the practice, said Rondle E. Edwards, assistant
superintendent of public instruction.
   But Virginia law allowed the ``reasonable'' use of spankings, so
district policies did not legally prohibit teachers and school
officials from the practice, said Del. V. Thomas Forehand Jr.,
sponsor of the ban.
   In the Senate debate, supporters said spanking sends a ``might
makes right'' message to youngsters that violence by authority
figures is acceptable.
   Sen. Mark L. Earley said the Office of Civil Rights reported
11,301 instances of corporal punishment in Virginia schools in 1986,
and 90 percent was directed at children between 5 and 9 years old.
Most of those spanked were minority, handicapped or learning
disabled students, he said.
   Sen. Dudley J. Emick Jr. said youngsters who need spanking should
get it at home, not in school.
   ``Anyone outside the family who does it is in big trouble'' at
the Emick household, he said.
   Opponents said the elimination of corporal punishment sends the
wrong message to parents concerned about increasing discipline
problems in the classroom.
   ``A whack on the wrist or a spank on the rear is a better
alternative than putting a disruptive child on the streets,'' said
Sen. R. Edward Houck, who is an assistant principal.
   The Virginia Education Association, a lobbying organization for
teachers, and the Virginia PTA supported Forehand's bill, as did
associations representing school boards and school administrators.
   The measure allows teachers to use physical contact to maintain
order and control, quell a disturbance, protect themselves or
others, prevent a student from harming himself or seize weapons or
illegal drugs.
   Tommy Neal, a research analyst with the National Conference of
State Legislatures, said the 13 states that have banned corporal
punishment in schools are California, Hawaii, Maine, Massachusetts,
Nebraska, New Hampshire, New Jersey, New York, Rhode Island,
Vermont, Wisconsin, Michigan and Maryland.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890222-0206 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-89 2034EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-SatanicVerses-US 2ndLd-Writethru a0771 02-22 0910</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Satanic Verses-US, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0771,0928</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Chains Reverse Stand on `Satanic Verses' After Protests</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs grafs 14-16, `The writers...' with 6 to UPDATE with Waldenbooks
selling but not displaying book, comment from Jimmy Carter and professors'
union head; picks up 17th graf, `Not all...' SUBS grafs 21-22, `In Boston...'
with 1 to UPDATE with San Francisco demonstration; picks up 23rd graf,
`Elsewhere in...' Edits to trim.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos NY27, NY52</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Satanic Verses, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL STIEG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Writers nationwide protested Wednesday against
the Islamic death warrant for author Salman Rushdie, and the
controversy led a book company to reverse its decision to pull the
``The Satanic Verses'' from store shelves.
   The B. Dalton bookstore chain and its subsidiary, Barnes &amp; Noble,
said Wednesday afternoon that they would resume selling the book
because of ``the urging of an overwhelming majority of its store
managers and employees.''
   The announcement came after a day of protest _ including a march
on a B. Dalton and a Barnes &amp; Noble store _ and a reading of
excerpts from the book.
   ``I write controversial books. What publisher is now going to
take chances with a controversial book?'' asked activist Abbie
Hoffman, one of about 300 members of the National Writers Union who
marched in driving rain outside the Iranian Mission to the United
Nations.
   Similar protests were staged in Washington and Boston, with more
rallies or panel discussions of the book planned later in the day in
Chicago, San Francisco, Minneapolis and elsewhere. Wednesday marked
the official American publication date of the book, which was
published last fall in Britain.
   More than 300 people heard some of the nation's most celebrated
writers _ Norman Mailer, Larry McMurtry, Gay Talese and E.L.
Doctorow among them _ read from Rushdie's work.
   Susan Sontag, president of the PEN American Center, the writers
group that sponsored the reading, said the threat against Rushdie
was ``an act of international terrorism against the life of the
mind, against human lives.''
   She read a statement from Rushdie's American-born wife, writer
Marianne Wiggins, who along with her husband is in hiding.
   ``Writers everywhere have been weighed and measured by the edict
from Iran,'' Ms. Wiggins said. ``We are a dangerous breed and always
have been, because words outlive their authors. ... Only fear can
stop a writer's writing. Only fear can stop a book from being sold.''
   Mailer lashed out at booksellers who stopped selling the book.
Such merchants ``seem to have more respect for terrorists than for
culture,'' he said.
   Security guards searched bags of each person attending the
reading. About two dozen Moslems protested across the street, with
signs reading ``Satanic Verses is blasphemous'' and ``Rushdie is a
friend of Satan.''
   Iran's Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini and others in the Islamic
world consider Rushdie's book blasphemous. They have issued death
threats against the author and his publishers. Rushie is an
Indian-born Moslem living in Britain.
   At the protest outside the Iranian mission, security guards
rebuffed National Writers Union President Alec Dubro trying to
deliver a letter expressing outrage at the death threats.
   The writers then marched to two B. Dalton's and Barnes &amp; Noble's
Fifth Avenue book stores. The two chains had pulled the book from
store shelves in several cities. Waldenbooks, the nation's largest
chain, also withdrew the book from display, but said in a statement
Wednesday, ``Store managers continue selling the books where
available.''
   ``To see book stores caving in like that to demagoguery is
horrifying,'' said author Laura Shapiro.
   Former President Carter joined in the criticism of booksellers
who removed the book from shelves, calling it a ``disgrace.''
   Fundamentalists Anonymous, a group organized to counter the
influence of religious fundamentalists, called for a four-week
boycott of the store chains. The Overseas Press Club of America also
issued a statement condemning the booksellers as having demonstrated
``that terrorism and ignorance do pay.''
   And Carole Simpson Stern, president of the American Association
of University Professors, said booksellers who suspended sales of
the book dishonored themselves.
   ``The proper response to a government that proposes a bounty for
the murder of the author of some book it finds offensive is not to
suppress the book. The proper response is to give that book safe
sanctuary as will make clear the futility of trying to kill ideas by
killing authors and burning their books,'' she said.
   Not all bookstores have followed the lead of the big chains.
   The Association of American Publishers, the American Booksellers
Association and the American Library Association took out a
full-page ad in Wednesday's New York Times to declare that they
would ensure that copies of ``The Satanic Verses'' remain available
in stores and libraries.
   In Washington, about 75 people, including novelist Barbara
Raskin, protested outside the Office of Iranian Interest, Iran's
representative in the nation's capital.
   Leaders of the two groups that organized the protest, Arthur J.
Kropp, president of People for the American Way, and Noelle McAfee
of the National Writers Union, were allowed inside to present a
petition opposing the death threats.
   In both Boston and San Francisco, crowds of about 100 people
picketed peacefully outside B. Dalton outlets.
   Elsewhere in Massachusetts, writers and literary critics planned
a panel discussion Wednesday evening to substitute for a canceled
appearance by Rushdie in Cambridge, and U.S. Rep. Barney Frank said
he would read passages of the novel into the Congressional Record to
show his support for the author.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
