<FIRST>r i AM-Kuwait-Lebanon     02-22 0524</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kuwait-Lebanon,0540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Round-Table On Lebanon Said To Consider Beirut Demilitarized Zone</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ABDUL-JALIL MUSTAFA</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KUWAIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Arab League mediation committee opened a meeting
Wednesday with six Lebanese religious leaders in an effort to unify
a country wracked by civil war and a government split between
Moslems and Christians.
   Informed sources said the clerics were being sounded out on a
proposed demilitarized zone comprising greater Beirut, the capital.
   ``The Lebanese should take advantage of the present spirit of
international detente,'' said Sheik Sabah Ahmad Jaber, Kuwaiti
foreign minister and chairman of the Arab League's six-member
committee.
   ``The failure to exploit the committee's good offices will mean
missing an opportunity that may not return,'' he said.
   The Arab League mediation effort aims to prevent formal partition
of Lebanon into sectarian cantons after more than 13 years of civil
war. The strife between Moslems and Christians has been compounded
by Parliament's failure to elect a successor to outgoing Christian
President Amin Gemayel five months ago.
   Before stepping down Sept. 22, Gemayel appointed Michael Aoun, a
Christian, to head an interim Cabinet. Syrian-backed Moslem leaders
rejected the appointment and backed Salim Hoss, who formed a rival
Moslem Cabinet.
   Aoun's appointment, the Moslems charged, violated an unwritten
national covenant dating to Lebanon's independence from France in
1943. The covenant says the premiership is given to the Sunni Moslem
sect, the presidency to the Maronite Christians and the position of
Parliament speaker to a Shiite Moslem.
   The informed sources at Wednesday's meeting, who spoke on
condition they not be identified, said the panel was also sounding
out the clerics on electing a president and a Parliament speaker as
well as on the appointment of a prime minister.
   In addition, the sources said the mediation committee is
proposing to modify an ``Arab deterrent force'' to include troops
from the six countries represented in the panel in addition to the
Syrian forces in Lebanon.
   Arab League members on the panel also included Secretary-General
Chedli Klibi of Tunisia and the foreign ministers of Tunisia, Sudan,
Algeria, Jordan and the United Arab Emirates.
   The religious leaders attending are Maronite patriarch Nasrallah
Sfeir; Greek Catholic patriarch Maximos Hakim; acting leader of the
Supreme Shiite Moslem Council, Sheik Mehdi Shamseddin; and Sunni
Moslem Grand Mufti, Sheik Hassan Khaled.
   Also attending were the supreme religious judge of the Druse
community, Sheik Mursel Nasr and the Greek Orthodox Patriarch of
Antioch, Ignatius Hazim.
   Syria, the main power broker in Lebanon, has an estimated 40,000
forces there under an Arab League peacekeeping mandate issued in
1976.
   The League panel last month met with Lebanon's three senior
political leaders: Acting Prime Minister Salim Hoss, a Sunni Moslem,
army commander Gen. Michel Aoun, a Maronite Christian who heads a
rival Christian Cabinet, and Parliament Speaker Hussein Husseini, a
Shiite Moslem.
   Sabah said the committee's next round of talks would be held with
leaders of the rival Lebanese militias.
   The leaders of Lebanon's Christian and Moslem factions were due
to hold talks with the committee on Monday, but the session was
delayed while Sabah held private talks with each leader in an effort
to prepare the way for agreement.
</TEXT>
