<SECOND>AM-Gun Ban,0181</SECOND>
<HEAD>Petition Seeks Overturn of City Gun Bans</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A petition filed with the state Supreme
Court on Wednesday seeks the overturn of two city bans on
semiautomatic weapons.
   The request for a temporary stay of a Los Angeles ordinance due
to take effect Thursday and a similar measure already in effect in
Stockton claimed the regulations are pre-empted by state law.
   Documents filed with the Supreme Court on behalf of several
individuals contended California already has a regulatory program
governing possession of firearms. They also cited a 1982 opinion by
the state attorney general that cities cannot prohibit possession of
handguns within their municipal areas.
   By overruling the Los Angeles and Stockton measures, the petition
said the court would ``ensure the effectiveness'' of the state's
firearms laws against ``unwarranted interference.''
   The bans on possession of military style assault rifles were
approved in the wake of the slaying of five children last month by
Partick E. Purdy, who came to a Stockton elementary school and
opened fire with an AK-47 semiautomatic weapon.
</TEXT>
