<FIRST>u a AM-Murphy'sFuture 1stLd-Writethru a0678 02-22 0596</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Murphy's Future, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0678,0610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Retarded Man Ordered Released From Mental Hospital After 32 Years</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs last graf, `Murphy last...' with 5 grafs to UPDATE with
background on case, comment from prosecutor; no pick up.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILARY ISRAELSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A retarded man mistakenly held for 32 years
in a mental hospital gained new freedoms Wednesday with a judge's
ruling that he can live in a less-restrictive setting if he wears an
electronic monitoring device.
   The monitor was among the conditions imposed on Bernt Murphy, 51,
who was committed to the state hospital near Provo following the
1957 rape and beating of a 5-year-old girl, for which Murphy was
found incompetent to stand trial.
   In June, the Utah Supreme Court ruled that Murphy must be freed
from the hospital because he was mistakenly ruled insane by a judge
in 1957.
   On Wednesday, District Judge Pat Brian ordered Murphy transferred
to Opportunity House, on the edge of the hospital property. He will
be allowed to come and go during the day but must report back each
night.
   ``This deals with the most complex and social problems this court
or any other district court has ever resolved,'' the judge said.
   The judge ruled that in addition to wearing the electronic
monitoring device, Murphy must return to court every four months for
review.
   ``The record should be clear. The court will not tolerate
violations of the order. Even a child knows the difference between
right and wrong,'' Brian warned. ``The court and the community wish
you well and have every right to expect you'll succeed.''
   Murphy, estimated to have the mental capacity of an 8-year-old,
cried when he heard the decision.
   His attorney, Brooke Wells, said Murphy feared that the
electronic monitoring device would somehow shock him but calmed down
after being assured it would not.
   Murphy, his arm around Wells' shoulders, said, ``I feel great and
I'm glad to have it over with. ... I'll show them. I want a job in
security.''
   At Opportunity House, where he had been tentatively housed prior
to the hearing Wednesday, Murphy has been in charge of janitorial
duties and a fish pond.
   ``We're not unhappy with this. We always knew it would be a
transitional thing, and this is just fine,'' Wells said. ``We're
going to see how that works. This is an important, happy day.''
   Wells said Murphy has always wanted to prove he can do things on
his own, and the ruling gives him new freedom.
   During questioning about the child rape, Murphy, then 19,
admitted to the 1955 slaying of a 23-year-old mentally retarded
woman he had known at the Utah State Training School for the
developmentally disabled in American Fork.
   Murphy later denied killing the woman and was found incompetent
to stand trial. On the rape charge, he was declared insane. In 1972,
doctors at the state hospital said Murphy had been cured of his
insanity, and he was tried on the rape charge and found innocent by
reason of mental illness. The slaying was never solved.
   In 1985, an appeal was filed on Murphy's behalf, questioning his
continued confinement at the hospital.
   Wells had argued that Murphy could do well in a group home with
other retarded adults. But state officials believed he still is
capable of violent behavior.
   Deputy Salt Lake County Attorney Bud Ellett said the Supreme
Court's ruling and Brian's actions Wednesday had resolved the Murphy
case, and there are no plans to pursue any charges.
   ``He's not insane, but is retarded,'' he said.
</TEXT>
