<FIRST>u i AM-Nicaragua 1stLd-Writethru a0759 02-22 0526</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0759,0539</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Split Over Government Offer of Talks on Electoral Reforms</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with Ortega meeting opposition. No
pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition parties met Wednesday with
President Daniel Ortega to discuss electoral reforms, and at least
one party suggested Ortega not run for re-election.
   The Conservative Democratic Party, which has the largest
opposition representation in the National Assembly with 14 deputies,
also asked for absentee balloting for Nicaraguans abroad, many of
whom live in Miami.
   In a communique issued after party officials met with Ortega, the
Conservative Democrats said, ``Although re-election is not
forbidden, it would be convenient for the peaceful coexistence in
the nation that (Ortega) not present his candidacy for re-election.''
   Ortega has hinted he will run again and seems the likeliest
choice, although the ruling Sandinista National Liberation Front has
not announced an official candidate.
   In spurning early elections, the Conservative Democrats echoed
the view of other parties that they don't have enough time to
organize effectively for elections in February 1990.
   The party also demanded that no state property or employee be
used for political propaganda; that the military be denied the vote;
and that the number of regional vote-counting centers be cut in
half, apparently to allow all parties to have observers at all such
centers.
   A faction of the Liberal party met with Ortega on Wednesday.
   This Central American country of about 3 million people has 15
legal political parties. Seven of them are represented in the
National Assembly.
   The 14 opposition parties met Tuesday night to discuss Ortega's
offer of renewing talks on reforming electoral laws.
   ``Most of us decided not to go, but we left the option open for
whoever wants to attend independently,'' Alan Zambrana of the
Communist Party said Wednesday. His party declined Ortega's
invitation.
   Ortega has said negotiations would center on the agreement he and
the presidents of El Salvador, Honduras, Costa Rica and Guatemala
signed on Feb. 14 in El Salvador.
   It calls for Nicaragua to institute democratic reforms, such as
giving equal air time to the opposition; including opposition
representatives in the Supreme Electoral Council, and allowing
international observers to oversee general elections, which Ortega
moved up by 10 months, to Feb. 25, 1990.
   ``Any dialogue must be with the entire civic opposition,''
Zambrana, a deputy in the assembly, said. ``We're not going to lend
ourselves to the Sandinistas' game of trying to divide us by
inviting us to bilateral talks.''
   It does not appear that the Sandinistas would have to make much
of an effort to divide the opposition. Already existing are three
Liberal parties; four Social-Christian parties and three
Conservative parties.
   The Communist Party and the Marxist-Leninist Popular Action
Movement split the far left. Each has two deputies in the assembly.
   Mauricio Diaz, president of the left-of-center Social-Christian
Popular Party, initially said his party would talk with Ortega, then
said a decision had not been made. His party has the second-largest
opposition representation in the legislature, with six deputies.
   Eric Ramirez's Social-Christian Party is sending two delegates to
meet with Ortega, a party official said.
</TEXT>
