<FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-89 2238EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-AirForceCrash     02-22 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Air Force Crash,0405</SECOND>
<HEAD>Six Bodies Recovered, Search Continues For Others</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HURLBURT FIELD, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rescuers recovered the remains of six
people by Wednesday and planned to continue their search for the
bodies of two others presumed dead in the crash of an Air Force
cargo jet, officials said.
   An Air Force safety team arrived to investigate why the C-141B
Starlifter from Norton Air Force Base, Calif., went down during a
violent thunderstorm Monday night.
   The recovered remains are being taken to the regional military
hospital at neighboring Eglin Air Force Base for identification,
said Hurlburt spokeswoman Victoria Hanson.
   The crash site, which was in the Florida Panhandle about four
miles north of Hurlburt, could be reached only on foot or by
helicopter pending construction of a half-mile dirt road through a
heavily wooded swamp inhabited by poisonous snakes and alligators.
   An Air Force civil engineering battalion had not completed the
road, including construction of a bridge over a creek, before the
six bodies were recovered, Ms. Hanson said. The road work was to
continue Thursday.
   Two of the bodies were found inside the plane and four outside
near the nose area, said Col. Howard Oakes, Eglin's base commander.
He said four bodies were found Tuesday and two Wednesday.
   The front of the plane was severely burned and damaged. The rear
half was charred but intact. Searchers had not been through all
portions of the plane Wednesday and were to continue their work at
dawn, officials said.
   While investigators were not yet ready to speculate on what
caused the crash, attention has centered on the weather.
   The four-engine transport had departed Monday morning from Norton
and stopped in Colorado Springs, Colo., en route to Hurlburt where
it was to pick up 50 passengers and their baggage for a flight to
Howard Air Base in Panama.
   The C-141 had a crew of seven and had picked up a passenger,
retired Air Force Capt. John G. Galvin of Jacksonville, during a
refueling stop in Colorado Springs, Ms. Hanson said.
   Staff Sgt. Robert Pfenning, a Norton spokesman, identified the
crew members as Capt. Mark J. Chambers, 30; Capt. John F. Young, 30;
Master Sgt. Robert E. Wright Jr., 37; Tech. Sgt. Ronald D. Grubbs,
29; Staff Sgt. Karl M. Kohler, 32; Airman 1st Class Scott Craig, 22,
and Staff Sgt. John W. Remerscheid, 33. No hometowns were available.
</TEXT>
