<FIRST>u a AM-BabyCalvin     02-22 0294</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Baby Calvin,0302</SECOND>
<HEAD>Boy Who Received Rare Double Transplant Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADISON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 16-month-old Florida boy who received a
rare liver and small intestine transplant nearly two months ago died
Wednesday.
   Calvin Oliveira's death was caused by a respiratory system
failure, said Dr. Munci Kalayoglu, who performed the liver-intestine
transplant. The boy died at the University of Wisconsin Hospital and
Clinics.
   Calvin's transplanted liver began to fail Tuesday, according to
hospital spokesman Greer Sutter.
   Calvin received national attention after his father, Brazilian
immigrant Carlos Oliveira, made a tearful plea to Florida Gov. Bob
Martinez for help in saving the boy's life. Money for the down
payment on the operation was quickly raised from private and
corporate donors.
   Calvin was the only child of Oliveira and his wife, Adriana, who
worked opposite shifts in restaurants so that they could care for
the baby.
   Although Calvin continued to receive blood and oxygen, Kalayoglu
and the child's parents had agreed Monday that there would be no
attempt to resuscitate Calvin if his heart stopped. The Oliveiras
referred all questions to Kalayoglu, a hospital spokesman said.
   The liver and intestinal transplant was necessary because the boy
was born with use of only 5 percent of his intestine. The
intravenous feeding that kept him alive caused his liver to
deteriorate so severely by December that his only hope was the
experimental operation, Kalayoglu said. The operation took place
Dec. 31.
   Kalayoglu had expected Calvin to be able to use the new intestine
and go off intravenous feeding a few weeks after the operation. But
a mysterious lung ailment developed.
   Family friend Marge Gallece said the long hospitalization made it
likely that Calvin's bills would add up to more than $300,000. Less
than $200,000 has been raised.
</TEXT>
