<FIRST>u p AM-ChicagoMayoral 2nd-Writethru a0837 02-22 0635</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chicago Mayoral, 2nd - Writethru, a0837,0649</SECOND>
<HEAD>GOP Officials Brace for Vrdolyak Write-In Campaign</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs next-to-last graf to CORRECT month of Washington's death
to November sted December.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Edward Vrdolyak, a feisty former alderman who once
headed the local Democratic Party, declared Wednesday that he would
seek the Republican nomination for mayor next week through a
write-in campaign.
   ``I'll be your candidate,'' Vrdolyak told 400 supporters who
chanted ``Eddie, Eddie, Eddie.''
   Vrdolyak joined the GOP in 1987, soon after he unsuccessfully
sought the mayor's chair as a third-party candidate. In November he
lost a countywide race for clerk of courts.
   ``I can honestly tell you that I never thought that I would be a
speaker in front of an audience concerning a political topic
again,'' he told the crowd gathered at a restaurant Wednesday night.
``I came out of the November election soundly defeated. I was good
and tired. I was soured on politics.''
   Vrdolyak said he decided to run because many of his admirers told
him ``you are the reason we came to the Republican Party.''
   He pulled out an oversized ballot and showed the crowd how to
write in his name when they go to the polls during next Tuesday's
primary.
   ``If everybody in this room goes out and gets 20 votes it's a
landslide,'' Vrdolyak said.
   Some observers said Vrdolyak, win or lose, could have a
significant impact on the mayoral race.
   ``Nobody ever pays much attention to the Republican Party here,''
said Mike Royko, the Pulitzer Prize-winning syndicated columnist
based at the Chicago Tribune. ``But he could sure create problems,
the most obvious effect of which would be to siphon off white votes
from Rich Daley.''
   Both Democratic front-runner Richard M. Daley, Cook County
state's attorney and son of the late Mayor Richard J. Daley, and his
primary challenger, Mayor Eugene Sawyer, said Wednesday that
Vrdolyak would have minimal impact on their contest.
   GOP front-runner Dr. Herbert Sohn, who was endorsed by the city's
Republican Party, is taking the offensive, addressing the issue at
local appearances in these terms: ``Eddie, on Feb. 28th, I'm going
to beat you. ... No one's going to push me around.''
   Some political observers are not so sure, especially in a primary
where the GOP winner traditionally needs fewer than 10,000 votes.
   ``Eddie's like a cat with nine lives,'' said Tom Roesser, a
political analyst who is active in corporate and Republican circles,
``but he hasn't demonstrated an ability to win outside his own
ward.''
   Vrdolyak, 51, earned a reputation as a maverick during the tenure
of the elder Daley, when he led a rebellious group of aldermen who
opposed the administration and came to be known as the Young Turks.
   He held prominent positions in the administrations of subsequent
mayors Michael Bilandic and Jane Byrne.
   In 1983, he led a bloc of white aldermen in a series of
acrimonious City Council battles against the late Harold Washington,
elected earlier that year as the city's first black mayor.
   Vrdolyak, who served 18 years as alderman of the 10th Ward, a
gritty, predominantly white working-class enclave on the southeast
side, left the post in 1987 to make a third-party mayoral run
against Washington.
   Washington won re-election with 53 percent to Vrdolyak's 42
percent. GOP standard-bearer Don Haider, trying to break a
Democratic grip on City Hall dating back to 1931, wound up with 4
percent.
   Washington died in November 1987. An April 4 special general
election will follow Tuesday's party primaries. Voters are choosing
a mayor to serve the last two years of Washington's term.
   Soon after his loss to Washington, Vrdolyak switched to the
Republican Party. He was defeated by Democrat Aurelia Pucinski in
last fall's Cook County clerk race, and returned to private law
practice.
</TEXT>
