<FIRST>a e PM-APonTV-Principal Adv23   02-22 0800</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP on TV-Principal, Adv 23,0818</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv23</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Thursday PMs, Feb. 23</HEAD>
<HEAD>Victoria Principal Is Star and Producer of TV Movie</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For her latest movie, CBS' ``Naked Lie,''
Victoria Principal's two roles as actress and executive producer
were occasionally at odds.
   ``There were some things that the executive producer wanted the
actress to do, but as the actress I didn't want to do them,'' she
said. ``Generally, the executive producer won.
   ``One day, for instance, the actress had a scene early in the
morning and wanted to take the rest of the day off. But the
executive producer felt it was more economical to have her do one
more scene at the end of the day. Another time, the producer felt
that since the wardrobe had been made for the actress she should pay
half price to take it home. But the actress wanted it and we gave it
to her.''
   She laughed and said, ``I'm sure the supermarket tabloids will
take that and the headlines will read: `Victoria Principal Has Fight
With Self.' For the last few days a tabloid reporter's been parked
outside my house. They've gone through my trash and they've been
following me everywhere I go.''
   ``Naked Lie'' will be telecast this Sunday by CBS. Principal
stars as a prosecuting attorney whose affair with a judge, played by
James Farentino, threatens to destroy her career when they're both
assigned to a politically explosive case.
   The movie is her second since she left ``Dallas'' after nine
years on the hit prime-time soap opera. She had starred as Pamela
Barnes Ewing.
   When she read the screenplay of ``Naked Lie,'' she said, ``I
liked the story. I was drawn to its concept, which was new to TV at
the time. It had aspects of `Suspect' and `Jagged Edge.' I felt it
could be a very tight, suspenseful, romantic mystery. Our story is
very tight, which is unusual for TV. Usually, you can drive a truck
through the plot. You don't have to suspend belief.''
   Principal is developing other projects and has deals with NBC and
ABC. She is in no hurry to do another series.
   ``I own several properties that I think would make good series,''
she said. ``But I want to have deep artistic involvement. It would
have to be done by my company. Doing a series is a grueling
lifestyle. In order to live that lifestyle it would have to be a
project I believe in. It would have to be one from the heart.
   ``The best of all worlds in terms of lifestyle is a half-hour
comedy. I do have one I like. But for one-hour dramas, outside of
`Murder, She Wrote,' there are no shows starring women. First, you
entertain, but if I did a series I'd want to do something
meaningful. If you can touch someone and cause them to think, you've
reached TV's potential. Even if you disturb or upset someone _ as
long as you make the audience feel something.''
   At one point in her career she quit acting and became a talent
agent. She began acting again when she needed money to pay for
tuition for law school. She became so successful the second time she
kept at it. It wasn't long before she was cast in ``Dallas,'' her
only series.
   ``Dallas'' was originally conceived as a kind of ``Romeo and
Juliet'' meets ``Giant'' for her and Patrick Duffy. But Larry
Hagman, as J.R. Ewing, became the major focus of the show.
   Was she bothered at losing the lead role?
   ``Whatever concern I had about that was offset by its success,''
she answered. ``Would I rather be a leading performer in a show that
runs five weeks or part of an ensemble that runs for many years. The
latter, of course. Because of my years as an agent I have an ability
to stand back and look at the project as a whole.''
   Principal said there is no chance she will return to ``Dallas.''
   ``They might bring Pam back, but it won't be me,'' she said.
``They've asked me back, but that's not where my life is going. I
don't want to live my life in reverse. I'm not bitter and have no
ill feelings. I chose to leave simply because it was in my own best
interests.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere in television:
   RULE ELECTED _ Elton H. Rule, former vice chairman of ABC Inc.,
has been elected the first president of the newly reorganized
Academy of Television Arts &amp; Sciences Foundation, the charity and
education wing of the TV academy. Foundation projects include an
internship program, the academy's research library and a facility
for the television academy's Hall of Fame.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Thurs PMs, Feb. 23</NOTE>
</DOC>
