<FIRST>a w PM-WalterMears ADV23   02-22 0764</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Walter Mears, ADV 23,0758</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv 23</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Thurs Feb 23 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Reagan Turned Up Heat; Bush Tries Warmth</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WALTER R. MEARS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ronald Reagan used to say that when Congress
wouldn't see the light, he'd make them feel the heat. President Bush
is trying for warmth instead.
   Bush's first stint of domestic campaigning as president is, like
Reagan's eight years ago, tied tightly to the budget and the
economy, but with a difference. Reagan sought to pressure a
half-Democratic Congress. It's solidly Democratic now, Senate and
House, and the kind of coalition of Republicans and conservative
Democrats that delivered for Reagan is not in sight for Bush.
   Reagan was campaigning for a right turn from the policies of a
Democratic administration. His first post-inaugural address was a
nationally televised speech from the White House; in it he declared
``we're in the worst economic mess since the Depression.''
   Bush is arguing his case for modest change with praise, not
blame, for what went before. ``We've made tremendous progress and I
mean to build on that progress,'' he said in the first of three
speeches on the budget last week.
   The president said his purpose was ``to talk as directly as
possible to the American people,'' in speeches to a business group
in Manchester, N.H., legislators in South Carolina and college
students in St. Louis.
   Reagan's first term economic wares were a 25-percent, 3-year tax
cut, drastic reductions in domestic spending, and sharp increases
for defense.
   Bush wants a flexible freeze on domestic spending, with increases
for selected social programs, to be balanced by cuts in others _
although his budget doesn't say which ones, and neither does he.
   He'd like a tax cut, on capital gains, but nothing so dramatic as
Reagan's income tax reduction. And Bush's chances of getting the
reduction he wants are slim to none in the Democratic House.
   As part of his road show, Bush told each audience about the items
for which he wants to increase federal spending _ the environment,
space, the war on drugs, education, child care, help for the
homeless.
   That's starting to irk Democrats who say he's taking credit for
projected increases without saying what he wants cut to pay for it.
   In those speeches, Bush also pressed his call for a line-item
veto, so he and future presidents can veto specific spending items
without rejecting an entire appropriations bill. That isn't likely
to happen, either, because Congress would lose its ability to force
spending upon an administration.
   The chairman of the Senate Budget Committee, James Sasser of
Tennessee, remarked that Bush wants line-item veto but won't but
won't deliver a line-item budget.
   There are other signs of strain, but both the administration and
Congress still are talking about cooperation rather than
confrontation. Bush stressed that in his speeches, making
bipartisanship a refrain at each stop.
   It was a theme at the Capitol, too. ``You get an A for mood,''
Sen. Bennett Johnston of Louisiana told budget director Richard G.
Darman.
   Reagan talked of bipartisanship, too, during his early days in
the White House. ``I extend my hand in cooperation and I believe we
can go forward in a bipartisan manner,'' he said in one of his
initial messages to Congress.
   But he had a special definition. Reagan bipartisanship meant
Republicans plus conservative Democrats who were predisposed to go
along with the White House. With that coalition vote, he got his
spending and tax cuts and House Democratic leaders couldn't do a
thing about it. The Senate was in Republican hands.
   Bush has neither of those advantages. His bipartisanship means
working with the Democratic leaders of House and Senate, not
confronting them.
   Pressing his program, Reagan told a Republican crowd ``the battle
is on, lines are being drawn.'' Reagan said that when necessary,
he'd go over the heads of Congress, directly to the voters, to get
support for his proposals.
   Bush doesn't talk that way. He says voters want an end to
political bickering. His White House spokesman said the budget
speeches were intended to underscore those aims, not to pressure
Congress.
   ``It's an attempt to explain to the American people that he
intends to work with the Congress,'' said Marlin Fitzwater, the
White House press secretary. ``All the indications we have are that
the Congress intends to work with us ... to try to solve this
problem.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Walter R. Mears, vice president and columnist for
The Associated Press, has reported on Washington for more than 25
years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
