<FIRST>a a PM-OntheMoney Adv23   02-22 0601</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-On the Money, Adv 23,0616</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv23</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Thursday, Feb. 23</HEAD>
<HEAD>Despite Inflation Talk, Gold Not Shining</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   All the talk about reviving inflation these days
has provided little comfort to advocates of gold investments.
   The price of gold, which is supposed to thrive on inflationary
worries, has instead been slumping, hitting 2{-year lows this month.
   Hovering lately around $380 an ounce, it is down more than 20
percent from its early-1988 high near $500 and off about 7 percent
since just the beginning of 1989.
   Even news of a bigger-than-expected 1 percent jump in the
producer price index of finished goods for January failed to stir
gold out of its doldrums.
   In a strange twist, analysts attribute the weakness in gold to
the alarms sounded about the dangers of inflation by such prominent
observers as Alan Greenspan, chairman of the Federal Reserve.
   ``Recent upward pressure on the producer price index points to a
modest pickup in the inflation rate during coming months,'' say
economists at Merrill Lynch.
   ``But the behavior of gold prices underlines confidence in the
inflation-fighting resolve of the Fed and a belief that inflation
pressures will ultimately be contained.''
   Or as the Value Line Survey put it in its latest quarterly
appraisal of gold-mining stocks, ``the continued assertions by
Chairman Greenspan that inflation in the United States is too high
sends a bearish signal to gold markets.
   ``The concomitant increase in short-term interest rates that the
Fed has orchestrated serves, meanwhile, to shore up the dollar,
placing further downward pressure on bullion quotations.''
   Yields at or near 9 percent on virtually riskless investments
such as Treasury bills represent stiff competition for gold
investments, which pay no current return in most of their various
forms.
   Dividend yields in the 9 percent range can be had in the American
depositary receipts of some South African mining companies, which
trade like stocks and can be obtained through just about any broker.
   However, these stocks are under a cloud because of controversy
over South Africa's political policies, in particular apartheid.
   On top of that, high interest rates increase the cost of carrying
gold on credit, as many dealers and other businesses do.
   Other, separate reasons have been advanced for gold's slump. The
Soviet Union, which ranks behind only South Africa among the biggest
gold producers of the world, is said to have been selling gold in
large amounts lately.
   Reports from gold-trading centers in Europe suggest that these
sales are likely to continue as the Soviets seek to upgrade their
industrial production base under the restructuring effort known as
perestroika.
   All in all, gold's glory days when it soared above $800 an ounce
at the start of the 1980s seem long past.
   Yet there is a vocal camp of analysts and advisers who still
recommend devoting at least a small fraction of one's assets to gold
as insurance, if nothing else, against future inflationary outbreaks.
   Some argue that gold could enjoy a nice rally if for any reason
policymakers such as Greenspan find it tougher than expected to keep
inflation in check.
   ``We are not turning into gold bugs,'' says James Stack, editor
of the advisory letter InvesTech Market Analyst, but recent
stirrings in inflation ``could point toward substantial gains in
gold and gold stocks in the months ahead.''
   ``Don't look for gold stocks to immediately soar,'' he cautions.
``Most investors firmly believe that inflation will fade after this
latest increase in short-term interest rates. It'll take a while to
shake that confidence.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Thurs Feb 23</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890222-0227 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-89 0538EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e BC-WeekendTV-Hussein Adv03-05   02-22 0779</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Weekend TV-Hussein, Adv 03-05,0793</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv03</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv04</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv05</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, March 3-5, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Director Goes Against Trend Toward `Cute Baby' Movies</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Katie's newborn image filled the big screen
and her cries from the cradle filled the sound dubbing stage as
director Waris Hussein called for louder wailing.
   The NBC movie ``Those She Left Behind'' focuses on the crisis
caused by Katie's arrival. The mother dies in childbirth and the
father is overwhelmed by grief and the responsibility of taking care
of his new daughter.
   ``I'm putting in some more baby cries,'' said Hussein, who sat at
the control board with several sound technicians.
   ``When we filmed, she wasn't crying all the time. When the father
tells her to calm down, she wasn't crying. We made the baby cry a
few times, but you can only go so far in provoking a child. You have
to go with whatever happens at the time.''
   ``Those She Left Behind,'' which NBC will telecast on Monday,
stars Gary Cole as the father, Joanna Kerns as a business associate,
Colleen Dewhurst as his mother-in-law and Mary Page Keller as the
mother. Michael O'Hara wrote the screenplay.
   Hussein said he selected Dewhurst for the role. He'd previously
directed her in two movies, ``And Baby Makes Six,'' his first film
after moving to California, and its sequel ``Baby Comes Home.'' They
were about a middle-aged couple who have another baby even though
they have grown children.
   ``To me this is more than just about being a father,'' said
Hussein. ``It's about adjustment. It's about growth. I'm always
interested in human nature and how it develops. A man thinks he's
shaped his destiny, but it suddenly changes and he has to start from
rock bottom.
   ``It's a life-enhancing experience. Through his wife's death, he
has to reassess his life and grow. Many men hide behind a lot of
macho assertions. The wife has the baby and she takes care of it. A
man left in those circumstances is basically a child. I think a lot
of women are going to dig their husbands in the ribs.''
   Hussein said one of the things that attracted him to ``Those She
Left Behind'' was that it was not a ``cute baby'' movie.
   ``There's a tendency to do pictures about cute babies,'' he said.
``The baby is very pretty, but I didn't want the audience to `ooh'
and `ah' over the baby. This is going to change people's concepts.
Another thing that appealed to me was that it shows how precarious
life is. It can happen to anybody. Someone's here one minute and
gone the next.
   ``Gary returns to an empty house when that very morning his wife
asked him if he'd be home for dinner. The baby still represents his
wife's death. He has to forgive the baby. He has to adjust to his
wife's death. It's about basic human conditions. It has no frills.
It has an honest approach with no false emotions. I like the way he
has to adjust to his mother-in-law.''
   Kerns, who stars in ABC's ``Growing Pains,'' plays an associate
who helps Cole get through the emotional crisis.
   ``They kind of fall for each other,'' she said in an interview,
``but it was nice that they didn't ride off into the sunset. They
didn't get together and `baby makes three.' I loved working with
Waris. He let the actors act. He wasn't in our faces all the time.''
   Hussein also directed the miniseries ``Little Gloria _ Happy at
Last'' and such TV movies as ``Copacabana'' and ``When the Bough
Breaks.''
   ``I tend to gravitate toward character studies,'' he said. ``I
would hate to be categorized over what I do. I'm not really a
`woman's director.' I've done some things unexpected of me. I
directed `Coming Out of the Ice,'' which had only two women in it. I
do have a reputation among certain actresses. The director I most
admire is George Cukor, who was known as a `woman's director.'
Hitchcock, for instance, is not a director I'd want to follow.''
   Hussein was born in India, but was raised in England and went to
Cambridge University. He began as a theater director, then became a
director-trainee at the BBC at 21. He spent seven years at the BBC,
starting with a soap opera and going on to direct the TV version of
``A Passage to India'' in 1965.
   ``When I came to Los Angeles the biggest thrill for me was seeing
the studio back lots,'' he said. ``I grew up with American movies.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, March 3-5</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890222-0228 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-89 0125EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     02-22 0890</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0930</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan said
the central bank will keep up its inflation-fighting efforts by
pushing interest rates higher to combat what he termed a troubling
acceleration in price pressures.
   Greenspan said Tuesday the Fed expects ``to support continued
economic expansion while putting in place conditions for a gradual
easing in the rate of inflation over time.''
   He added, however, ``the current rate of inflation, let alone an
increase, is not acceptable, and our policies are designed to reduce
inflation in coming years.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's plan for rescuing the savings
and loan industry is based on overly optimistic economic assumptions
and understates the program's true cost by billions of dollars,
private analysts said.
   The White House Office of Management Budget released figures
Tuesday showing long-term interest rates falling 3 percent in two
years to the lowest point in 20 years and savings and loan deposits
growing at an annual rate of 7.2 percent.
   If the administration's projections are off, the government will
have to spend hundreds of millions of dollars more a year to finance
the bailout.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A government regulatory agency concluded the
Chicago Board of Trade, the world's largest futures market, does a
poor job of detecting abuses and investigates potential violations
sluggishly.
   The Commodity Futures Trading Commission, which reviewed the
board of trade's performance from July 1987 to April 1988, said
Tuesday the board's routine computer surveillance program was ``not
properly tailored to efficiently identify potential trading abuses.''
   The report comes as a federal grand jury in Chicago is reviewing
evidence from a two-year FBI undercover investigation of widespread
alleged abuses at the CBOT and the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's chief tax collector told Congress
the system of federal tax penalties has swollen into a hodgepodge
the public finds hard to understand and the IRS difficult to
administer.
   In 1954, the law carried 14 penalties designed to encourage
taxpayer compliance, but now there are 150, Internal Revenue Service
Commissioner Lawrence B. Gibbs told a House Ways and Means
subcommittee Tuesday.
   The commissioner presented to the subcommittee the report of an
IRS task force recommending significant overhaul of the penalty
system.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BAL HARBOUR, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Labor Secretary Elizabeth Dole promised
to work with labor and piqued the interest of union leaders by
calling for a flexible pension system, but she also disagreed with
them on several issues.
   The tone of the first meeting between the AFL-CIO Executive
Council and Mrs. Dole Tuesday was amiable despite the differences, a
stark contrast with the first such session of the Reagan presidency.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>GLENVIEW, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Zenith Electronics Corp., the only domestic
television maker, reported its first annual profit in four years,
attributing the performance to booming computer sales and modest
growth in its consumer electronics division.
   Some industry analysts said Tuesday the $11.7 million in 1988 net
income could mark a turning point in the company's fortunes.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Polaroid Corp. announced its proposed
$1.1 billion stock buyback may include $325 million in privately
negotiated share purchases, which some analysts said were aimed at
the company's hostile suitor.
   The company, which announced Jan. 30 that it would undertake the
buyback, began a cash tender offer Tuesday for 16 million shares at
$50 a share in addition to the private purchases.
   The offer of private negotiations was seen by some as an
invitation to Shamrock Holdings Inc. of Burbank, Calif., which holds
a 6.7 percent stake in Polaroid and is pursuing a $3.2 billion
hostile takeover of the company.
</TEXT>
