<TEXT>
   Several independent oil producing countries said
they would cut or freeze oil exports during the second quarter to
help OPEC support world oil prices.
   The non-OPEC group, after meeting Tuesday in London, released a
statement saying more information was forthcoming but did not
disclose details of the agreement or say which countries would
participate.
   Oil analysts said the agreement would help bolster oil prices in
the short-term.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Compaq Computer Corp. announced it no longer will
market its products through Businessland Inc. stores in the wake of
a dispute with the huge retail chain.
   Businessland last year accounted for about 7 percent of the $2.1
billion in annual revenue for Compaq, a leading maker of desktop,
laptop and portable personsal computers.
   At the same time, sales of Compaq products accounted for about 15
percent of the $872 million in net sales during fiscal 1988 for
Businessland, which is based in San Jose, Calif.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The Dow Jones industrial average posted a tiny gain Tuesday but
broader market measures slumped in what some analysts said was a
reflection of deepening worries about inflation and interest rates.
The Dow Jones average eked out a gain of 1.61 points to close at
2,326.43.
   The dollar was mixed after Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan
Greenspan failed to signal a dramatic shift in U.S. monetary policy
in testimony to Congress.
   Bond prices ended slightly lower, pressured by the falling dollar
and some market disappointment with Greenspan's remarks.
   Copper futures prices posted their sharpest gains in three
months; gold futures rose sharply; cotton futures soared; livestock
and meat futures rallied; grains and soybeans were mixed; and energy
futures were mostly lower.
