<FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-89 0137EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-747Problems     02-22 0562</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-747 Problems,0581</SECOND>
<HEAD>Boeing Confident 747-400 Program Is Getting Back On Track</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Boeing Co. isn't looking for scapegoats to
blame for delays in its 747-400 jumbo-jet program, and instead is
concentrating on getting the project back on track, a Boeing
executive says.
   Some of the problems were simply ``unk-unks'' _ insider talk for
unknowns that can't be planned for, said Bruce Gissing, senior vice
president of Boeing Commercial Airplanes.
   Lengthy design, manufacturing and testing processes, along with
unanticipated airline demand, combined to slow production of what is
the world's largest commercial jetliner, Gissing said.
   ``It just blows my mind to try and figure out why we don't
predict this market better, but when you look at all the factors
that go into it, it's unbelievable that we can do as well as we
do,'' Gissing said in a recent interview. ``We are dealing with
thousands of things here that all must mesh together.''
   The delays forced Boeing to push back delivery dates by several
months for 57 of the 747s due out this year _ the first time in two
decades Boeing has failed to meet delivery deadlines.
   The first 747-400 was delivered in late January to Northwest
Airlines, about a month late. Other deliveries, including those to
Japan Airlines and United Airlines, are running about two months
late, Boeing has said. About 172 of the jets have been ordered.
   One problem delaying delivery is a shortage of workers at
Boeing's Everett plant, where the planes are assembled. To ease
this, Boeing is borrowing workers with needed skills from elsewhere
in the corporation, he said.
   Even so, Gissing said, substantial overtime will be needed until
the program stabilizes. The Everett plant employes about 17,000.
   Gissing declined to discuss specific problems with the $125
million, high-technology airplane, but said there were signs almost
from the start that the program would be behind schedule.
   The switch to a two-person cockpit, for example, required
electronic systems dramatically different from earlier 747 models,
which require a flight crew of three. Customers also wanted many
different configurations of the jet, including a choice of Pratt &amp;
Whitney, General Electric or Rolls-Royce engines.
   Each engine requires the 747 to gain a separate certification
from the Federal Aviation Administration.
   Gissing said the plane missed its FAA certification target date
in December.
   Some airlines have said publicly that they will seek compensation
from Boeing for the revenue lost by not taking delivery of the jets
on schedule.
   ``JAL is very upset about the delays, and I think that Boeing
should do something about that,'' said Tad Fujimatsu, a New York
spokesman for Japan Airlines, which learned recently that five of
its 20 747-400s on order would be delayed. ``Just exactly what that
will be is being negotiated by the head office now.''
   Industry watchers, however, say demands for compensation are
likely to be tempered by the airlines' need to preserve a long-term
relationship with the world's largest aircraft manufacturer.
   The 747-400 can be distinguished from other 747s by its curved
wingtips and extra-long upper deck. The jet, which can seat up to
509 passengers depending upon its configuration, promises reduced
fuel consumption, while its two-member flight crews will save on
employee costs.
   But critics of the jets, including some pilots' unions, have
questioned the safety of the smaller crews, which do without a
flight engineer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890222-0231 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-89 0147EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-AutoCredit     02-22 0584</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Auto Credit,0602</SECOND>
<HEAD>GM, Ford Try To Reduce Bad Car Loans With New Credit-Rating Systems</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's two biggest automakers, concerned
about rising default rates on car loans they offer through
subsidiaries, are trying to attact more credit-worthy buyers through
new loan programs.
   General Motors Acceptance Corp. is experimenting with a plan that
divides potential borrowers into three categories according to
credit risk, while Ford Motor Credit Corp. is engaged in a similar
plan.
   The GMAC system, which should be in place nationwide within the
next few months, gives dealers more flexibility in setting the
amount of monthly payments, GMAC spokesman John Andrews said Tuesday.
   ``It will afford us the opportunity of getting some
higher-quality customers,'' he said.
   Joy Wolfe, a spokeswoman for Ford Motor Credit, said the
automaker has been experimenting with a preferred customer plan
since last fall and hopes to make a decision this spring about
whether to implement it nationwide.
   The testing, she said, has been going on at 35 of the credit
company's 137 branches and covers up to a third of the Ford
dealerships nationwide.
   Jack Ferry, a spokesman for Chrysler Financial Corp., said the
lending arm of Chrysler Corp. envisioned no program similar to
Ford's or GM's.
   GM officials have declined to say how much they have lost on a
year-to-year basis because of bad loans, but have said their costs
are increasing. Last week, Andrews said GM had boosted its
automotive loan-loss reserve to about $1 billion in 1988, up 2.1
percent from 1987's reserve to cover bad loans.
   Under the GMAC Quality Finance Plan, a buyer provides a credit
history to the finance officer at a GM dealership and the buyer's
credit worthiness is determined. The buyer then is placed in either
an A, B or C category, with A the best loan risk and C the worst.
   Buyers in the A category, who usually have no trouble getting
loans, would be offered lower rates than the rates available under
conventional GMAC loans. B-level buyers would have rates roughly the
same as those determined under current GMAC policies.
   C-category buyers may be required to come up with additional
co-signers, higher down payments or higher monthly payments to
qualify for a GMAC loan.
   Interest rates for the categories vary from city to city and
could have a spread of 5 percentage points.
   The rates also can be affected by whether the dealership is a
recourse or non-recourse business. A recourse dealership would
guarantee a loan to GMAC. In other words, if the loan went sour, the
dealership would pick up the cost, reducing GMAC's potential loss
and keeping consumer rates down.
   A non-recourse dealer would share any bad loan costs with GMAC.
That obligation on GMAC's part would increase the rates to the buyer.
   Andrews said dealers will be briefed on the program during the
coming months, and, like participation in GMAC itself, have the
option of whether or not to join the program.
   One dealer who joined was Howard Chevrolet Inc. of West Roxbury,
Mass. There, finance manager Stu Sterling said it appears to be
working well.
   ``I can say with some certainty that I've saved about 10 percent
of the deals that I would have lost to a credit union,'' he said
Tuesday. ``When I'm able to show them a rate only off by a half a
percent, that the monthly payment will only change less than 50
cents, it's convenient for the customer.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890222-0232 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-89 0220EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Britain-Non-OPEC Bjt   02-22 0679</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Non-OPEC, Bjt,0704</SECOND>
<HEAD>Analysts: Oil Agreement Will Bolster Prices, But Not For Long</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An agreement among independent oil producers to cut
their oil exports unilaterally by an as-yet-unspecified amount
during the second quarter will help OPEC bolster oil prices in the
short-term, analysts say.
   But the agreement, reached Tuesday at a one-day meeting in
London, will have little impact on the buoyant supply and weak
demand in the oil market, the analysts said.
   ``I think it means the extension of the oil producers' cartel,
even if the countries don't want to commit themselves to OPEC at
this stage,'' said Philip Morgan, an oil analyst at the London
investment firm Citicorp Scrimgeour Vickers.
   There was little immediate reaction in the market. After the
group issued a communique early evening outlining its plans, the
spot price of North Sea Brent Blend, the most widely traded
international crude oil, was $16.30 a barrel, up 10 cents from late
Monday.
   The group of independent oil producers said that a majority of
its members agreed to cut their oil exports, but it didn't identify
them, nor did it say by how much. Other participants agreed to
freeze their exports, it said.
   ``Specific announcements with respect to the above decisions will
be made by the respective authorities in the course of next week,''
the group's communique said.
   Participating at talks at the Mexican Embassy were Mexico, Oman,
Malaysia, Egypt, China, and Angola, the communique said. Also
attending were observers from the Soviet Union, Colombia, North
Yemen, Norway, the U.S. state of Alaska and the Canadian province of
Alberta, it said.
   The agreement ``is fairly significant,'' Morgan said.
   It was important that the independent producers were acting
unilaterally, analysts said, doing so because the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries has managed to curb its production.
   Last year, independent oil producers offered to cut their output
by 5 percent if OPEC agreed to reciprocal cuts. OPEC refused.
   Some OPEC members have expressed resentment that independent
producers enjoy the benefits of the cartel's production limits
without making a contribution.
   OPEC's 13 members are estimated to be producing about 19.5
million barrels a day, 1 million barrels above their agreed
production limit but well below their fourth-quarter output. OPEC
has set a target price of $18 a barrel.
   ``The psychological impact (on the oil markets) will be quite
strong,'' Morgan said. But, he added,``I think the total volume of
the cuts makes little difference to the whole supply and demand
question.''
   James Henderson, an analyst at Barclays de Zoete Wedd Ltd. in
London, said: ``Basically, we see it as fairly positive for the oil
price short-term.
   ``Basically, it will help OPEC through the seasonal demand
downturn in the second quarter. We still see a dip in the oil price
but not as dramatically as it would have been.''
   Oil prices will fall to $14.50 to $15 a barrel in March and
April, Henderson predicted.
   The analyst said he expects the independent producers to cut
exports by 200,000 to 300,000 barrels a day in the April-June
quarter.
   But, he said, a reduction of up to 300,000 barrels ``isn't going
to have a dramatic effect on the supply and demand balance.''
   The communique also said some participants ``will go back to
their authorities for further consultations in order to determine
their contribution.''
   ``Further meetings of technical experts will be convened on a
regular basis in order to monitor the evolution of the market
situation as well as compliance with the agreement,'' the statement
said.
   The next such meeting was planned for May 16, and would ``also
address the prospects of the second half of the year, a period
viewed by the experts with caution.''
   ``The experts expressed the strong wish of their authorities to
see all oil-producing and exporting countries contributing to market
stability in a concerted way,'' it said.
   Individual delegates wouldn't elaborate when they emerged from
the meeting.
   OPEC's members are Algeria, Ecuador, Gabon, Indonesia, Iran,
Iraq, Kuwait, Libya, Nigeria, Qatar, Saudi Arabia, the United Arab
Emirates and Venezuela.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
