<FIRST>r f PM-FlagFlap     02-22 0476</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Flag Flap,0492</SECOND>
<HEAD>Label Switch Didn't Help Flagging Sales, Manager Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Harley Staggers and Harley Davidson in grafs 12 and 14 are cq.
A version moving on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHERINE RIZZO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Taiwanese company that offered ``Made in
USA'' labels to American distributors of its U.S. flags says it quit
the business because even that ploy didn't generate business.
   ``We stopped sales to the United States about two years ago
because our products were strongly rejected,'' Ni Feng-ming, general
manager of Ming Teh, told an interviewer in Taipei. ``I guess
Americans hate to see their national flag made by foreigners.''
   The Taiwanese government said Tuesday it was looking into the
label-switching allegations, which amount to a suggestion that
American importers violate U.S. country-of-origin labeling law.
   The U.S. Customs Service already is looking into the allegations.
   Both investigations were sparked in part by Rep. Douglas
Applegate, D-Ohio, who asked for the Customs investigation and
publicized the complaints of a Coshocton, Ohio, flag maker.
   The Colonial Flag Co. provided Applegate with a copy of the Ming
Teh solicitation, which says ``we can realize why you need'' to
remove the original label and replace it.
   ``If possible, we suggest you cut off this label after you
receive the goods and spend very little cost to mark on the flags
your own brand name and Made in U.S.A. signs,'' the 1987 letter
said. ``We can offer the labels too.''
   Ni, who said his company never changed the labels on its flags,
blamed the lack of response to the 1987 solicitation on U.S.
protectionism. The company now makes national flags for Canada,
Japan, West Germany and Australia, he said.
   Victor Chin, a spokesman for the Taiwanese government office in
Washington, confirmed Tuesday that country's Board of Foreign Trade
is looking into the matter. He predicted quick action as ``an
example to other companies.''
   ``We are very concerned,'' he said. ``We are concerned about our
image, naturally, but we are also concerned about our free trade
practices.
   ``I assume something will happen this week,'' Chin said.
   Also Tuesday, Rep. Harley Staggers Jr., D-W.Va., resubmitted
legislation that would require that all U.S. flags be made in the
United States.
   ``I am asking that my colleagues help me to keep our Stars and
Stripes raised in the battle against the exploitation of foreign
countries,'' said Staggers, who told the House some imported flags
violate the U.S. Flag Code.
   ``I have, for example, a U.S. flag that was made in Taiwan,'' he
said. ``Superimposed upon it is a Harley Davidson motorcycle with
the words `High Times' written across the gas tank.''
   Chin, an assistant in the public affairs arm of the Coordination
Council for North American Affairs, said the Taiwanese government
didn't want to comment on the potential impact of the ban sought by
Staggers.
</TEXT>
