<FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-89 0756EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Iraq-Economy 1stLd-Writethru f0013 02-22 0873</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iraq-Economy, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0013,0903</SECOND>
<HEAD>Postwar Iraq Faces Economic Problems</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: To delete INCORRECT reference to amount Iraq owes creditors,
SUB 6th graf, Creditors who ... little interest. Picks up 7th pvs, The
economic ... A version moving on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NEIL MacFARQUHAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the week after the shooting stopped in
their war with Iran, Iraqis went on a $318-million shopping spree in
state-run stores. They bought up television sets, refrigerators and
other luxury items the government released from warehouses.
   Six months later, the state-run stores are closed to
non-government employees and their shelves are empty. One recently
had only a few light sockets in its electrical department.
   Iraqis are beginning to realize that the $60 billion to $70
billion their country borrowed during the 8-year Persian Gulf war is
going to affect their wallets for a long time.
   No one has come forward to help finance reconstruction, although
neighboring Kuwait has said it might offer some aid.
   Creditors are pressing hard for repayment. New laws designed to
attract private money from Iraqis and from around the Arab world
have attracted little interest.
   ``The economic situation's very bad. Salaries are low and prices
go up and up,'' said Mukhtar, 34, who recently started a chicken
farm to try to supplement his family's government incomes.
   ``I think things will stay bad because they have to pay for the
war. It may be five to seven years before it gets better.''
   Diplomats conjecture that Iraq is spreading the estimated $10
billion to $12 billion a year it earns from oil exports too thinly
by trying to pay for reconstruction, buy expensive armaments,
develop heavy industry, meet consumer demands and pay off its debts.
   Iraqi officials maintain the problems are short-term and that the
economy will eventually refloat on the 100 billion barrels of oil
lying under their feet.
   ``I'm optimistic that the price of oil will hold and Iraq will
remain an important oil-producing country for at least the next
century,'' said deputy Foreign Minister Nizar Hamdoon.
   ``Our resources are quite sufficient to pay the debts back. It's
just a question of time.''
   Hamdoon confirmed reports that Iraq will not have to pay back aid
from Saudi Arabia and Kuwait, estimated by diplomats at about $30
billion.
   ``Our Arab brothers are very considerate of the fact that Iraq
was defending not just its own interests, but the interests of those
countries,'' he said.
   Diplomats said private suppliers in the Persian Gulf, however,
were balking at writing off an estimated $6 billion to $8 billion in
goods supplied on credit, but the Kuwaiti government might step in
to pay that bill.
   Hamdoon called the $60-billion debt figure ``exaggerated.'' But
the government will not release any exact figure.
   Diplomats say uncertainty over the size of the debt, an
overvalued dinar currency and a lack of trust in the government's
commitment to the private sector are all factors keeping investors
away.
   ``Arab investors really want the Iraqis to open their books, to
say what their debts are,'' said one diplomat.
   Potential investors dislike the discrepancy between the official
and free market currency exchange rates and worry about the
availability of foreign exchange, diplomats said.
   The Iraqi dinar sells for about 50 cents on open markets in
neighboring countries, but Baghdad fixes its worth at $3.
   Investors have to exchange at least 50 percent of their foreign
currency at that official rate.
   In addition, foreign exchange can be hard to find, especially
with an estimated 2 million Egyptian workers in the country who can
legally send home about $2 billion a year.
   Harsh attacks in the press on steep price increases caused by
businessmen passing on the cost of the official exchange rate have
not encouraged investors.
   The price of an automobile tire, for example, went from 14 dinars
($42) to 100 dinars ($300) when private importers took over and
thefts shot up. Prices like 625 dinars ($1,875 at the official
exchange rate) for a small color television unleashes consumer
charges of extortion. Government salaries have been fixed at about
150 dinars ($450) a month since the beginning of the war.
   Iraqi consumers are also railing against shoddy local
merchandise, complaining about everything from heaters that don't
heat to perfume that has no scent.
   President Saddam Hussein's privatization program aimed at
increasing efficiency and luring back billions of dollars held
abroad has met with limited success, with an estimated 30 to 40
percent of the state-run companies put on the block actually sold.
   Small factories have been snapped up, but items like luxury
hotels at $50 million each remain largely unsold. State television
nightly runs 10 minutes of ads for government enterprises on sale.
   The state retains control of 80 percent of the economy and plans
to keep control of heavy industry and the oil sector, with the
exception of gasoline stations.
   In the meantime, Iraqis remain starved for goods.
   Arab tradition dictates that when a friend admires something you
own, you offer it to him, but the offer is customarily refused.
   An Iraqi visiting from Los Angeles said he offered his Ray-Ban
sunglasses, a crocodile leather belt and an Olympus camera to
friends in Iraq.
   They took them.
</TEXT>
