<FIRST>r f PM-Pennwalt-Centaur     02-22 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pennwalt-Centaur,0316</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pennwalt Rejects Centaur's $110 Per Share Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pennwalt Corp. says it will consider further
restructuring or seek a buyer rather than accept Centaur Partner's
$869 million takeover bid.
   In rejecting the $110-a-share offer Tuesday, Pennwalt repeated
earlier allegations that Centaur lacked necessary funding and that
the investor group was looking for short-term profits rather than an
acquisition by driving up Pennwalt's stock price.
   ``The board expressed the view that alternatives superior to the
Centaur offer exist,'' said Edwin E. Tuttle, chairman of the
Philadelphia-based Pennwalt. ``The board believes that in light of
the restructuring work commenced in March 1988, it would be
inappropriate to sell Pennwalt to Centaur at $110 per share.''
   The company said its management and the investment firm Goldman,
Sachs &amp; Co. will study the possibility of selling Pennwalt to
someone else or further restructuring. The company already sold its
pharmaceutical division and most of its equipment businesses in
fighting the takeover attempt.
   ``We will wait to see what proposal, if any, is offered by
Goldman Sachs and Pennwalt,'' Centaur spokesman Jerry Seeman said in
a statement. ``We intend to continue on our course of bringing our
acquisition proposal to shareholders of Pennwalt for a determination
of whether they will support it.''
   Centaur has forced Pennwalt to call a special stockholders
meeting March 30, when the investment firm will try to replace the
board with members who support the takeover.
   Centaur, based in New York and Bethesda, Md., on Feb. 14
increased its 2-month-old, $100-per-share offer to $110 for the
6,982,000 shares of outstanding Pennwalt stock it does not already
own.
   The latest offer is due to expire March 6.
   Pennwalt, which was trading for about $70 per share in June 1988
when Centaur first made its intentions known, closed at $118.25 per
share Tuesday, up $3.37{.
</TEXT>
