<FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-89 0916EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-WorldsOfWonder     02-22 0572</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Worlds Of Wonder,0590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Toy Manufacturer Says It Has Agreed To Be Sold</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FREMONT, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An investor trying to buy the Baltimore
Orioles also is heading efforts to buy Worlds of Wonder Inc., the
toy company that rocketed to fleeting success with the talking bear
Teddy Ruxpin.
   The company, which filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection 14
months ago, announced Tuesday it reached a ``definitive'' agreement
to sell the company to a group of New York investors headed by Eli
Jacobs.
   The sale, for an undisclosed amount, is subject to U.S.
Bankruptcy Court approval, but Worlds of Wonder had ``no
expectation'' the plan would not be approved, said Anne Jordan, the
company's general counsel.
   The investors headed by Jacobs, the majority stockholder of a
group buying the Orioles, plan to continue operating Worlds of
Wonder in Fremont under the same name, the company said.
   ``It allows the company to move forward with the plans for a
revitalized business, which we developed over the past year,''
Stephen J. Hopkins, Worlds of Wonder chairman and chief executive
officer said in a statement.
   Hopkins, a corporate turnaround specialist hired after founder
and president Donald Kingsborough resigned at the request of
creditors last year, also said he was pleased with Worlds of
Wonder's showing at the recent Toy Fair in New York.
   Analysts could not immediately be reached for comment after the
Tuesday afternoon announcement.
   In addition to Jacobs _ whose efforts to buy the Orioles must
still be approved by major league owners _ the investment group
includes Franklyn S. Barry Jr., former president of Fisher-Price
Toys, and David Edelman, former president of Ingram Software.
   Once the reorganization plan is approved, a newly formed company
formed by the investors will acquire the toy company's assets for an
undisclosed amount of cash, notes and preferred stock.
   Proceeds from the sale will go to its secured creditors, Algemene
Bank Nederland and Fist National Bank of Chicago, lead bank for a
group of five financial institutions, the company said.
   The new company plans to issue its own stock, which would be
issued only to the investors and creditors, Jordan said.
   The company, founded in a trailer in 1985, saw its sales jump to
$300 million within two years with novel, high-tech toys, including
Teddy Ruxpin and Lazer Tag, in which players ``shot'' each other
with beams of infrared light.
   But the company became plagued by lagging sales and production
and delivery problems. It suffered heavy losses and filed for
bankruptcy protection in December 1987. The company said in its
Chapter 11 filing that it had $312.1 million in liabilities against
$313.6 million in assets.
   Worlds of Wonder, which continued to promote new toys, including
the Skip Stik, a version of the jump rope, announced late last year
it was talking with investors about a possible sale.
   The company has been negotiating the agreement with Jacobs and
the other investors for the past few weeks, Jordan said.
   Just before it filed for Chapter 11 protection, Worlds of Wonder
employed about 500 people. About 120 people now work for the company.
   ``I think the expectation is that the new investors will build up
the company, and if that happens they probably need to increase (the
workforce),'' Jordan said.
   The company hoped to file a reorganization plan with the
Bankruptcy Court in Oakland during the next few weeks and expected
confirmation hearings within a few months, she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
