<SECOND>PM-Champion Spark Plug, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0041,0450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Champion, Cooper Boards Approve Takeover</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: To UPDATE with Dana comment, SUBS 5th graf pvs, Dana, an...
with 2 new grafs. Picks up 6th graf pvs, Under terms...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MITCH WEISS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOLEDO, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Champion Spark Plug Co., the world's largest
spark plug producer, could become part of diversified manufacturer
Cooper Industries Inc. this spring under a $800 million cash buyout
agreement.
   The acquisition, which is expected to begin Thursday and be
completed by May 1, was approved Tuesday by the board of directors
of both companies, said Ellen Myers, a Cooper spokeswoman.
   Chinook Partners L.P., established in 1986 by the founding
Stranahan family to maintain a dominant voice in Champion's affairs,
has not publicly stated whether it would approve Cooper's offer.
Chinook controls 35 percent of Champion's common stock.
   Champion had terminated an earlier agreement to be acquired by
Dana Corp., which had offered to purchase the company for $590
million in cash and stock, or $17.50 a share.
   Dana, an automotive parts giant, today confirmed the termination
of its agreement with Champion and said it does not intend to make a
new offer.
   ``It's not in the best interests of our shareholders to go
higher,'' said Southwood J. Morcott, Dana President. ``We are unable
to identify potential values in the combination that would justify
an increased price.''
   Under terms of the latest agreement, Houston-based Cooper will
pay $21 a share in cash for all of Champion's 33.6 million common
shares outstanding. The deal, including debt reduction legal fees
and other considerations, brings the total purchase price to about
$800 million, Ms. Myers said.
   Champion stock closed at $22.25 a share Tuesday, down 37.5 cents
on the New York Stock Exchange.
   William Prebe, an automotive industry analyst and former Dana
vice president, said he does not expect Cooper to make any changes
at Champion for at least a year.
   ``I think they (Cooper) will begin to absorb their name into
their parts network. I think things will remain pretty much as they
are for at least a year. After a period of time, they will determine
what they will do with the Toledo operation,'' he said.
   Champion is the world's leading manufacturer of spark plugs for
all types of internal combustion engines. It also makes Anco
windshield wiper blades and a variety of other fuel system and
automotive maintenance parts. It has annual revenue of about $720
million and employs about 9,200 people worldwide.
   Cooper, with 1988 revenue of $4.3 billion, is a diversified,
worldwide manufacturer of products from the electricial, electronic,
commercial, industrial, compression and drilling markets.
</TEXT>
