<FIRST>d f BC-SouthKorea-Trade     02-22 0167</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-South Korea-Trade,0173</SECOND>
<HEAD>South Korea Regrets Possible U.S. Trade Sanctions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Korea expressed regret Wednesday
over a U.S. government decision that could lead to trade sanctions
for alleged barriers blocking U.S. sales of telecommunications
equipment here.
   ``We deeply regret the U.S. government's designation of South
Korea as a country to open negotiations,'' targeting it for possible
trade sanctions, a Foreign Ministry statement said.
   The statement urged the United States to be more prudent in
applying the 1988 Trade Act.
   Trade Representative Carla Hills announced Tuesday the U.S.
government has designated South Korea and the European Economic
Community for possible trade sanctions if they fail to lower
barriers against U.S. telecommunications equipment.
   Hills reportedly took the action following a five-month
investigation under the law, which requires the United States to
open negotiations with countries considered to be blocking sales by
American exporters.
   If negotiations don't succeed in removing trade barriers within a
year, the law requires U.S. officials to impose trade sanctions.
</TEXT>
