<TEXT>
   Stock prices fell today, weighed down by a
government report that consumer prices rose in January at the
highest rate in two years.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials fell 7.14 to 2,319.29 in
the first half-hour of trading.
   Declining issues led advancers 9 to 5 on the New York Stock
Exchange, with 337 higher, 604 lower and 514 unchanged.
   Big Board volume came to 22.98 million as of 10 a.m. EST.
   The Labor Department said the 0.6 percent rise in consumer prices
in January was propelled by higher costs for gasoline, poultry,
fish, eggs and tobacco. It followed moderate increases of 0.3
percent in both November and December.
   The January price increase, which is seasonally adjusted, would
amount to an annual inflation rate of 7.2 percent if the pace for
the first month of 1989 held throughout the year.
   Utilities involved in dividend plays accounted for most of the
early volume leaders on the NYSE.
   Among other issues, Champion Spark Plug was off 1] at 20~.
Champion said Tuesday it had signed a definitive agreement to be
acquired by Cooper Industries for 21 a share, convincing some
investors that a bidding war for the company was over.
   Texas Eastern was off [ at 52\. It had jumped 3~ in heavy trading
on Tuesday after Panhandle Eastern began a tender offer for 80
percent of its stock at 53 a share and Coastal, a rival bidder, said
it was weighing its options.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was
down 0.54 at 165.52. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index was down 0.63 at 324.23.
   On Tuesday, the Dow Jones industrial average rose 1.61 points to
2,326.43.
   But declining issues outnumbered gainers by nearly 3 to 2 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
611 up, 872 down and 505 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 141.95 million
shares, down from 159.52 million in the previous session.
