<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   02-22 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0302</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Demand Boosts Wheat Market</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Signs of higher export demand boosted grain and
soybean futures prices this morning on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   The wheat market was the leader in early trading, with buy orders
prompted partly by indications that the Soviet Union was bidding for
400,000 metric tons of the U.S. wheat it agreed to buy at subsidized
prices under a long-term grain pact signed late last year.
   An Agriculture Department report showing unexpectedly high wheat
exports last week also contributed to the bullish tone, analysts
said.
   The USDA reported Tuesday that 39 million bushels of wheat had
been inspected for export last week, about 15 million bushels more
than the market had expected.
   Prices of other grain and soybean futures rose in sympathy with
wheat, analysts said.
   In early trading, wheat was 1} cents to 3\ cents higher with
March at $4.27} a bushel; corn was } cent to 1} cents higher with
March at $2.71 a bushel; oats were unchanged to 3 cents higher with
May at $2.20{ a bushel; soybeans were 1 cent to 1} cents higher with
March at $7.47{ a bushel.
   Cattle futures were mostly lower while pork futures were higher
in early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .20 cent lower to .03 cent higher with April at
77.72 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .38 cent lower to .10 cent
higher with March at 84.17 cents a pound; live hogs were .05 cent to
.37 cent higher with April at 43.15 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .05 cent to .28 cent higher with March at 38.90 cents a
pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled higher on Tuesday.
</TEXT>
