<DOCNO> AP890222-0245 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-89 1157EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Fed-Economy 1stLd-Writethru f0020 02-22 0798</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fed-Economy, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0020,0817</SECOND>
<HEAD>Greenspan Intensifies Inflation Warnings</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Tops with 7 grafs of today's testimony, picks up 4th graf pvs,
``The Fed has ... This also moved on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan
intensified his warnings about growing inflationary pressures today,
labeling ``disturbing'' a new report which showed consumer prices
shot up in January at their fastest pace in two years.
   Greenspan, who was appearing for the second consecutive day of
congressional testimony on the central bank's handling of monetary
policy, referred to a government report released earlier in the day
showing that consumer prices climbed by 0.6 percent in January,
spurred by higher costs for food and energy.
   Greenspan said that a recent acceleration in wage increases was
probably the reason that prices at the consumer level were beginning
to climb more rapidly.
   Appearing before a House Banking subcommittee, Greenspan repeated
his belief that the economy is not currently in danger of a
recession. But, he said, if inflation is allowed to get out of hand
the next downturn could come suddenly.
   ``If inflation re-emerges, I think a recession will move up on us
much more quickly than we can imagine and when it occurs it will be
a prolonged one,'' he said.
   Greenspan's warning put further distance between the central bank
and the Bush administration, which has sought to play down fears
that the country was about to embark on a new inflationary spiral.
   President Bush on several occasions has said he believes the
Fed's efforts to push interest rates higher are an overreaction and
run the danger of slowing economic growth.
   The Fed has so far ignored the comments, putting in place just
last week another round of credit-tightening. Consumer prices rose
4.4 percent in 1988, and the latest Fed move followed an unusually
bad inflation report on wholesale prices in January.
   ``Let me stress that the current rate of inflation, let alone an
increase, is not acceptable, and our policies are designed to reduce
inflation in coming years,'' Greenspan told the Senate Budget
Committee on Tuesday.
   The credit-tightening moves come at a particularly delicate time
for the Bush administration, which based its $1.16 trillion 1990
federal budget on assumptions that the economy would continue
growing at a robust rate with interest rates declining significantly.
   That economic forecast has been roundly criticized. Rep. Leon
Panetta, D-Calif. and chairman of the House Budget Committee, said
Tuesday that the Bush assumptions are more optimistic than even the
``rosy scenario'' used by David Stockman in preparing Ronald
Reagan's first budget in 1981.
   Panetta told Michael Boskin, Bush's chief economic adviser, that
wildly inflated economic assumptions ``will come back to haunt us,
and you, in August'' when the administration is required to reassess
the performance of the economy to determine whether mandatory
across-the-board spending cuts will automatically take effect.
   The Bush budget is based on an assumption that economic growth
will accelerate to an annual rate of 3.5 percent this year, up from
2.7 percent growth in 1988, as measured from the fourth quarter of
the previous year.
   In economic assumptions released Tuesday, Greenspan said the Fed
is tailoring its policies to support economic growth of between 2.5
percent and 3 percent in 1989, a top range that would be a full
one-half percentage point below the administration's estimate.
   Nonetheless, both Greenspan and the administration tried to
minimize their disagreements, with both sides listing prompt action
to trim the federal budget deficit as the No. 1 economic priority.
   Greenspan said the important thing is for Congress and the
administration to reach agreement quickly on a credible, multi-year
program to reduce the budget deficit, which is expected to hit $163
billion this year. He said such action would reassure financial
markets and allow interest rates to decline.
   Boskin, testifying before the House Budget Committee, maintained
that the Fed's monetary policies are generally consistent with the
administration's expectations for economic growth.
   He also said he did not see any problem on the horizon that
threatens to end the six-year economic recovery, the longest in
peacetime history.
   ``We are now at a point in the expansion where an acceleration of
inflation is a greater risk than it was earlier,'' Boskin said.
``This risk is real and we certainly do not want inflation to drift
up into the 7, 9 or finally double-digit rates we saw in the 1970s.''
   The central bank has been pushing interest rates higher since
March of last year, an effort which has sent a variety of short-term
interest rates climbing by about 3 percent. The Fed believes that it
is critical to dampen demand by increasing the costs of borrowing in
light of the nation's tight labor markets and high factory operating
rates.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
