<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Pulitzer     02-22 0275</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Pulitzer,0284</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pulitzer Announces 34 Percent Increase In Net Income</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pulitzer Publishing Co. on Wednesday reported a
34 percent increase in its fourth-quarter profit, due partly to
increased revenue from the company's broadcasting division.
   ``Fourth-quarter results were encouraging with cash flow from
operations up almost 17 percent, reflecting a strong revenue
performance from broadcasting and the benefit of expense controls in
publishing and broadcasting,'' said Joseph Pulitzer Jr., chairman of
the board.
   ``Television revenues were up approximately 9 percent for the
quarter, partly as a result of the Summer Olympics, which aired on
the company's three NBC affiliates, and political advertising,'' he
said.
   The company reported fourth-quarter after-tax income was $7.7
million, or 73 cents a share, on revenue of $106 million, compared
with net income of $5.7 million, or 55 cents a share, on revenue of
$99.3 million in the same period last year.
   The company said net income for the year increased 28 percent to
$19.6 million, or $1.88 a share, from $15.3 million, or $1.46 a
share, the year before. Revenue increased to $391 million from $367
million in 1987.
   The company publishes the St. Louis Post-Dispatch and The Arizona
Daily Star in Tucson, Ariz., and newspapers and shoppers in the
Chicago area, including the Southtown Economist and The Daily
Calumet, daily and Sunday newspapers.
   The company's broadcasting operations consist of seven
network-affiliated television stations: WYFF in Greenville, S.C.;
WGAL in Lancaster, Pa.; WXII in Winston-Salem, N.C.; KOAT in
Albuquerque, N.M.; KETV in Omaha, Neb.; WLKY in Louisville, Ky.; and
WPTA in Fort Wayne, Ind. The company also owns two radio stations,
KTAR-AM and KKLT-FM, in Phoenix.
</TEXT>
