<FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-89 1339EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-Britain-Stocks 1stLd-Writethru   02-22 0208</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0214</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Stocks Close Sharply Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Persistent concern about inflation and the course
of worldwide interest rates combined with a weak early performance
on Wall Street drove London stock prices sharply lower Wednesday.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index was down 27.3
points, or 1.3 percent, at 2,033.7, the day's lowest level. At its
best, the index was down 4.4 points.
   Volume was little changed from the previous day at 547.8 million
shares, compared with Tuesday's 543.3 million shares.
   Sparking the latest bout of nerves was news of a 0.6 percent rise
in U.S. consumer prices in January and a subsequent comment by
Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan that he found the increase
disturbing.
   In addition, further declines in the level of the British pound
against the West German mark were taken to mean the government had
room to leave interest rates high for the time being.
   But the widespread declines in equities took place in light
trading volume. What institutional selling there was was met by
reciprocal buying interest. Markdowns by market makers accounted for
much of the price falls, dealers said.
   ``The momentum isn't really there this week. People are willing
to stand on the sidelines,'' one dealer said.
</TEXT>
