<SECOND>BC-Dollar-Gold,0285</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Varied In Europe, Gold Higher</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: AMs version planned by 5:30 p.m. EST</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar fell against most major currencies
in European trading Wednesday. Gold prices were higher and rose in
London by more than $5.
   Foreign exchange dealers said trading was fairly quiet.
   Traders were unhappy because they believe the U.S. interest rate
is not going to be raised soon, dealers said. Higher rates make the
currency more attractive for buyers.
   The feeling was influenced by Congressional testimony by U.S.
Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan who said he was satisfied
with the dollar's current levels despite a ``disturbing'' increase
in retail prices.
   The British pound came under pressure from a strong West German
mark. One pound was one cent cheaper for buyers in London than on
Tuesday, costing $1.7465 late Wednesday compared with $1.7565.
   Other rates for the dollar in Europe late Wednesday compared with
Tuesday's late rates: 1.8380 West German marks, down from 1.8420;
1.5667 Swiss francs, down from 1.5685; 6.2625 French francs, down
from 6.2735; 2.0725 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0910; 1,350.50
Italian lire, down from 1,356.00; 1.1965 Canadian dollars, up from
1.1897.
   Earlier in Tokyo the dollar eased to 126.62 Japanese yen, down
from 127.15. In London late Wednesday the dollar traded higher at
126.65.
   The late bid price for gold in London, the major center, was
$386.30 a troy ounce, up from $380.75. Zurich's late bid price was
$386.25 dollars, up from $383.00
   Earlier in Hong Kong, gold closed at $387.51 dollars bid, up from
$384.34.
   Silver bullion traded late in London at $5.97 dollars a troy
ounce, up from $5.93.
</TEXT>
