<FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-89 1511EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet3pm     02-22 0457</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 3pm,0481</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices tumbled today after the government
reported a big jump in consumer prices and Federal Reserve Chairman
Alan Greenspan said he found recent inflation trends ``disturbing.''
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials dropped below the 2,300
level, falling 32.14 to 2,294.29 an hour before the close.
   Declining issues led advancers nearly 4 to 1 on the New York
Stock Exchange, with 314 higher, 1,190 lower and 439 unchanged.
   Big Board volume came to 142.32 million shares as of 3 p.m. EST.
   The Labor Department said consumer prices rose 0.6 percent in
January, the biggest monthly increase in two years.
   The increase was propelled by higher costs for gasoline, poultry,
fish, eggs and tobacco. It followed moderate increases of 0.3
percent in both November and December.
   ``We're beginning to get a stronger inflationary tone,''
Greenspan said today in testimony before the House Banking Committee.
   Traders feared Greenspan would push up interest rates even higher
to squelch inflation. That would tend to draw money away from stocks
and into high-yielding debt securities.
   ``There has been a lot of optimism built into the market and
you're seeing some of that come out,'' said John Candela, head of
fixed-income and commodities trading at Ladenburg, Thalmann &amp; Co.
   The January price increase, which is seasonally adjusted, would
amount to an annual inflation rate of 7.2 percent if the pace for
the first month of 1989 held throughout the year.
   Utilities involved in dividend plays accounted for most of the
volume leaders on the NYSE.
   Among other stocks, Champion Spark Plug was off 1\ at 21.
Champion said Tuesday it had signed a definitive agreement to be
acquired by Cooper Industries for 21 a share, convincing some
investors that a bidding war for the company was over.
   Texas Eastern was unchanged at 52]. It had jumped 3~ in heavy
trading on Tuesday after Panhandle Eastern began a tender offer for
80 percent of its stock at 53 a share and Coastal, a rival bidder,
said it was weighing its options.
   In over-the-counter trading, MiniScribe was off { at 4 in heavy
volume of more than 4.6 million shares on rumors that a supplier had
cut off supplies because of non-payment of bills.
   Warren Perry, manager of investor relations for the Longmont,
Colo.-based computer disk drive maker, said the rumors were
unfounded. MiniScribe posted a big fourth-quarter loss and projected
operating losses for the first half of 1989.
   Separately, the company said Q.T. Wiles had resigned as its
chairman and chief executive, effective immediately.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was
down 2.02 at 164.04. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index was down 2.91 at 321.95.
</TEXT>
