<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   02-22 0198</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0207</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soybeans Surge In Technical Rally</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices closed sharply higher
Wednesday on the Chicago Board of Trade in a surge attributed to
technical factors in the absence of significant supply-and-demand
developments.
   Corn and wheat futures also advanced while oat futures prices
fell slightly.
   The soybean complex repeated a pattern established Tuesday.
Soybean oil prices rallied first on buying by speculators who trade
mainly on chart interpretations. That triggered sympathetic buying
in the soybean and soybean meal markets.
   ``It was a very firm close overall,'' said Victor Lespinasse, a
trader with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in Chicago.
   Wheat futures were supported by signs of heightened export
demand, including talk that the Soviet Union had submitted a bid for
400,000 metric tons of U.S. wheat at subsidized prices.
   At the close, wheat was { cent to 2{ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in March at $4.26\ a bushel; corn was
unchanged to 3{ cents higher with March at $2.73\ a bushel; oats
were unchanged to 2 cents lower with March at $2.13 a bushel;
soybeans were 4\ cents to 9{ cents higher with March at $7.55 a
bushel.
