<FIRST>r f AM-Hewlett-Packard-3Com     02-22 0253</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hewlett-Packard-3Com,0264</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hewlett-Packard To Form Alliance, Buy Up to 5 Percent of 3Com</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hewlett-Packard Co. said Wednesday it would form
an alliance with 3Com Corp. and buy 5 percent of the computer
networking company.
   Hewlett-Packard and 3Com said they would work together to network
software that allows different brands of personal computers and
workstations to share information and programs.
   3Com, based in Santa Clara, Calif., is a leading maker of local
area networks for personal computers. Hewlett-Packard, the
Cupertino, Calif.-based electronics giant, makes minicomputers and
personal computers.
   Hewlett-Packard will buy 5 percent of 3Com's shares on the open
market at the prevailing market price, Hewlett-Packard spokesman Roy
Verley said. He said acquisitions beyond 5 percent, if any, would be
announced.
   3Com stock edged up 25 cents a share to $26.75 a share in late
over-the-counter trading Wednesday.
   As part of their alliance, the companies will work to make it
easier for personal computers that are connected in a 3Com local
area network to get information stored on a Hewlett-Packard
minicomputer, Verley said.
   The companies said they would jointly promote the use of
Microsoft Corp.'s LAN Manager technology for connecting different
kinds of computers. 3Com already has a version of the software that
it has developed in cooperation with Microsoft, and Hewlett-Packard
will bring out a version based on the 3Com system, the companies
said.
   Some future releases of 3Com products will have the same screen
appearance, or ``look and feel,'' as Hewlett-Packard's New Wave
format, the companies said.
</TEXT>
