<FIRST>r f AM-MarvinWarner     02-22 0281</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Marvin Warner,0292</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former S&amp;L Owner Gets Another Reprieve From Jail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Home State Savings Bank owner Marvin L.
Warner won a reprieve from jail Wednesday, nearly two years after
his conviction on charges arising from the collapse of the savings
and loan.
   The 1st Ohio District Court of Appeals ordered the Hamilton
County Common Pleas Court to hear Warner's request for a new trial.
Warner is alleging that juror misconduct at his 1987 trial
prejudiced the case.
   The appeals court rejected the argument by the state that Warner
waited too long to ask for a new trial.
   Warner was convicted in March 1987 of nine criminal charges
arising from the March 1985 collapse of Home State, a privately
insured Cincinnati-based savings and loan.
   At the time, Home State owed depositors more than $144 million as
a result of bad investments through securities transactions with ESM
Government Securities Inc. of Fort Lauderdale, Fla.
   Warner, a millionaire now living in Ocala, Fla., immediately
appealed the conviction and sentence. He was sentenced to 3{ years
in prison and ordered to pay $22 million in restitution to Ohio to
cover the costs of protecting Home State deposits.
   More than a month after the trial, Warner's wife, Jody,
interviewed two jurors who said a third juror's mother-in-law had an
account at Home State. Warner's lawyers argue that the juror would
have been disqualified if the information had been known during jury
selection.
   Home State's collapse caused a crisis for 69 other privately
insured Ohio savings and loans whose deposits were insured by the
same private agency. Gov. Richard Celeste temporarily closed the
S&amp;Ls and ordered them to obtain federal deposit insurance.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
