<FIRST>r f AM-SteelImports     02-22 0386</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Steel Imports,0399</SECOND>
<HEAD>Material Handlers Ask Investigation Of Steel-Import Limit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HERBERT G. McCANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials of the material handling industry asked
President Bush on Wednesday to appoint a commission to study how a
voluntary steel import limit has affected domestic steel prices.
   The voluntary restraint agreement was enacted by Congress five
years ago to restrict the import of foreign steel and help the
domestic steel industry recover from a slump.
   ``We support a strong domestic steel industry,'' said Albert
Leffler, chief executive officer of the Material Handling Industry
of America, a trade group representing tractor, lift truck and robot
manufacturers. ``But we feel something is wrong.''
   Leffler said the reduced manufacturing capacity of domestic
steelmakers and reduced imports have caused steel shortages and
higher steel prices, putting his industry at the mercy of the steel
industry.
   ``The little guy can't question price and quality at the same
time,'' Leffler said during a conference at the industry's trade
show here. ``He has to take what the steel industry gives him.''
   Officials of the material handling industry say steel prices for
U.S. manufacturers rose 17 percent in 1988, while prices for the
auto industry increased only 4 percent.
   Leffler said the material handling industry, which consumes about
15 percent of domestic steel, wants to see some modification in the
restraint agreement.
   He agreed that the U.S. steel industry is healthier since the
enactment of the voluntary restraint agreement. But he said recent
productivity gains by the industry may have been produced by closing
obsolete plants and by the devalued dollar.
   ``Though the VRA program started with the best intentions, it has
created a cartel-like atmosphere that is charged with opportunity
for abuse,'' Leffler said. ``The small customer without a voice will
get lost in the cheers for Big Steel's success.''
   A bill authorizing the extention of the voluntary restraint
agreement is currently before Congress.
   ``We realize that President Bush and many members of Congress are
supporting the extension of the restraint agreement in the fall of
1989, but they have the time now to rethink and modify the program
before it is too late,'' Laffer said.
   He said representatives of the trade group will meet with
congressional representatives of steel producing states to try to
influence them to modify the agreement.
</TEXT>
