<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0546</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Lower; Gold Gains</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON-BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell against most major foreign
currencies Wednesday as dealers weighed the implications of a
government report showing consumer prices rose sharply during
January.
   Gold prices gained, driven higher by the inflation report. Prices
for the precious metal rose by more than $5 an ounce in London.
Later, Republic National Bank of New York quoted a gold at a bid of
$386.40 a troy ounce at 4 p.m. EST, up 90 cents from Tuesday's late
bid.
   The Labor Department said consumer prices surged 0.6 percent in
January, the highest montly rate in two years. Last month's rise
doubled the more modest 0.3 percent increases in November and
December.
   Mary Anne Tompkins, a foreign exchange trader at Barclays Bank
PLC in New York, said the inflation report intensified market
speculation that U.S. interest rates will be hiked to slow inflation.
   Higher U.S. interest rates raise the value of dollar-denominated
investments.
   But in the meantime, many dealers seem to be focusing their
attention on the strong West German economy and British economic
prospects.
   The dollar slid against the West German mark, falling below
levels considered key thresholds at which the U.S. currency would
find support. The dollar fell to 1.8380 marks in London from 1.8420
marks late Tuesday. Later in New York, the dollar fell to 1.83425
marks from 1.8440 marks on Tuesday.
   The British pound came under pressure from the mark's strength.
The pound fell in London to $1.7465 late Wednesday from $1.7565 late
Tuesday. In later New York dealings, sterling dipped to $1.7470 from
Tuesday's late $1.74725.
   Earlier in Tokyo, the dollar eased to 126.62 Japanese yen from
Tuesday's 127.15 yen. In London, the dollar traded at 126.65 yen and
later in New York the dollar finished at 126.525 yen, down from
127.15 yen late Tuesday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with Tuesday's late
rates, included: 1.5658 Swiss Francs, down from 1.5690; 1.1999
Canadian dollars, up from 1.19225; 6.2560 French francs, down from
6.2795; and 1,349.75 Italian lire, down from 1,351.00.
   Other rates for the dollar in Europe late Wednesday, compared
with Tuesday's late rates, included: 1.8380 West German marks, down
from 1.8420; 1.5667 Swiss francs, down from 1.5685; 6.2625 French
francs, down from 6.2735; 2.0725 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0910;
1,350.50 Italian lire, down from 1,356.00; and 1.1965 Canadian
dollars, up from 1.1897.
   Gold prices benefit when price pressures build because investors
typically use precious metals as a hedge against inflation. Renewed
demand for bullion this week also has bolstered gold prices.
   The late bid for gold in London was $386.30 a troy ounce, up from
Tuesday's $380.75. Zurich's late bid was $386.25 an ounce, up from
$383.00.
   Earlier in Hong Kong, gold closed at a bid of $387.51, up from
$384.34.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery rose to $386.90 a troy ounce, up $1 from Tuesday's
settlement price.
   Silver bullion traded late in London at $5.97 a troy ounce, up
from $5.93. On New York's Comex, silver bullion for current delivery
settled at $5.935 a troy ounce, up from Tuesday's $5.926.
</TEXT>
