<FIRST>u f AM-CommoditiesRdp     02-22 0650</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodities Rdp,0668</SECOND>
<HEAD>Copper Surges Again On Reported Shipping Delays</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Copper futures prices rose sharply for the second straight day
Wednesday on reports that shipments from Zambia and Zaire would be
delayed by rail problems.
   On other markets, precious metals and energy futures advanced;
grains and soybeans were mostly higher; and livestock and meat
futures were mixed.
   Copper settled 2.3 cents to 5 cents higher on New York's
Commodity Exchange with the contract for delivery in March at $1.385
a pound. The two-day gain of 12.3 cents in the March contract
represents a 9.7 percent increase in the contract's value.
   Tuesday's strong advance was fueled by reports that flooding had
disrupted copper production at a mine in Zambia, the world's
fourth-largest copper producer, and by a reported decline in the
already tight supplies of copper registered with the London Metal
Exchange.
   Analysts said the gains may have primed the market for another
upward surge. Wednesday's news of shipping delays was not an
especially alarming development; transportation problems are fairly
routine in Zambia and especially in Zaire, the world's No. 7 copper
producer.
   James Steel, a metal market analyst with Refco Inc. in New York,
said the copper market had been technically oversold after a
two-month slide to Friday's low of $1.252 a pound for March
delivery. Copper futures prices peaked Dec. 8 on the Commodity
Exchange at $1.6475, a record high.
   Many speculators exited the copper market as prices fell, leaving
the market thin and susceptible to sharp price swings.
   ``No one trusts this market anymore,'' said Craig Sloane, an
analyst in New York with Smith Barney, Harris Upham &amp; Co. ``It's
very, very treacherous.''
   Gold and silver futures advanced modestly on the Commodity
Exchange in reaction to the inflationary implications of Wednesday's
higher oil prices and the government's report of a 0.6 percent
increase in consumer prices in January.
   Gold settled 80 cents to $1.20 higher with April at $390.20 a
troy ounce; silver was 0.9 cent to 2.1 cents higher with March at
$5.94 a troy ounce.
   Heating oil led the energy complex higher on the New York
Mercantile Exchange in reaction to the American Petroleum
Institute's report late Tuesday of a 4.1-million-barrel drop in U.S.
inventories of petroleum distillates.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil futures settled 21 cents to 29
cents higher with April at $17.84 a barrel; heating oil was .86 cent
to 1.26 cents higher with March at 50.15 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .55 cent to 1.18 cents higher with March at 49.07 cents
a gallon.
   Soybean futures moved sharply higher on the Chicago Board of
Trade in a surge attributed to technical factors in the absence of
significant supply-and-demand developments. Corn and wheat futures
also advanced while oat futures prices fell slightly.
   ``It was a very firm close overall,'' said Victor Lespinasse, a
trader with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in Chicago.
   Wheat futures were supported by signs of heightened export
demand, including talk that the Soviet Union had submitted a bid for
400,000 metric tons of U.S. wheat at subsidized prices.
   Wheat settled { cent to 2{ cents higher with March at $4.26\ a
bushel; corn was unchanged to 3{ cents higher with March at $2.73\ a
bushel; oats were unchanged to 2 cents lower with March at $2.13 a
bushel; soybeans were 4\ cents to 10 cents higher with March at
$7.56 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures finished mixed on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .25 cent lower to .07 cent higher with April at
77.70 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .33 cent lower to .05 cent
higher with March at 84.17 cents a pound; live hogs were .05 cent
lower to .25 cent higher with April at 42.97 cents a pound; frozen
pork bellies were .17 cent lower to .10 cent higher with March at
38.95 cents a pound.
</TEXT>
