<FIRST>r f AM-MiniScribe     02-22 0307</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-MiniScribe,0319</SECOND>
<HEAD>MiniScribe Chairman and CEO Resigns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONGMONT, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Q.T. Wiles stepped down Wednesday as
chairman and chief executive of MiniScribe Corp. as rumors of
financial troubles that were denied by the company caused heavy
trading in the stock.
   MiniScribe, a maker of personal computer hard disk drives, fell
50 cents a share to $4 a share in over-the-counter trading of more
than 4 million shares.
   Wiles, 69, resigned during a regular board meeting because ``his
family position does not now allow him to spend the time and energy
required to act as chief executive through another difficult period
in the industry,'' according to a company statement. His resignation
was effective immediately.
   Richard P. Rifenburgh, 57, Wiles' partner at Hambrecht &amp; Quist
Venture Partners, was elected by the board as the new chairman and
chief executive, at Wiles' suggestion.
   Spokeswoman Jeanne Boyd denied one rumor that a major supplier
had cut off supplies because of non-payment of bills. The company
conceded that it was late on some bills but had not been cut off.
``Everything is fine. There are no payment problems,'' she said.
   The 52-week high for the stock was $13.75 a share.
   MiniScribe reported a 1988 fourth-quarter loss last week of $14.6
million and said continuing losses were expected in the first half
of this year because of a slowdown in the market.
   Wiles commented Wednesday that after a growth in revenues from
$115 million in 1985 to $603 million in 1988, it was best to
stabilize the business and prepare for the next expansion period.
   Wiles' resignation comes amid rumors of more layoffs at the
company. MiniScribe laid off 240 Longmont workers in December, and
employees said they expect another round of layoffs when paychecks
are handed out Friday.
   Company officials earlier this week declined to comment on the
layoff rumor.
</TEXT>
