<FIRST>u f AM-AluminumPrices 1stLd-Writethru   02-22 0701</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Aluminum Prices, 1st Ld - Writethru,0720</SECOND>
<HEAD>Aluminum Prices Up, Cans Makers Resisting</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 6th graf, Alcoa last...to CLARIFY particular price hike
is for can body stock, CORRECT new price to about $1.22 a pound sted $1.23.
Picks up 7th graf, Aluminum producers...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARL BOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Aluminum producers have raised the price of
sheet used in beverage cans by 6 percent, but consumers may have to
swallow little of that even if can makers fail to stem the metal's
rise, industry officials said Wednesday.
   Can makers are likely to fight hard to reject the increases
announced Tuesday, first by Pittsburgh-based Aluminum Co. of America
and then by Reynolds Metals Co. of Richmond, Va., the nation's
second-largest producer behind Alcoa.
   ``We meet a lot of resistance'' to higher prices from bottlers,
said Frank Dalton, spokesman for Crown Cork &amp; Seal of Philadelphia.
``We'd like to give the aluminum companies a lot of resistance too.''
   If the increase sticks, ``it would hurt if we could not pass it
through,'' Dalton said.
   Alcoa blamed the price hike on higher prices for scrap and higher
labor costs.
   Alcoa last raised prices on can body stock to $1.15 per pound in
January 1988. It now cost will about $1.22 per pound.
   Aluminum producers held off raising prices last year because of
an increased threat from steel as a material for beverage containers.
   ``We're still mindful of the competition, but with higher metal
costs and higher labor costs we're forced to make the increase
now,'' Alcoa spokesman Al Posti said.
   A pound of aluminum sheet makes 25 cans, so the extra eight cents
per pound means each can would cost a third of a cent more and each
24-can case an extra 7.6 cents, said David Moison, analyst for
Resource Stratigies Inc.
   ``I would think that wholesalers, retailers and distributors
would completely miss 7 cents a case,'' Moison said.
   Industry analyst Paul Steinke of Wharton Econometrics Forecasting
Associates gives the can makers a good chance of turning back at
least part of the increase.
   ``Both Alcoa and Reynolds...posted record profits in 1988. Can
makers know that. Consumers know that, so I don't think people are
going to accept it at face value,'' he said. ``There may be some
increase but not the full 6 percent.''
   The price move could also be undermined by any economic slowdown,
which many economists expect later this year. Large additions to
sheet capacity by Alcoa and Aluminum Co. of Canada will further
undermine prices by boosting supply, Steinke said.
   ``I wouldn't be surprised if the increase was completely eroded
by the end of summer,'' he said. ``If what I'm saying is true, then
I think (consumers) will be pretty immune from it.''
   But aluminum producers been doing well, can makers are being
pinched by suppliers and customers.
   ``The bottlers have been just beating up on the can makers,''
said one can industry executive who spoke on condition he not be
named.
   ``There used to be a lot of smaller family-owned soft drink
franchises around the country. But Pepsi and Coke have bought up so
much of them that these monsters go into negotiations and beat up on
these guys,'' he said. ``Push will come to shove and they'll not
sell cans at a loss.''
   J. Clarence Morrison, a metals analyst for Dean Witter Reynolds,
said tight supplies made the aluminum price hike a foregone
conclusion.
   ``Can stock is fully sold out for 1989 and probably for the first
part of 1990.... Although the price is being raised to $1.23 here,
Japan has been paying as much as $1.50 per pound and cannot meet its
demand,'' he said.
   The contract price for alumina, an intermediate form between
bauxite and aluminum, has doubled from $150 per ton last year to
$300 per ton and the spot market price of alumina has reached $800
at times, Morrison said.
   The price of used aluminum cans, which account for half of the
metal Alcoa uses, has been at record levels of 71 cents to 74 cents
per pound.
   Alcoa on Wednesday raised the price it pays for used cans from 73
cents to 76 cents a pound, Posti said.
</TEXT>
