<FIRST>u f AM-Amex-College     02-22 0436</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Amex-College,0453</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Express Steps Up Marketing to College Students</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Express Co. is beefing up its marketing
efforts on campus, offering travel bargains and launching a magazine
for college students who carry the American Express Card, the
company said Wednesday.
   Researchers say there are about 7 million fulltime college
students in the United States spending an estimated $44 billion a
year.
   Students also have the potential for substantial earnings growth
once they are graduated and financial service companies are finding
that it can often pay off to establish a relationship while they are
still in college.
   The market research company CollegeTrak said 51 percent of
college students already have one of the major credit or charge
cards.
   Citibank, the nation's largest banking company which has also
courted the college crowd, counts 1.3 million college students as
holders of either its Visa or Mastercard credit cards.
   American Express said the number of college students holding its
payments card has doubled to more than 500,000 in the past two
years, partly because of relaxed eligibility requirements.
   Fulltime college students can get an American Express Card
without meeting any minimum income requirement and without a parent
as co-signer, provided they do not have a bad credit record. The
annual fee is $55, the same as for regular cardholders, and payment
in full is due every month.
   Despite the relaxed eligibility requirements, people who got the
American Express in college ``were just as responsible about
credit'' as other new cardholders, according to Ken Chenault,
general manager of American Express' personal card division.
   Ed Skonicki, a Citibank executive, said his bank has had the same
experience. ``They take responsibility a lot more seriously than you
would expect,'' he said.
   Under the new American Express program, cardholders who are
fulltime students at a four-year college will get two vouchers for
round trips at $99 each between any two domestic destinations served
by Northwest Airlines in the 48 contiguous states.
   In addition, they will get vouchers for reduced rates on
Northwest to specific destinations and bonus mileage toward
Northwest's free travel program.
   Tickets must be purchased with an American Express Card issued to
the student named on the voucher.
   American Express also plans to publish a quarterly lifestyle
magazine, American Express Connections, that will be sent to its
college student cardholders. The magazine will offer tips on travel
and money management, stories about campus theater and the
professions and mail-order clothing, electronics, entertainment and
travel.
   American Express officials declined to specify how much it was
spending on the program, but said it was a multimillion dollar
effort.
</TEXT>
