<FIRST>u f AM-Drexel-Casinos     02-22 0484</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drexel-Casinos,0503</SECOND>
<HEAD>Casino Commission Temporarily Bans Drexel From Atlantic City Business</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM KRATTENMAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAWRENCE TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. was
banned Wednesday from New Jersey's lucrative gaming industry because
of criminal charges against the investment firm in a major Wall
Street scandal.
   ``If a corporation does not have the integrity, it should not be
a part of this industry,'' Casino Commissioner W. David Waters said.
   The state Casino Control Commission voted 4-0 to order Drexel to
rescind its current business with three casino holding companies and
refrain from new business.
   The temporary ban applies at least until resolution of the
criminal case and Drexel's application for a state license to do
business in Atlantic City.
   The New York investment firm has agreed to plead guilty to six
felonies and pay a record $650 million to settle charges including
insider trading and other securities fraud violations following a
two-year federal investigation.
   Drexel attorney Clive Cummis asked the commission to delay action
until the securities case settlement is approved by the Securities
and Exchange Commission. He said the case would be resolved in a
month.
   State gaming enforcement officials asked the commission Jan. 31
to impose the temporary ban on Drexel, whose expertise in high-yield
bond financing helped build the Atlantic City casino industry in the
last decade.
   Drexel said it has raised about $2.8 billion in capital for New
Jersey casinos, about 70 percent of the public funds for the
gambling houses. In the process, the company has earned more than
$120 million in fees, according to state regulators.
   Drexel was hired by Griffin Resorts Inc., last November to help
former entertainer Merv Griffin acquire Resorts International Casino
Hotel. In addition, it has been doing business with holding
companies for Del Webb's Claridge Casino Hotel and the Sands Hotel &amp;
Casino.
   Cummis said Drexel officials would meet with the gaming
enforcement division to determine how it would sever ties with the
casinos.
   Industry analysts say Drexel's ouster would leave a void in
Atlantic City because no other investment companies have financed as
many bonds for casinos as Drexel.
   But Commission Chairman Walter Read said: ``It may be a leader,
but I don't think it's the only one.''
   Cummis contended that Drexel should be allowed to continue in
Atlantic City because it had demonstrated a commitment to firing
employees involved in the fraud scandals.
   But Eugene Schwartz, deputy director of the Gaming Enforcement
Division, told the commissioners that promises of a house-cleaning
were not enough to assure the public that Drexel should do business
in the tightly regulated casino industry.
   Because of the sheer volume of its casino trade, Drexel in 1987
was asked to become the first investment company to apply for a
state gaming license.
   Drexel agreed despite complaints that gaming oversight would
amount to overkill because the firm already was tightly regulated by
the SEC.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
