<DOCNO> AP890222-0282 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-89 1928EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Lotus     02-22 0320</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lotus,0333</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lotus Begins Field Testing Of New Spreadsheet</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lotus Development Corp. said Wednesday it
has begun field testing the long-delayed new version of its
signature spreadsheet computer program, Lotus 1-2-3.
   An initial group of about 70 customers nationwide will receive
the new version, known as Release 3, during the next two weeks, the
company said.
   Lotus 1-2-3 has been the industry's best-selling spreadsheet
program, used by thousands of large and small businesses for
accounting, since it was introduced in 1983.
   But competitors have been gaining because of Lotus' repeated
delays in introducing the new version, which was originally
scheduled for shipment early last year and is now due out in the
spring.
   Lotus spokeswoman Susan Earabino called the start of ``beta'' or
field testing ``a milestone in the development process'' that puts
Release 3 on schedule for second-quarter shipment.
   Frank King, senior vice president of Lotus' software products
group, said testers will receive hands-on product training and
participate in feedback sessions with Lotus development, marketing
and sales teams.
   More than 5,000 individual testers at several hundred sites
eventually will try out the new spreadsheet, designed for both DOS
and OS-2 computer operating systems, King said.
   Getting Release 3 out by the latest self-imposed deadline is
widely perceived in the industry as a critical proposition for
Lotus, which is dependent on the spreadsheet for an estimated 60
percent of its sales.
   According to International Data Corp., Lotus had 51.2 percent of
the worldwide market for spreadsheets in the first six months of
1988. Microsoft Corp. was second with a 20 percent combined share
for its Multiplan and Excel spreadsheets.
   In an effort to take advantage of Lotus' delays, Microsoft Corp.
has slashed prices on Excel. Some aggressive retailers are selling
it for as little as $209, or $286 below the suggested price.
   Other competitors include Quattro from Borland International
Inc., which functions exactly like 1-2-3.
</TEXT>
