<FIRST>r f AM-Station-Revoked 1stLd-Writethru f0234 02-22 0673</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Station-Revoked, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0234,0689</SECOND>
<HEAD>FCC Yanks Radio Station License, Citing Owner's Unfitness</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 5th graf, bgng: This was xxx to include
detail on deadlines; SUBS 9th graf, bgng: The FCC xxx to clarify nature
of charge of lying. Also moved on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Communications Commission voted
Wednesday to to pull the license of a tiny New York radio station
saying the owner lied, ran a contest where the prize was awarded to
the station and racially discriminated against a job applicant.
   ``He has 90 days to go off the air or 30 days to appeal'' to the
U.S Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit, FCC
spokeswoman Rosemary Kimball.
   The commissioners voted 3-0 in a closed session not to renew the
license of Catoctin Broadcasting Corp., which runs WBUZ-AM, a
250-watt station in Fredonia, about 35 miles southwest of Buffalo,
N.Y. The station is owned by Henry Serafin.
   Among the charges against Serafin was that he discriminated
against a black job applicant in 1980, calling her employment agency
and demanding, ``Don't you have any white girls to send me?'' and
adding that the woman ``would make charcoal look white.''
   This was the first time since 1981 that the FCC pulled a
station's license on character grounds, Kimball said. Only about 100
stations have lost their licenses at renewal since the FCC was
founded in 1934.
   FCC lawyer Richard Bozzelli said the clock doesn't start on the
deadlines imposed on Serafin until the order is officially issued,
which could take two to four weeks.
   Serafin, in a telephone interview from the station, said he would
appeal.
   ``They won't let me sell,'' he said. ``If you have no license,
you're out of business, you have nothing to sell.''
   ``Although we do not lightly decide to deny renewal of a license,
we will nevertheless reach such a determination where the record
demonstrates that renewal would not serve the public interest,'' the
FCC said in announcing its decision. ``An analysis of the record
here leads us to conclude that this is such a case.''
   The FCC also found that Serafin had lied to the commission about
the discrimination allegation and about the station's public
inspection file.
   Finally, the commissioners agreed that Catoctin violated FCC
rules by conducting a contest and failing to award the grand prize
of a stereo, instead keeping it for use at the station.
   On Wednsday, Serafin denied all the charges and said the FCC
picked on him ``being small, being poor.'' He has also maintained
that he was the victim of a campaign by the National Association for
the Advancement of Colored people, the Chautauqua County Rural
Ministries Inc. and a staff member of the local Comprehensive
Employment Training Act office, who ``had an ax to grind.'' The
black job applicant Serafin turned away had been sent to the station
by CETA.
   Andrew Jay Schwartzman, a lawyer for the Media Access Project,
which represented groups challenging WBUZ's license, said the FCC
only decided to act in the face of repeated threats to get a court
order to force final action.
   ``They've stalled all the way, even after their own hearing
officer affirmed our charges of blatant racism nearly three years
ago,'' he said. ``It's about time that the FCC started enforcing the
law.''
   The case was originally filed in 1980 but it wasn't until 1986
that an administrative law judge denied the station's application
for license renewal. The judge, Walter C. Miller, found that Serafin
was ``dishonest, untrustworthy and unreliable'' and that he had
``violated a wide variety of commission rules.''
   Serafin appealed the ruling and the case went to an FCC review
board. In 1987, the board concurred with Miller and recommended
``outright denial of renewal of a license ... Serafin is not the
type of person that should be entitled to a public franchise.''
   The station continued to function under a temporary license as
Serafin appealed to the full commission.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
