<FILEID>AP-NR-02-22-89 1949EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-HeadStart 1stLd-Writethru f0157 02-22 0463</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Head Start, 1st Ld - Writethru, f0157,0471</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with four grafs to CORRECT by deleting incorrect $3.25
billion figure and references to `Head Start'. Also moved on general news
wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Business leaders, warning of a critical
shortage of skilled laborers in the next century, on Wednesday
embraced plans by Sen. Edward M. Kennedy to create a
multibillion-dollar education program for pre-kindergarten children.
   ``Investing in our children is not just rhetoric. It's sound
business practice, although many of our colleagues have yet to make
that discovery,'' said Arnold Hiatt, chief executive officer of
Stride Rite in Cambridge, Mass.
   Top executives from Stride Rite, General Electric Co., Time Inc.,
and Goodyear Tire and Rubber told the Senate Labor and Human
Resources Committee, which Kennedy chairs, that fast-advancing
technologies require workers with strong educational backgrounds who
can learn new skills quickly.
   Kennedy's ``Smart Start'' program would have the federal
government finance much of the effort through grants to state and
local governments, which would decide whether to have the programs
operated through schools or community organizations.
   State and parental participation would be voluntary.
   Kennedy, a Massachusetts Democrat, said programs for children in
the year before they attend kindergarten have shown that
participants are twice as likely to be literate, twice as likely to
have a job, one-third less likely to drop out of high school and
half as likely to be on welfare.
   One executive who testified Wednesday, Goodyear Chairman Robert
Mercer, told Kennedy's committee that, ``in our tire plants, you
can't have a guy who can't read or write running a million-dollar
tire machine. Today's tire manufacturing is a highly sophisticated,
computer-controlled process.''
   Frank Doyle, senior vice president at General Electric, said his
company is already having difficulty ``finding job applicants at all
levels who meet our requirement of either being ready to work or
ready to train. ... There is little we at GE can do ... with
employees who cannot read, write or count and who are either
unwilling or unable to learn.''
   Kennedy's proposal would have the federal government cover 70
percent of the program's costs in the first year, 60 percent in the
second and 50 percent in each of the next three years. State and
local governments would pay the balance of the costs.
   The legislation proposes a $500 million federal expenditure next
year, $750 million in 1991 and $1 billion in each of the following
three years.
   All children whose family income is less than 15 percent above
the federal poverty line could attend the programs without charge.
Parents of other children would pay on a sliding scale, based on
family income, up to the full cost.
   Half of all slots would be reserved for poor children.
</TEXT>
