<HEAD>B. Dalton's To Return `Satanic Verses' to Shelves</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to DELETE name of B. Dalton spokesman in grafs
2, 5 and 6 at his request.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The B. Dalton and Barnes &amp; Noble bookstore
chains, which pulled ``The Satanic Verses'' from their shelves
Friday, reversed themselves Wednesday and said they will restock the
novel.
   ``At the urging of an overwhelming majority of its store managers
and employees ... and in light of the statement yesterday by the
President of the United States, B. Dalton company will resume sales
of `The Satanic Verses,''' said a B. Dalton spokesman who asked not
to be identified.
   He said the decision applied to the Barnes &amp; Noble subsidiary as
well.
   The two chains have about 1,250 bookstores across the country.
   The spokeman estimated the book's publisher, Viking Press, should
have additional copies of Salman Rushdie's novel to B. Dalton within
10 days.
   ``As has been the company's practice throughout its history, it
makes no recommendations as to the worthiness or lack thereof of any
of the books found on its shelves,'' the spokesman said. ``The
company continues to believe that bookstore employees are not
capable of, nor should they be required to, bear the burden of
resolving conflicts contained on the pages of the books they sell.''
   Paul Slovak, a spokesman for Viking Press, said the publisher had
no immediate comment on the bookstores' reversal.
   In comments Wednesday, President Bush said he found the Ayatollah
Khomeini's death threat against Rushdie ``deeply offensive to the
norms of civilized behavior.''
