<FIRST>r f AM-RockwellFine 1stLd-Writethru f0177 02-22 0392</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rockwell Fine, 1st Ld - Writethru, f0177,0402</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Seeks $5 Million Fine For Defense Fraud</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with Rockwell comment, additional details
of government's allegations. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prosecutors asked a judge to fine Rockwell
International Corp. $5 million for overbilling the Air Force on a
sophisticated satellite navigation system.
   Prosecutors said in a sentencing memorandum filed Tuesday in U.S.
District Court that the fine is necessary ``to punish Rockwell
adequately for its egregious contemptuous conduct.''
   Assistant U.S. Attorney George Newhouse Jr. called the request
``conservative,'' citing the company's $812 million profit for 1988
and a projected $176 million profit on its NAVSTAR satellite
production contract alone.
   ``The only rational conclusion that can be drawn from the
evidence is that corporate officials at Rockwell knew about the
deception, knew that the auditors were being told lies and approved,
if not directed, that course of action,'' the government said in the
sentencing memo.
   Rockwell on Wednesday rejected the government's contention.
   ``The prosecutor's assertion that higher company officials
`encouraged and countenanced' deceiving the government is absolutely
false,'' Charles Harff, Rockwell's senior vice president and general
counsel, said in a statement.
   Top managers weren't charged in the criminal case, and Rockwell
blames the double-billing on renegade employees who have been fired
and prosecuted separately. The employees aren't accused of profiting
personally.
   Rockwell entered a conditional guilty plea in the case Jan. 19,
which means that if the company succeeds in an appeal of an early
ruling in the case the plea will be stricken from the record.
   In that ruling, Rockwell failed to persuade a judge to dismiss
the charges against it on the grounds it had reported the
double-billing under a Pentagon voluntary disclosure program.
   Rockwell was charged with conspiracy and contempt in an
indictment that alleges the company and two employees overbilled the
Air Force $446,000 for the manufacture of NAVSTAR Global Positioning
System satellites.
   The satellites transmit radio signals that are received by ships
and planes, enabling them to pinpoint their exact location on Earth.
   The overbilling occurred between October 1982 and March 1986, the
government said.
   In addition to the fine, prosecutors asked that Rockwell be
ordered to repay the $446,000 that was overbilled and take steps to
ensure that its employees know the rules of government contracts.
Sentencing was scheduled for Friday.
</TEXT>
