<SECOND>AM-Beretta Vs. Beretta, 1st Ld - Writethru, f0326,0440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with a GM spokesman denying that
settlement has been reached, another confirming settlement; picks up 7th
graf pvs, `The gunmaker ...'.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp. will contribute $500,000 to
cancer research as part of a settlement announced Wednesday by an
Italian gunmaker in a trademark infringement case against GM's
Beretta model.
   The automaker also will pay unspecified legal and administrative
fees associated with the lawsuit filed by Fabbrica d'Armi Pietro
Beretta S.p.A., Beretta said in a statement.
   A GM spokesman, however, denied that a settlement had been
reached.
   The 500-year-old Italian company, which has registered trademarks
in this country for the Beretta name starting in 1954, sued GM in
federal court in New York last July, seeking $250 million in damages.
   The settlement calls for GM to donate $500,000 to the Beretta
Foundation for Cancer Research, Berett a spokesman Ralph Cole said
in a statement.
   Under the agreement, GM will be permitted to continue to use the
Beretta name for its Chevrolet car line. The automaker also must
acknowledge in its sale catalogs and Beretta owner's manuals that
the name is being used with the permission of the Italian company,
the Beretta statement said.
   ``We believe that this settlement provides an adequate,
conciliatory resolution to both parties of the litigation,'' Beretta
President Pier Giuseppe Beretta said in the statement.
   Ralph Kramer, a Chevrolet spokesman, said the automaker was
pleased with the settlement but still contends the lawsuit was
unnecessary.
   ``It's been our position and continues to be that no one who
would come into a showroom to look at a Beretta would be confused
that the firearms company would have something to do with the car,''
Kramer said. ``But we're glad that it's over and it's behind us
now.''
   But GM spokesman David Hudgens said later Wednesday that
``Beretta's announcement of a settlement is premature.''
   ``We have not signed a settlement agreement with them,'' he said.
``We are hopeful the matter will be resolved in the best interests
of both parties in the near future.''
   The gunmaker went after GM when the automaker unveiled the
Chevrolet Beretta in 1987 despite warning letters from Beretta
lawyers the previous year.
   The conflict between the two companies and the Beretta name was
parodied last month by Car and Driver magazine, which did a ``road
test'' comparing the GM sports car with the handgun whose name it
shared.
   The Italian company makes luggage, clothing, cutlery and optical
equipment as well as target, hunting and military guns.
